{"title_page": "Shawn Mendes", "text_new": "{{About|the singer|his self-titled album|Shawn Mendes (album){{!}}''Shawn Mendes'' (album)}}\n{{short description|Canadian singer, songwriter, and model}}\n{{pp-vand|small=yes}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Shawn Mendes\n| image              = Shawn Mendes Glamour May 2018.png\n| caption            = Mendes in May 2018\n| birth_name         = Shawn Peter Raul Mendes\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1998|8|8}}\n| birth_place        = [[Pickering, Ontario]], Canada\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Singer\n* songwriter\n* record producer\n}}\n| years_active       = 2013\u2013present\n| home_town          =\n| agent              = [[Wilhelmina Models]]\n| partner            = <!--This parameter is for LONG-TERM unmarried life partners\u2014not girlfriends or flings-->\n| awards             = [[List of awards and nominations received by Shawn Mendes|Full list]]\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes<!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| background = solo_singer <!-- mandatory field -->\n| instrument      = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* guitar\n* piano\n}}\n| genre               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Pop music|Pop]]\n* [[folk-pop]]\n* [[pop rock]]\n}}<!--Only list genres that are prominent/recurring in his career. -->\n| label           = {{flatlist|\n* [[Island Records|Island]]\n* [[Republic Records|Republic]]<ref>{{cite magazine| last1=Rubin|first1=Rebecca|last2=Halperin|first2=Shirley|url=https://variety.com/2017/music/news/shawn-mendes-theres-nothing-holdin-me-back-no-1-charts-1202528804/|title=Shawn Mendes' 'There's Nothing Holdin' Me Back' Hits No. 1 on Top 40|date=15 August 2017|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=31 March 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Universal Music Canada]] <ref> https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7767524/universal-music-canada-relocating-rock-star-building-toronto</ref>\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[Teddy Geiger]]\n* [[Camila Cabello]]\n}}<!-- Please DO NOT ADD associated acts unless they have collaborated with Mendes on at least 2 songs. -->\n| website         = {{URL|shawnmendesofficial.com}}}}\n}}\n\n'''Shawn Peter Raul Mendes''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|m|\u025b|n|d|\u025b|z}}; born August 8, 1998) is a Canadian singer and songwriter. He gained a following in 2013, posting song covers on the video-sharing application [[Vine (software)|Vine]]. The following year, he caught the attention of artist manager [[Andrew Gertler]] and [[Island Records]] [[Artists and repertoire|A&R]] Ziggy Chareton, which led to him signing a deal with the record label. He has since released [[Shawn Mendes discography|three studio albums]], headlined [[Shawn Mendes#Tours|three world tours]], and received [[List of awards and nominations received by Shawn Mendes|several awards]].\n\nMendes released his [[The Shawn Mendes EP|self-titled debut EP]] (2014) and his debut studio album ''[[Handwritten (Shawn Mendes album)|Handwritten]]'' (2015), whose single \"[[Stitches (Shawn Mendes song)|Stitches]]\" reached number one in the United Kingdom and the top 10 in the United States and Canada. He then released his second studio album ''[[Illuminate (Shawn Mendes album)|Illuminate]]'' (2016), whose singles \"[[Treat You Better]]\" and \"[[There's Nothing Holdin' Me Back]]\" reached the top 10 in several countries. His [[Shawn Mendes (album)|self-titled third studio album]] (2018) was supported by the lead single \"[[In My Blood (Shawn Mendes song)|In My Blood]]\". All three albums debuted atop the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], with the first one making Mendes one of five artists ever to debut at number one before the age of 18 and the third one making him the third-youngest artist to achieve three number one albums. In 2017, Mendes became the first artist to land three number-one singles on the ''Billboard'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]] chart before turning 20 years old. In 2018, he became the first artist to achieve four number-one singles on the [[Adult Top 40|Adult Pop Songs]] chart before the age of 20 as well. In 2019, he released the hit singles \"[[If I Can't Have You (Shawn Mendes song)|If I Can't Have You]]\" and \"[[Se\u00f1orita (Shawn Mendes and Camila Cabello song)|Se\u00f1orita]]\", with the latter peaking at number one on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].\n\nAmong his accolades, Mendes has won 13 [[Society of Composers, Authors and Music Publishers of Canada|SOCAN]] awards, 10 [[MTV Europe Music Award]]s, eight [[Juno Award]]s, eight [[iHeartRadio MMVAs]], two [[American Music Awards]], and received three [[Grammy Award]] nominations. In 2018, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' named Mendes as one of the 100 most influential people in the world on their [[Time 100|annual list]].\n\n== Early life ==\nMendes was born in the city of [[Pickering, Ontario]], to Karen ([[n\u00e9e]] Rayment), a real estate agent, and Manuel Mendes, a businessman, who sells bar and restaurant supplies in Toronto. His father is Portuguese (from the [[Algarve]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noticiasmagazine.pt/2015/shawn-mendes-o-rapaz-do-momento/|title=Shawn Mendes: o rapaz do momento|date=October 23, 2015|work=noticiasmagazine.pt|accessdate=February 2, 2016}}</ref> while his mother is from England. He has a younger sister named Aaliyah.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/music/a28137090/shawn-mendes-sister-aaliyah/|title=Who Is Shawn Mendes's Sister Aaliyah Mendes and Is She Famous?|date=June 21, 2019|work=Seventeen|accessdate=July 24, 2019}}</ref> He was raised in a religious family.<ref>{{cite magazine| last1=Marine|first1=Brooke|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/shawn-mendes-met-gala-2018|title=Shawn Mendes Opens Up Before His First Met Gala About His Friend Hailey Baldwin, Being a Romantic at Heart, and His New Music|date=8 May 2018|magazine=[[W Magazine]]|accessdate=6 November 2018|quote=\"Forever, religion is going to have a massive impact on people's fashion. It always has been and always will be,\" Mendes\u2014who later revealed he did come from a religious upbringing\u2014told W when asked how he planned to incorporate the theme into his look for the evening.}}</ref>\n\nMendes was raised in Pickering where he attended [[Pine Ridge Secondary School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/11340960/Shawn-Mendes-How-a-six-second-video-launched-the-next-Justin-Bieber.html|title=Shawn Mendes: How a six-second video launched the next Justin Bieber|date=January 16, 2015|work=Telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=January 27, 2015}}</ref> At school, he played ice hockey and soccer, joined his high school [[glee club]], and practised his stage presence in acting lessons (leading as [[Prince Charming]] at one point). He also auditioned for [[Disney Channel]] in Toronto.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.iheartradio.com.au/entertainment/entertainment-news/shawn-mendes-was-nearly-a-disney-kid |title=Shawn Mendes Was Nearly A Disney Kid |date=July 10, 2017 |accessdate=November 9, 2018 |work=iHeartRadio |location=Canada}}</ref> Mendes graduated from high school in June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/shawn-mendes-finally-graduated-high-school|title=Shawn Mendes Finally Graduated High School Yesterday|date=June 29, 2016|work=Teen Vogue|accessdate=October 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n=== 2013\u20142015: ''Handwritten'' ===\n{{Main|Handwritten (Shawn Mendes album)}}\n[[File:Shawn Mendes VOA.png|left|200px|thumb|Mendes at the [[Jingle Ball Tour 2014]]]]\nMendes learned to play guitar by watching [[YouTube]] tutorial videos at the age of 14 in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.axs.com/shawn-mendes-5-things-you-didn-t-know-50268 |title=Shawn Mendes: 5 things you didn't know |date=April 23, 2015 |work=AXS |accessdate=February 12, 2017}}</ref> Less than a year later he started posting [[cover version|cover videos]] on YouTube. Mendes started attracting viewers after he posted a cover from [[Justin Bieber]] \"[[As Long as You Love Me (Justin Bieber song)|As Long as You Love Me]]\" on the social video app [[Vine (service)|Vine]] in 2013 and got 10,000 likes and as many followers the next day. After that he gained millions of views and followers in a few months, becoming well known for his six-second snippets of renditions of many popular songs.<ref>{{cite web |title=Getting Honest With Shawn Mendes |url=http://honestblue.com/getting-honest-with-shawn-mendes/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140605021933/http://honestblue.com/getting-honest-with-shawn-mendes/ |archive-date=June 5, 2014 |work=Honest Blue |url-status=dead |accessdate=April 30, 2018}}</ref> By August 2014, he was the third most-followed musician on Vine.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shawn Mendes: 5 Things You Need To Know About The Vine Star Turned Chart-Topping Singer (PHOTOS) |url=http://www.hngn.com/articles/142503/20151021/shawn-mendes-5-things-you-need-to-know-about-the-vine-star-turned-chart-topping-singer-photos.htm |website=Headlines & Global News |date=October 21, 2015 |accessdate=2015-11-14}}</ref> Artist manager Andrew Gertler discovered Mendes online in November 2013, bringing him to [[Island Records]] in January 2014. In April, he won [[Ryan Seacrest]]'s \"Best Cover Song\" contest with \"[[Say Something (A Great Big World song)|Say Something]]\" by [[A Great Big World]]. He officially signed to Island in May 2014.\n\nHe released his first single \"[[Life of the Party (Shawn Mendes song)|Life of the Party]]\" on June 26, 2014.<ref name=Billboard>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6165603/shawn-mendes-vine-magazine-story |title=How Shawn Mendes Is Turning Vine Fame into A Music Career |magazine=Billboard |date=July 18, 2014 |accessdate=July 18, 2014}}</ref> He became the youngest to debut in the top 25 on the US [[The Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], making it to number 24 for the week ending July 12, 2014.<ref name=Idolator1>{{cite web |url=http://www.idolator.com/7525178/shawn-mendes-vine-celebrity-life-of-the-party-billboard-debut-record-charts/ |title=Shawn Mendes, 15-Year-Old Vine Celebrity, Makes Record-Breaking Debut on Billboard Hot 100 |publisher=Idolator |date=July 2, 2014 |accessdate=July 13, 2014}}</ref> Prior to his signing, Mendes toured as a member of the [[Magcon]] Tour<ref>{{cite web |title=Girls go gaga for Vine video boys at Itasca meet and greet DailyHerald.com |url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20140301/news/140309846/ |date=March 3, 2014 |work=Daily Herald}}</ref> alongside other young Viners with a large following on social media.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2014-02-21/news/ct-vine-app-met-20140221_1_instagram-app-teen |title= Viners' meet and greet fosters teen idol frenzy Boys encounter stardom as popular producers of Twitter app's 6-second videos |date=February 21, 2014 |first=Ted |last=Gregory}}</ref> Mendes was also on a nationwide tour with [[Austin Mahone]] as an opening act. He released his debut major label EP in July.<ref>{{cite web|title='Secret' is out: Austin Mahone announces album, tour |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2014/04/04/the-secret-is-out-austin-mahone-announces-album-tour/7293633/ |work=USA Today |date=April 4, 2014}}</ref> The EP debuted and peaked at number five on [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], selling 48,000 copies in its first week.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6531900/shawn-mendes-handwritten-number-one-album|work=Billboard |title=Shawn Mendes Album on Course for No. 1 Debut on Billboard 200 Chart |first=Keith |last=Caulfield |date=April 15, 2015 |accessdate=October 2, 2015}}</ref> He won a [[Teen Choice]] award in 2014 for Webstar in Music.<ref>{{cite web |title=Vine Superstar Shawn Mendes Signed to Island Records (Exclusive) |first=Harley |last=Brown |date=June 4, 2014 |url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/legal-and-management/6106433/vine-superstar-shawn-mendes-signed-to-island-records |work=Billboard}}</ref> On September 5, 2014, \"[[Oh Cecilia (Breaking My Heart)]]\" featuring Mendes was released as the fifth single from [[The Vamps (British band)|The Vamps]]' debut album, ''[[Meet the Vamps]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://popcrush.com/the-vamps-oh-cecilia-shawn-mendes/ |title=The Vamps Release Remix of 'Oh Cecilia (Breaking My Heart)' Feat. Shawn Mendes [LISTEN] |publisher=popcrush.com}}</ref> On November 6, 2014, \"[[Something Big (song)|Something Big]]\" was released as the second single.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1990288/shawn-mendes-something-big-released/ |title=Shawn Mendes' New Single 'Something Big' Is Actually Something Huge |publisher=MTV.com}}</ref>\n\nOn April 14, 2015, Mendes released his full-length album ''[[Handwritten (Shawn Mendes album)|Handwritten]]'', which debuted at number one on the ''Billboard'' 200 chart with 119,000 [[Top Album Sales|equivalent album units]], selling 106,000 copies in its first week and was certified platinum.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6538916/shawn-mendes-handwritten-debut-no-1-billboard-200-chart|work=Billboard|title=Shawn Mendes' 'Handwritten' Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Chart|first=Keith|last=Caulfield|date=April 22, 2015|accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"RIAA\">{{cite web|title=You searched for shawn mendes&nbsp;\u2014 RIAA|url=https://www.riaa.com/?s=shawn+mendes|website=RIAA|accessdate=22 August 2017}}</ref> Mendes then became the youngest artist to debut at number one since the release of [[Justin Bieber]]'s [[My World 2.0]].<ref name=\"idolator\">{{cite web|last1=Daw|first1=Robbie|title=Shawn Mendes Becomes Youngest Artist To Top Album Chart In Half A Decade&nbsp;\u2014 idolator|url=http://www.idolator.com/7589967/shawn-mendes-youngest-artist-album-chart-handwritten|website=idolator|accessdate=22 August 2017|date=22 April 2015}}</ref> The third single from the album, \"[[Stitches (Shawn Mendes song)|Stitches]]\", peaked at number four on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100, becoming his first top 10 single in the US,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6738614/weeknd-tops-hot-100-adele-no-1-next-week|work=Billboard|title=The Weeknd Tops Hot 100; Adele No. 1 Next Week?|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=October 26, 2015|accessdate=October 26, 2015}}</ref> and became his first number one on the Adult Pop Songs<ref name=popsongs>{{Cite web| url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8467895/shawn-mendes-first-artist-to-have-four-no-1s-adult-pop-songs | title=Shawn Mendes Is the First Artist to Land Four No. 1s on the Adult Pop Songs Chart Before Age 20 | work=Billboard | date=November 15, 2015 | accessdate=23 September 2018| author=Trust, Gary}}</ref> and Adult Contemporary charts.<ref name=adultcontemporary>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8023330/shawn-mendes-ac-chart-three-number-ones-before-age-20|title=Shawn Mendes Is First Artist in AC Chart's History to Notch Three No. 1s Before Age 20|work=Billboard|last=Trust|first=Gary|accessdate= 23 September 2018}}</ref> The song later reached number one in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/shawn-mendes-stitches-knocks-justin-bieber-from-singles-number-1__13615/|title=It's not a stitch-up! Shawn Mendes knocks Bieber off Number 1|last=Copsey|first=Rob|date=January 22, 2016|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=January 24, 2016}}</ref> Also in 2015, Mendes opened for [[Taylor Swift]] during [[1989 World Tour]] dates for North America and recorded \"[[Believe (Shawn Mendes song)|Believe]]\" for the soundtrack of [[Disney Channel Original Movie]] ''[[Descendants (2015 film)|Descendants]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/music/news/a31593/disneys-descendants-will-feature-a-brand-new-song-from-shawn-mendes/|work=Seventeen|title=Shawn Mendes Wrote a New Song for Disney's \"Descendants\" Soundtrack!|first=Hayley|last=Glatter|date=June 12, 2015|accessdate=November 5, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news| url=http://headlineplanet.com/home/2014/11/03/vance-joy-shawn-mendes-join-taylor-swifts-1989-tour-dates-revealed/ | work= Headline Planet | title=Vance Joy, Shawn Mendes tapped to support Taylor Swift on her \"1989\" tour | date=November 3, 2014}}</ref> In late 2015, Mendes and [[Camila Cabello]], who was at the time a member of the group [[Fifth Harmony]], released their collaborative single \"[[I Know What You Did Last Summer (song)|I Know What You Did Last Summer]]\". The song was included on Mendes' ''Handwritten Revisited'' reissue.<ref>{{cite web|title = Shawn Mendes & Camila Cabello Announce 'I Know What You Did Last Summer' Duet: Hear a Preview|url = https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6760707/shawn-mendes-camila-cabello-i-know-what-you-did-last-summer-song|website = Billboard|accessdate = 2015-11-14}}</ref>\n\nMendes was listed among ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'}}s \"25 Most Influential Teens of 2014\", debuting in the list after being the youngest-ever artist to debut in the top 25 of ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://time.com/3486048/most-influential-teens-2014/ | title=The 25 Most Influential Teens of 2014 | publisher=Time | work=TIME Staff | date=October 13, 2014 | accessdate=November 16, 2015}}</ref> He was listed in ''Time''{{'}}s \"The 30 Most Influential Teens of 2015\", making the list after his debut album topped the ''Billboard'' 200 and his single \"Stitches\" made the top 10 in the US and other countries.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://time.com/4081618/most-influential-teens-2015/ | title=The 30 Most Influential Teens of 2015 | publisher=Time | work=TIME Staff | date=October 27, 2015 | accessdate=November 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016\u20142017: ''Illuminate'' ===\n{{Main|Illuminate (Shawn Mendes album)}}\n[[File:Shawn Mendes live in concert.jpg|thumb|220px|Mendes in 2017]]\nOn January 21, 2016, Mendes made his acting debut on [[The CW]]'s ''[[The 100 (TV series)|The 100]]'' third-season premiere.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2724779/shawn-mendes-the-100-song/?xrs=_s.fb_news | title=Watch Shawn Mendes Bring Sweet, Beautiful Music To 'The 100\u2032 | work=MTV news | accessdate=January 18, 2016}}</ref> He later announced his second world tour as a headliner, the [[Shawn Mendes World Tour]], which started in March 2016<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/shawn-mendes-announces-second-headlining-world-tour-20160128 | title=Shawn Mendes Announces Second Headlining World Tour | work=Rolling Stone | date=January 28, 2016 | accessdate=January 31, 2016 | author=Spanos, Brittany}}</ref> and sold out 38 shows in North America and Europe within minutes.<ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite web|last1=Guardia|first1=Niko|last2=Berkofsky|first2=Blossom|title=Shawn Mendes' World Tour Sells Out in Minutes&nbsp;\u2014 Music News|url=http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2016/2/8/shawn-mendes-world-tour-sells-out-in-minutes.html|website=ABC News Radio|accessdate=22 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nMendes released \"[[Treat You Better]]\", the lead single from his second studio album, in June 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7438055/shawn-mendes-treat-you-better-video | title=Shawn Mendes Tries to End an Abusive Relationship in 'Treat You Better' Video | work=Billboard | date=July 12, 2016 | accessdate=July 13, 2016}}</ref> In the US, the single reached the top 10 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, became his second single to peak atop both the Adult Contemporary<ref name=adultcontemporary /> and Adult Pop Songs<ref name=popsongs /> chart, and was certified triple platinum.<ref name=\"RIAA\" /> It also went top 10 in the UK. The album, [[Illuminate (Shawn Mendes album)|Illuminate]], was released on September 23, 2016 and debuted at number one on the US ''Billboard'' 200 with 145,000 equivalent album units, including 121,000 in pure album sales and was certified platinum.<ref name=\"RIAA\" /><ref name=\"US debut\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7526648/shawn-mendes-no-1-billboard-200|title=Shawn Mendes Earns Second No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 With 'Illuminate'|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=October 2, 2016|accessdate=October 3, 2016}}</ref> It debuted atop the charts in Canada, becoming his second number one album in his home country. \"[[Mercy (Shawn Mendes song)|Mercy]]\" was released as the second single on August 18, 2016,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.teenvogue.com/story/shawn-mendes-mercy|work=[[Teen Vogue]]|title=Shawn Mendes's New Song \"Mercy\" Will Break Your Heart|first=Ella|last=Ceron|date=August 18, 2016|accessdate=December 24, 2016}}</ref> which entered the top 20 in the US and the UK and was certified double platinum.<ref name=\"RIAA\" /> Mendes released the live album ''Live at Madison Square Garden'' in December 2016.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7625617/shawn-mendes-live-at-madison-square-garden-album-release |title=Shawn Mendes Gifts Fans Early: 'Live at Madison Square Garden' Coming Friday |date=December 19, 2016 |work=Billboard}}</ref> He appeared as the musical guest on [[Saturday Night Live]] December 3, 2016.<ref name=\"SNL\">{{cite web|last1=Atkinson|first1=Katie|title=Shawn Mendes Performs 'Mercy' & 'Treat You Better' on 'Saturday Night Live'|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7597359/shawn-mendes-performs-snl-mercy-treat-you-better|website=Billboard|accessdate=22 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, Mendes embarked on his [[Illuminate World Tour]], which sold out arenas around the world such as Los Angeles' [[Staples Center]] and London's [[The O2 Arena]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Middleton|first=Ryan|title=Shawn Mendes Announces 2017 Illuminate World Tour Dates|url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/73147/20160908/shawn-mendes-2017-illuminate-world-tour-dates.htm|work=musictimes.com|date=September 8, 2016|accessdate=December 28, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"staples center\">{{cite web|last1=Wilker|first1=Deborah|title=Shawn Mendes Rocks His Dream Stage at Sold-Out L.A. Staples Center Concert|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7865868/shawn-mendes-staples-center-la-concert-recap-charlie-puth|website=Billboard|accessdate=August 24, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Standard\">{{cite web|last1=McClean|first1=Craig|title=Shawn Mendes: I was the most upset I've ever been after Manchester|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/music/shawn-mendes-after-the-manchester-attack-i-was-the-most-upset-i-ve-ever-been-a3554201.html|website=Evening Standard|accessdate=August 24, 2017}}</ref> He released the single \"[[There's Nothing Holdin' Me Back]]\" on April 20, 2017, included on his [[Illuminate (Shawn Mendes album)|''Illuminate'' deluxe edition]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7767807/shawn-mendes-theres-nothing-holdin-me-back-new-single-listen|title=Shawn Mendes Drops Feisty New Single 'There's Nothing Holdin' Me Back' |last=Weatherby|first=Taylor|date=April 20, 2017|work=Billboard|accessdate=May 24, 2017}}</ref> The song was Mendes' third single to reach the top 10 in the US<ref name=\"Forbes\">{{cite web|last1=McIntyre|first1=Hugh|title=Shawn Mendes Grabs Another Top 10 Hit, While 'Despacito' Leads For Week 10|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2017/07/17/shawn-mendes-grabs-another-top-10-hit-while-despacito-leads-for-week-10/#472a753f71e5|website=Forbes|date=July 17, 2017|accessdate=August 24, 2017}}</ref> and third single to reach number one on both the Adult Contemporary<ref name=adultcontemporary /> and Adult Pop Songs<ref name=popsongs /> chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shawn Mendes' \"There's Nothing Holdin' Me Back\" tops \"Billboard's\" Pop Songs chart&nbsp;\u2014 Music News|url=http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2017/8/15/shawn-mendes-theres-nothing-holdin-me-back-tops-billboards-p.html|website=ABC News Radio|date=August 15, 2017|accessdate=August 24, 2017}}</ref> In August 2017, he became the first artist under 20 years old to have three number-one songs on the ''Billboard'' Adult Pop Songs chart.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Trust|first1=Gary|title=Shawn Mendes First Artist Under 20 to Land Three No. 1s on Adult Pop Songs Chart|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7942259/shawn-mendes-three-no-1s-adult-pop-songs-before-20|website=Billboard|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> In November 2017, Mendes became the first artist to have three number-one songs on the ''Billboard'' Adult Contemporary chart before turning 20 years old,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8023330/shawn-mendes-ac-chart-three-number-ones-before-age-20|title=Shawn Mendes Is First Artist in AC Chart's History to Notch Three No. 1s Before Age 20|accessdate=23 September 2018|work=Billboard|first=Gary|last=Trust}}</ref> an unprecedented feat since the founding of the chart more than 50 years ago.\n\nMendes was listed among ''Time's The 30 Most Influential Teens of 2016''<ref name=\"Time 2016\">{{cite web|title=The 30 Most Influential Teens of 2016|url=http://time.com/4532104/most-influential-teens-2016/|publisher=Time|work=TIME Staff|date=October 19, 2016|accessdate=August 27, 2018}}</ref> and made his first appearance on ''[[Forbes]]'s 30 Under 30 2016: Music''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/30-under-30-2016/music/ | title=Forbes 30 Under 30: Music | work=Forbes | date=January 3, 2016 | accessdate=January 4, 2016}}</ref> He topped ''Billboard''{{'}}s 21 Under 21 list in 2017, after his two albums topped ''Billboard'' 200 and his single \"There's Nothing Holding Me Back\" became his fifth top 20 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/photos/7980786/21-under-21-shawn-mendes-lorde-khalid-camila|title=21 Under 21 2017: Music's Next Generation|accessdate=13 October 2018|work=Billboard}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018\u2014present: ''Shawn Mendes'' ===\n{{Main|Shawn Mendes (album)}}\nOn March 22, 2018, Mendes released the lead single \"[[In My Blood (Shawn Mendes song)|In My Blood]]\" from his upcoming third studio album,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-shawn-mendes-raw-new-song-in-my-blood-w518221|title=Hear Shawn Mendes' Raw New Song 'In My Blood'|publisher=}}</ref> followed up by the second single \"[[Lost in Japan]]\" on March 23.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ShawnMendes/status/977032906802696197|title=Shawn Mendes on Twitter|website=Twitter}}</ref> \"In My Blood\" topped the ''Billboard'' Adult Pop Songs chart, making Mendes the first and only artist to have four number one singles in the chart before turning 20 years old.<ref name=popsongs /> \"[[Youth (Shawn Mendes song)|Youth]]\" was released on May 3, featuring American singer [[Khalid (singer)|Khalid]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mymix106.com/shawn-mendes-and-khalid-release-youth/|title=Shawn Mendes and Khalid release 'Youth'|work=Mix 106|last=Tucker|first=Eric|date=May 7, 2018|accessdate=January 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHis [[Shawn Mendes (album)|self-titled studio album]] was released on May 25, 2018, to positive critical reviews, with particular praise towards his songwriting and artistic growth.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8384050/shawn-mendes-shares-artwork-track-list-and-release-date-for-new-album |title=Shawn Mendes Shares Artwork, Track List and Release Date for New Album |last=Brandle |first=Lars |date=April 26, 2018 |work=Billboard |accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref> It debuted at number one in Canada, making it his third number one album in his home country. It debuted at number one on the US ''Billboard'' 200, making Mendes the third-youngest artist to collect three number-one albums.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8459028/shawn-mendes-album-billboard-200-chart-no-1|title=Shawn Mendes Scores No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart|work=Billboard|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=June 3, 2018|accessdate=June 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:QueenbdayRAH210418-28 (26886325387) (cropped).jpg|200px|thumb|left|Mendes performing at the concert honouring the 92nd birthday of [[Elizabeth II]] <small>(April 2018)</small>]]\nTo promote the album, Mendes embarked on his self-titled world tour in 2019.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8455111/shawn-mendes-tour-dates-2019 |title=Shawn Mendes Announces Self-Titled International Arena Tour |last=Jones |first=Abby |date=May 8, 2018 |work=Billboard |accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref> Besides the tour, he performed at music festivals across Europe, North America, and South America. He performed at a televised concert honouring the 92nd birthday of [[Queen Elizabeth II]] on April 21, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/stars-like-tom-jones-and-kylie-minogue-shine-for-queens-92nd-birthday-party-11342015|title=Stars like Tom Jones and Kylie Minogue shine for Queen's 92nd birthday party|publisher=}}</ref> He made TV show appearances on ''[[The Late Late Show with James Corden]]'' in June where he sang one of his latest singles each night for a week.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbs.com/shows/late-late-show/news/1008442/shawn-mendes-is-moving-in/|title=Shawn Mendes Is Crashing With James Corden At The Late Late Show For A Week|accessdate=23 September 2018}}</ref> The tracks he performed live were \"Nervous\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=oN0qlGigpKg|title=Shawn Mendes:Nervous #LateLateShawn|accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref> \"Lost in Japan\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=6Diq5gWKHSE|title=Shawn Mendes:Lost In Japan #LateLateShawn|accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref> \"Perfectly Wrong\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=nc6pLSQGcHQ|title=Shawn Mendes:Perfectly Wrong #LateLateShawn|accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref> and the duet with Julia Michaels \"Like to be You\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=FnL0ubcralI|title=Shawn Mendes:Like to be You #LateLateShawn|accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref> Mendes made an appearance on the late-night talk show ''The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon'' in October and performed Lost in Japan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=xMTX50rb2LY|title=Shawn Mendes- Lost in Japan|accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref> He, together with Fallon and the show's resident band [[The Roots]], performed a special version of \"Treat You Better\" for the show's ''Classroom Instruments'' series.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://etcanada.com/news/374553/shawn-mendes-joins-jimmy-fallon-to-perform-treat-you-better-using-classroom-instruments-watch/|title=Shawn Mendes Joins Jimmy Fallon To Perform 'Treat You Better' Using Classroom Instruments \u2014 Watch!|accessdate=9 October 2018|work=ET Canada|last=Longmire|first=Becca}}</ref> He has also performed his latest singles on the [[iHeartRadio MMVAs]] in Canada on August 27, where he received eight nominations and won four awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8472211/shawn-mendes-dominates-2018-iHeartRadio-Much-Music-Video-Awards|title=Shawn Mendes Dominates iHeartRadio MMVAs 2018|work=Billboard|accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nMendes starred in a documentary directed by YouTube star [[Casey Neistat]]. The short film is part of YouTube's Artist Spotlight Story series, featuring an interview with Mendes and backstage and behind-the-scene footage of Mendes during one of his tours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capitalfm.com/artists/shawn-mendes/documentary-watch-youtube-news/|title=Shawn Mendes' New Documentary Is Confirmed: Here's Where To Watch It|work=CapitalFM|accessdate=23 September 2018}}</ref> The trailer was released on YouTube on September 22 to officially announce the upcoming documentary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=JHUCsvYlFHw|title=SHAWN MENDES \u2013 Artist Spotlight Story (Official Trailer)|accessdate=23 September 2018}}</ref> The documentary, ''Shawn Mendes \u2013 Artist Spotlight Stories'', was published on September 28.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=ZYkvxtriIrI|title=SHAWN MENDES \u2013 Artist Spotlight Stories|accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref> Ahead of the official release day, Mendes and Neistat held a previewing show of the film where selected fans of Mendes were invited for the event.\n\nThe remixed version of \"Lost in Japan\", by Russian-German DJ [[Zedd]], was released on September 27.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8477169/zedd-remix-shawn-mendes-lost-in-japan|title=Zedd Turns Shawn Mendes' 'Lost In Japan' Into a Neon Fantasy: Watch|accessdate=9 October 2018|work=Billboard|last=Bein|first=Kat}}</ref> Mendes performed the remix version of the single during the 2018 American Music Award held in Los Angeles on October 9.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/events/amas/8478128/shawn-mendes-camila-cabello-to-perform-2018-amas|title=Shawn Mendes, Zedd & Camila Cabello To Perform at 2018 American Music Awards|work=Billboard|last=Weatherby|first=Taylor|accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref> He was joined onstage by Zedd.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=CpHHzv5xGBs|title=Shawn Mendes, Zedd \u2013 Lost in Japan (Live from the AMAs / 2018)|accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref> Mendes was listed on ''Billboard'' \"21 Under 21 2018\", topping the list for the second year in a row for his chart performance, having three consecutive number one albums.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/photos/8478197/2018-21-under-21-shawn-mendes-lil-pump-billie-eilish-list|title=21 Under 21 2018: Shawn Mendes, Juice WRLD, Noah Cyrus & More|accessdate=13 October 2018|work=Billboard}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Shawn Mendes Performs \"In My Blood\" MTV VMAs in 2018 Part 4.jpg|220px|thumb|right|Mendes performs \"[[In My Blood (Shawn Mendes song)|In My Blood]]\" at the [[2018 MTV Video Music Awards]].]]\nMendes and [[Zac Brown Band]] were featured in an episode of the American TV program [[CMT Crossroads]], a show that pairs a country musician with a musician from another genre. The episode was aired on October 24 and was taped a month before the scheduled airing date. Mendes and Zac Brown Band performed nine songs, where they sang parts of each other's songs and covered [[Michael Jackson]]'s \"[[Man in the Mirror]]\". Parts of the dialogue between Mendes and Zac Brown Band, talking about music and experiences throughout their career, were shown in between the song performances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/shawn-mendes-zac-brown-band-crossroads-746292/|title=Shawn Mendes on Working With Zac Brown Band, Country-Pop Fusion|work=Rolling Stone|last=Kelly|first=Hunter|accessdate=25 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn November 1, Mendes was announced as one of the musical performers for the 2018 Victoria's Secret Fashion Show which was recorded in New York City in November and aired in December.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8482734/victorias-secret-fashion-show-2018-performers|title=Victoria's Secret Fashion Show Performers Announced: Shawn Mendes, Halsey, The Chainsmokers & More|work=Billboard|last=Bajgrowicz|first=Brooke|accessdate=3 November 2018}}</ref> He released a three-song remix EP on December 21 entitled ''The Album (Remixes)''. The EP includes remixes of songs from his self-titled album such as \"[[Where Were You in the Morning?]]\" with [[Kaytranada]], \"Why\" with [[Leon Bridges]], and \"[[Youth (Shawn Mendes song)|Youth]]\" with [[Jessie Reyez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8491239/shawn-mendes-remix-ep|title=Shawn Mendes Drops Remix EP Featuring Leon Bridges, Jessie Reyez & Kaytranada|work=Billboard|last=Bajgrowicz|first=Brooke|accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn May 3, 2019, Mendes released the single \"[[If I Can't Have You (Shawn Mendes song)|If I Can't Have You]]\" along with its music video.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/shawn-mendes-if-i-cant-have-you-new-single-831360/|title=Song You Need to Know: Shawn Mendes, 'If I Can't Have You'|accessdate=14 May 2019|magazine=RollingStone|last=Spanos|first=Brittany}}</ref> The single debuted at number two in the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100, becoming his highest charting single on the chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8511123/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-sixth-week-hot-100-number-one|title=Lil Nas X's 'Old Town Road' Rules Billboard Hot 100 for Sixth Week; Shawn Mendes, Logic & Eminem Debut in Top Fivepublisher=Billboard|accessdate=14 May 2019|last=Trust|first=Gary}}</ref> It also debuted in the top 10 in Australia and the UK, becoming his fifth top 10 single in both countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/32758/shawn-mendes/|title=Official Charts: Shawn Mendes|accessdate=14 May 2019|publisher=Official Charts}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ariacharts.com.au/news/2019/fourth-week-at-1-for-lil-nas-x-s-old-town-road|title=FOURTH WEEK AT #1 FOR LIL NAS X'S OLD TOWN ROAD, Debuts for Shawn Mendes, Logic and more!|accessdate=14 May 2019|publisher=ARIA Charts}}</ref> On July 19, he released the [[Gryffin]] remix of \"If I Can't Have You\".<ref>{{cite|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/if-i-cant-have-you-gryffin-remix-single/1473301023|title=If I Can't Have You (Gryffin Remix) - Single Shawn Mendes on Apple Music|website=[[iTunes]]|date=July 19, 2019|accessdate=July 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn June 21, 2019, he released \u201c[[Se\u00f1orita (Shawn Mendes and Camila Cabello song)|Se\u00f1orita]]\u201d with [[Cuban Americans|Cuban-American]] singer-songwriter [[Camila Cabello]], along with the music video.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/5416141/shawn-mendes-camila-cabello-single-2019/|title=Shawn Mendes, Camila Cabello release new song, video for \u2018Se\u00f1orita\u2019 - National {{!}} Globalnews.ca|date=2019-06-21|website=globalnews.ca|language=en|access-date=2019-06-21}}</ref> The song debuted at number 2 on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100 chart and marks Mendes' and Cabello's second collaboration, following \"[[I Know What You Did Last Summer (song)|I Know What You Did Last Summer]]\" released in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Shawn-Mendes/chart-history/hot-100|title=Shawn Mendes Chart History (Billboard Hot 100)|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8518516/camila-cabello-shawn-mendes-senorita-five-burning-questions|title=Five Burning Questions: Billboard Staffers Discuss Shawn Mendes and Camila Cabello's 'Senorita' No. 2 Hot 100 Debut|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref> On August 26, 2019, \"Se\u00f1orita\" ascended to the number one position, making it Mendes' first chart-topper on the Hot 100.<ref>{{cite|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8528339/shawn-mendes-camila-cabello-senorita-number-one-hot-100|title=Shawn Mendes & Camila Cabello's 'Se\u00f1orita' Hits No. 1 on Billboard Hot 100|website=[[Billboard Hot 100]]|date=August 26, 2019|accessdate=August 26, 2019}}</ref> The deluxe edition of ''Shawn Mendes'' was released on July 27, 2019, and includes the songs \"If I Can't Have You\" and \"Se\u00f1orita\".<ref>{{cite|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/shawn-mendes-deluxe/1474313635|title=Shawn Mendes (Deluxe) by Shawn Mendes on Apple Music|website=[[iTunes]]|date=July 27, 2019|accessdate=July 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Artistry and musical influences ==\nMendes has mainly been described as a [[Pop music|pop]] and [[folk-pop]] singer.<ref name=AllMusic>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/shawn-mendes-mn0003276902/discography|title=Shawn Mendes AllMusic|website=[[AllMusic]]|author=David Jeffries|accessdate=November 11, 2017}}</ref><ref name=rsilluminate /> Mendes has cited [[John Mayer]], [[Ed Sheeran]], [[Justin Timberlake]], and [[Bruno Mars]] as his main musical influences.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/shawn-mendes/news/mtv-meets-shawn-mendes|work=MTV|title=MTV Meets: Shawn Mendes |first=Jennifer|last=Lynn|date=September 2, 2014|accessdate=September 27, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"et can\"/> Mendes also has cited [[Justin Bieber]] as a \"big early influence\" on him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressparty.com/pg/newsdesk/shawnmendes/view/158968/|title=Shawn Mendes talks moving on from Justin Bieber influence|website=Pressparty|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> Growing up, Mendes listened to reggae music, [[Led Zeppelin]], [[Garth Brooks]], and country music thanks to his parents.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.axs.com/news/q-a-shawn-mendes-talks-touring-musical-influences-and-having-a-no-1-al-55487|work=AXS|title=Q&A: Shawn Mendes talks touring, musical influences and having a No. 1 album|first=William|last=Pankey|date=May 27, 2015|accessdate=September 27, 2015}}</ref> He expressed that his second studio album was influenced by Mayer's work<ref name=\"et can\">{{Cite news |url=https://etcanada.com/news/169573/shawn-mendes-says-john-mayer-was-the-inspiration-behind-his-second-album/ |title=Shawn Mendes Says John Mayer Was The Inspiration Behind His Second Album |date=September 23, 2016 |work=ET Canada |accessdate=April 4, 2018}}</ref> while his third album was inspired by Timberlake, [[Kings of Leon]], [[Kanye West]], and [[Daniel Caesar]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Schiller|first=Rebecca|title=Shawn Mendes Talks Justin Timberlake-Inspired 'Lost in Japan,' Says He's 'Really Proud' of 'In My Blood': Watch|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8257664/shawn-mendes-interview-new-songs-in-my-blood-lost-in-japan-video|accessdate=March 23, 2018|work=Billboard|date=March 23, 2018}}</ref> For Brittany Spanos of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', Mendes incorporates \"catchy acoustic folk-pop tunes\" in his catalogue,<ref name=rsilluminate>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/shawn-mendes-on-grown-up-illuminate-dream-acting-role-w441215|title=Shawn Mendes on Grown-Up New LP, John Mayer's Advice, Dream Acting Role|work=Rolling Stone|date=September 23, 2016|accessdate=October 29, 2016}}</ref> while for Joe Coscarelli of ''[[The New York Times]]'', \"his soft, sometimes soulful pop-rock plays primarily to tweens and teenagers, but has also found traction on adult contemporary radio stations\".<ref name=\"tnyt\">{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/21/arts/music/shawn-mendes-illuminate-interview.html?_r=0 | title=Shawn Mendes, Pop Idol, Is Not Banking on a Gimmick | work=The New York Times | date=September 20, 2016 | accessdate=October 18, 2016}}</ref> In an interview with [[Clash (magazine)|''Clash'' magazine]], Mendes stated: <blockquote>\"I want to create anthems for people. I want to create anthems for big moments in their lives...I don't want my music to play for a few months and then go away forever. And not only that, I want to do incredible things that make a difference too. I think it's not only about the music you release, it's about the things you do while you're making the music.\"<ref name=\"Clash\">{{cite web|title=Shawn Mendes Is The First Face Of Issue 104|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/magazine/shawn-mendes-is-the-first-face-of-issue-104|website=Clash Magazine|accessdate=23 August 2017}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n== Brand endorsement and modelling ==\nMendes signed with [[Wilhelmina Models]] in 2016.<ref name=\"Shawn Mendes\">{{cite web|url=https://models.com/people/shawn-mendes|title=Shawn Mendes|website= models.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.teenvogue.com/story/shawn-mendes-modeling-contract | title=Shawn Mendes Gets Modelling Contract | work=[[Teen Vogue]] | date=January 5, 2016 | accessdate=February 27, 2016 | last=McCall|first=Tyler}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Roth|first1=Madeline|title=SHAWN MENDES IS A MODEL NOW&nbsp;\u2014 AND THESE PICS PROVE HE'S A NATURAL|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2721538/shawn-mendes-model-contract/|website=MTV News|accessdate=18 December 2018|date=4 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wilhelmina.com/talent/shawn-mendes-30074|title=Shawn Mendes \u2013 Model|website= www.wilhelmina.com}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Mendes walked the runway during the \"[[Armani|Emporio Armani]] Spring 2018\" show held in Milan, Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwd.com/fashion-news/fashion-scoops/emporio-armani-extends-partnership-shawn-mendes-1202693845/|title=Emporio Armani Extends Partnership With Shawn Mendes|publisher=WWD}}</ref> Mendes was wearing the Italian brand's new smartwatch, EA Connected, during the show. Ahead of his runway walk, the promotional video featuring Mendes was shown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7833946/shawn-mendes-emporio-armani-milan-fashion-week|title=Shawn Mendes Takes Turn on Emporio Armani Runway at Milan Fashion Week|work=Billboard|accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn June 6, 2018, Mendes was announced as the ambassador for Emporio Armani's entire \"Fall Winter 2018-2019\" watch collection. In July 2018, photographs of Mendes wearing the new EA Connected smartwatches were published on social media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8465841/shawn-mendes-emporio-armani-watch-campaign-pics-ea-connected|title=Shawn Mendes Models New Emporio Armani Watches For EA Connected Campaign|accessdate=28 October 2018|work=Billboard|last=Weatherby|first=Taylor}}</ref>\n\nOn February 16, 2019, Mendes announced that he was the latest brand ambassador for Calvin Klein's #MyCalvins campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8498744/shawn-mendes-calvin-klein-underwear-photos|title=Shawn Mendes Strips Down to His Underwear for Calvin Klein Campaign|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-02-17}}</ref> During the [[61st Annual Grammy Awards]], [[SmileDirectClub]] released an advertisement showcasing a campaign between the company and Mendes with some of the proceeds going to \"organizations that seek to improve children's health as well as mental and emotional well-being.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/shawn-mendes-smile-direct-club-partnership-1203130396/|title=Shawn Mendes to Launch SmileDirectClub Partnership With TV Spot During Grammys|magazine=Variety|author=Staff|date=6 February 2019|access-date=28 February 2019}}</ref> Later that month, Emporio Armani released a new black-and-white advertisement for its touchscreen smartwatches featuring an instrumental version of \"In My Blood\" with Mendes boxing.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8500503/shawn-mendes-armani-watch-ad-video-photos|title=Shawn Mendes Shares Steamy Ad for Armani Watches: Watch|magazine=Billboard|first=Glenn|last=Rowley|date=28 February 2019|access-date=28 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Mendes announced a partnership with Canadian-based food chain, [[Tim Hortons]], in which he features in a commercial and on beverage cups,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/why-shawn-mendes-is-taking-over-tim-hortons-coffee-cups-1.4570265|title=Why Shawn Mendes is taking over Tim Hortons coffee cups|publisher=toronto.ctvnews.ca|date=August 29, 2019}}</ref> followed by a partnership with [[Roots Canada]] in September.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/shawn-mendes-roots-tim-hortons-880065/|title=Shawn Mendes\u2019 Latest Collaborations Are the Most Canadian Thing Ever|publisher=rollingstone.com|date=September 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Philanthropy and supported causes ==\nIn 2014, Mendes and [[DoSomething.org]] launched their campaign called \"Notes from Shawn\" where fans were encouraged to write positive notes and leave them in unexpected places. The campaign was inspired by the lyrics to his first single, \"Life of the Party\", and addressed low self-esteem, depression and awareness of self-harm.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/a24633/shawn-mendes-do-something-notes-from-shawn/|work=seventeenmag|title=Join Shawn Mendes to Combat Low Self-Esteem & Spread LOVE! |first=Alex|last=Abel|date=August 28, 2014|accessdate=October 20, 2016}}</ref> They relaunched their campaign for the second year in a row in 2015, where the campaign was hashtagged online as NotesFromShawn. He partnered with BlendApp with the goal of raising up to $25,000, where $1 was raised for every signup and positive message shared on the application.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.teenvogue.com/story/shawn-mendes-notes-from-shawn-campaign |work=[[Teen Vogue]]|title=How Shawn Mendes is Spreading Happiness with Little Notes|first=Ben|last=Kassoy|date=August 13, 2015|accessdate=December 24, 2016}}</ref> The campaign was relaunched for a third year in a row in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Webster|first1=Emma Sarran|title=The One Note Shawn Mendes Wishes He Could Leave Everywhere He Goes|url=http://www.teenvogue.com/story/shawn-mendes-notes-from-shawn-papermate-campaign|website=Teen Vogue|accessdate=23 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe has also worked with [[Pencils of Promise]], a non-profit organization that builds schools and helps raise the quality of education for developing countries, raising $25,000 to build a school in [[Ghana]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.samaritanmag.com/musicians/shawn-mendes-wants-continue-making-difference-perhaps-go-africa|work=SamaritanMag|title=Shawn Mendes Wants To Continue Making a Difference, Perhaps Go to Africa |first=Karen|last=Bliss|date=November 11, 2015|accessdate=October 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, after witnessing the devastation of the [[Central Mexico earthquake|earthquake in Mexico City]], Mendes created the Mexico Earthquake Relief Fund in conjunction with the [[American Red Cross]] and donated $100,000 towards relief efforts.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tenreyro|first1=Tatiana|title=Shawn Mendes Teams Up With Red Cross For Mexico Earthquake Relief Campaign, $100,000 Already Donated|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7973742/shawn-mendes-red-cross-mexico-earthquake-donated|website=Billboard|accessdate=12 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Mendes worked with Omaze to raise funds through donations to support the WE Schools program, a movement aiming to support youth through educational services and mentorship. Mendes encouraged his fans to help the cause while giving the donors a chance to attend his upcoming concert tour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.omaze.com/experiences/hang-with-shawn-mendes?ref=shawn|title=Meet Shawn Mendes and Sit Front Row at His Show|accessdate=30 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, Mendes took part in the annual Global Citizen festival held at [[Central Park]], New York City.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/globalcitizen/news/how-watch-2018-global-citizen-festival-nyc-ncna913351|title=How to watch the 2018 Global Citizen Festival|accessdate=30 September 2018}}</ref> He performed, alongside other artists such as Janelle Mon\u00e1e, John Legend, and Janet Jackson, and raised awareness regarding the importance of education and children's lack of access to education around the world, particularly young women. Ahead of the event, he took to social media to reach out to Canada's Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]], thanking the Prime Minister for leading the initiative for Leave No Girl Behind, a movement whose goal is to empower girls through workshops and programs,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.leavenogirlbehind.org/directors-message/|title=Leave No Girl Behind International|accessdate=30 September 2018}}</ref> and expressing his willingness to talk more about the project. He also encouraged his fans to support the movement. In response, the Prime Minister thanked Mendes and stated that \"The more people we have fighting for girls' education, the better! Let's talk.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://etcanada.com/news/370734/shawn-mendes-urges-fans-to-join-him-in-supporting-leavenogirlbehind-ahead-of-global-citizen-performance/|title=Shawn Mendes Urges Fans To Join Him In Supporting #LeaveNoGirlBehind Ahead Of Global Citizen Performance|accessdate=30 September 2018|work=ET Canada}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, Mendes, together with producer Teddy Geiger, released a cover of \"[[Under Pressure]]\" by the British rock band [[Queen (band)|Queen]] and [[David Bowie]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://etcanada.com/news/375923/shawn-mendes-teams-up-with-teddy-geiger-for-cover-of-queen-bowie-classic-under-pressure/|title=Shawn Mendes Teams Up With Teddy Geiger For Cover Of Queen-Bowie Classic 'Under Pressure'|accessdate=14 October 2018|work=ET Canada}}</ref> The single was part of a series of covers of Queen's songs, released in celebration of Queen's biopic ''Bohemian Rhapsody''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/shawn-mendes-teddy-geiger-under-pressure-queen-david-bowie-736296/|title=Hear Shawn Mendes, Teddy Geiger Cover Queen's 'Under Pressure'|work=Rollong Stone|accessdate=14 October 2018}}</ref> The proceeds from the single were donated to the [[Mercury Phoenix Trust]], an organization founded by Queen bandmembers after [[Freddie Mercury]]'s death, which helps fight against HIV/AIDS.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2018/10/12/listen-now-shawn-mendes-covers-queens-under-pressure-to-bene.html|title=Listen now: Shawn Mendes covers Queen's \"Under Pressure\" to benefit fight against AIDS|accessdate=14 October 2018|work=ABC Radio}}</ref> Queen's manager, Jim Beach, expressed his gratitude to Mendes and Universal Music Group for helping the cause.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.peoplemagazine.co.za/celebrity-news/international-celebrities/shawn-mendes-teddy-geiger-cover-under-pressure-to-honour-freddie-mercury/|title=Shawn Mendes & Teddy Geiger Cover Under Pressure To Honour Freddie Mercury|accessdate=14 October 2018|work=People Magazine}}</ref>\n\nOn October 20, 2018, Mendes performed along with other artists such as Khalid, NF, Marshmello, Meghan Trainor, and Ella Mai at The Hollywood Bowl, Los Angeles for the \"We Can Survive\" event. The event was organized to raise funds for Young Survival Coalition, in an effort to support young women who were diagnosed with breast cancer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/concerts/8480938/we-can-survive-concert-2018-shawn-mendes-charlie-puth-meghan-trainor|title=Shawn Mendes, Charlie Puth, Meghan Trainor & More Team Up for 'We Can Survive' Concert|accessdate=22 October 2018|work=Billboard|last=Lenniger|first=Shea}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Mendes announced the launch of the Shawn Mendes Foundation, with the aim to \"inspire and empower his fans and today\u2019s youth to bring about positive change in the world and advocate for issues they care most about.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/5827681/shawn-mendes-foundation-audience-charity/|title=Shawn Mendes launches foundation; $1M raised to support audience issues|publisher=globalnews.ca|date=August 28, 2019}}</ref> On 8<sup>th</sup> January, 2020, Mendes announced that both he and his Shawn Mendes Foundation will be donating an undisclosed sum of money to causes including Australia's Red Cross, the New South Wales Rural Fire Service, and South Australia Country Fire Service, to help ease the strain on those impacted by the devastating fires that are tearing through parts of the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-xl/lifestyle/celebs/shawn-mendes-donates-to-australia-wildfire-relief-efforts/ar-BBYLcod?li=BBKhQr3&ocid=wispr|title=Shawn Mendes donates to Australia wildfire relief efforts|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nMendes has been open about his struggles with [[anxiety disorder|anxiety]], which he disclosed publicly through \"[[In My Blood (Shawn Mendes song)|In My Blood]]\", a track from his third studio album. He declared that he had been undergoing therapy in order to help him deal with the mental health condition, stating:\n{{quote|I spoke to a therapist a couple of times [...] Therapy is what works for you. Therapy is listening to music and running on the treadmill, therapy is going to dinner with your friends\u2014it's something that distracts you, that helps you heal and so it just depends on what you think therapy is. I made a conscious effort to be more connected to the people in my life. I found I was closing myself off from everybody, thinking that would help me battle it then realizing the only way I was going to battle it was completely opening up and letting people in.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/shawn-mendes-undergoes-therapy-to-cure-anxiety-118042100102_1.html |title=Shawn Mendes undergoes therapy to cure anxiety |date=April 21, 2018 |work=[[Business Standard]] |accessdate=April 22, 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nWith regard to speculation about his [[Sexual orientation|sexuality]], Mendes stated, \"First of all, I'm not gay. Second of all, it shouldn't make a difference if I was or if I wasn't. The focus should be on the music and not my sexuality.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Real |first1=Evan |title=Shawn Mendes Responds to Rumors About His Sexuality |url=https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/shawn-mendes-responds-to-rumors-about-his-sexuality-w211236/ |accessdate=27 November 2018 |work=Us Weekly |date=24 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Brammer |first1=John Paul |title=Let Shawn Mendes Be Heterosexual in Peace |url=https://www.them.us/story/shawn-mendes-is-heterosexual |accessdate=27 November 2018 |work=them. |date=9 May 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Doyle |first1=Patrick |title=Shawn Mendes: Confessions of a Neurotic Teen Idol |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/shawn-mendes-cover-interview-756847/ |accessdate=27 November 2018 |work=Rolling Stone |date=26 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nSince July 2019, he has been dating Cuban-American singer [[Camila Cabello]]. However, the relationship has garnered controversy, as both were accused of attempting to [[Publicity stunt|form a relationship for publicity]],<ref name=\"Capital 2019\">{{cite web |title=Inside Shawn Mendes and Camila Cabello's relationship |website=Capital FM |date=2019-09-12 |url=https://www.capitalfm.com/artists/shawn-mendes/camila-cabello-dating-relationship/ |access-date=2019-10-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/sep/13/camila-cabello-shawn-mendes-romance-real-j-lo-drake |title=Bad fauxmance: when celebrity couples become PR stunts |last=Cooper |first=Leonie |date=September 13, 2019 |website=The Guardian |language=en-GB |access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Bonner 2019\">{{cite web |last=Bonner |first=Mehera |title=Shawn Mendes and Camila Cabello's Relationship Timeline |website=Cosmopolitan.com |date=2019-07-30 |url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/entertainment/celebs/amp28551280/shawn-mendes-camila-cabello-relationship-timeline/ |access-date=2019-10-10}}</ref> but Mendes insisted it is \"definitely not a publicity stunt\".<ref name=\"Elle\">{{cite web |last=Bailey |first=Alyssa |title=Shawn Mendes Wants You To Know His Relationship With Camila Cabello Is 'Not A Publicity Stunt'|website=elle.com |date=2019-09-19 |url=https://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/a29122311/shawn-mendes-camila-cabello-kissing-date-fake-relationship-response/ |access-date=2019-10-20}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Shawn Mendes}}\nMendes has received several nominations and awards. He won 13 [[Society of Composers, Authors and Music Publishers of Canada]] (SOCAN) awards, 11 [[MTV Europe Music Awards]] (EMA), eight [[iHeartRadio Much Music Video Awards]] (MMVA), eight [[Juno Award]]s, three [[BMI Awards]], three [[American Music Award]]s, two [[MTV Video Music Award]]s, and the Allan Slaight Honour from [[Canada's Walk of Fame]]. He was nominated for three [[Grammy Award]]s.\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Films roles\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Roles !! Notes\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Metegol]]''\n| Young Jake (voice)\n| English dub; direct to video\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Television roles\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Roles !! Notes\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Yo quisiera''\n| Himself\n| Episode: \"Yo soy la bloguera de moda\"\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2016\n| ''[[The 100 (TV series)|The 100]]''\n| Macallan\n| Episode: \"Wanheda: Part 1\"\n|-\n| ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''\n|rowspan=3|Himself\n|Episode: \"[[Emma Stone]]/Shawn Mendes\"\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Drop the Mic]]''\n| Episode: \"[[Odell Beckham Jr]]. vs. Shawn Mendes / [[Molly Ringwald]] vs. [[Jon Cryer]]\"\n|-\n|2019\n| ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''\n|Episode: \"[[Adam Sandler]]/Shawn Mendes\"\n|-\n|}\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Shawn Mendes discography|List of songs recorded by Shawn Mendes|l2 = songs}}\n* ''[[Handwritten (Shawn Mendes album)|Handwritten]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Illuminate (Shawn Mendes album)|Illuminate]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Shawn Mendes (album)|Shawn Mendes]]'' (2018)\n\n== Tours ==\n=== Headlining ===\n* [[Shawn's First Headlines|#ShawnsFirstHeadlines]] (2014\u20132015)\n* [[Shawn Mendes World Tour]] (2016)\n* [[Illuminate World Tour]] (2017)\n* [[Shawn Mendes: The Tour]] (2019)\n\n=== Co-headlining ===\n* [[Jingle Ball Tour 2014]] (with various artists) (2014)\n* Jingle Ball Tour 2015 (with various artists) (2015)\n* Jingle Ball Tour 2018 (with various artists) (2018)\n\n=== Supporting ===\n* [[Austin Mahone: Live on Tour]] ([[Austin Mahone]]) (North America) (2014)\n* [[The 1989 World Tour]] ([[Taylor Swift]]) (North America) (2015)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links\n|collapsible=yes\n|wikt=no\n|c=Category:Shawn Mendes\n|n=no\n|q=Shawn Mendes\n|s=no\n|author=no\n|b=no\n|v=no\n}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.shawnmendesofficial.com/}}\n* {{IMDb name|6658398}}\n* {{Twitter|ShawnMendes}}\n* {{Instagram|shawnmendes}}\n\n{{Shawn Mendes}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mendes, Shawn}}\n[[Category:Shawn Mendes| ]]\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian pianists]]\n[[Category:Canadian child singers]]\n[[Category:Canadian male singers]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Portuguese descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian pop guitarists]]\n[[Category:Canadian male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Canadian pop pianists]]\n[[Category:Canadian pop singers]]\n[[Category:Child pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Toronto]]\n[[Category:People from Pickering, Ontario]]\n[[Category:MTV EMA winners]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for Single of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Juno Fan Choice Award winners]]\n[[Category:Canadian male pianists]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for Pop Album of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for Album of the Year winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the singer|his self-titled album|Shawn Mendes (album){{!}}''Shawn Mendes'' (album)}}\n{{short description|Canadian singer, songwriter, and model}}\n{{pp-vand|small=yes}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Shawn Mendes\n| image              = Shawn Mendes Glamour May 2018.png\n| caption            = Mendes in May 2018\n| birth_name         = Shawn Peter Raul Mendes\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1998|8|8}}\n| birth_place        = [[Pickering, Ontario]], Canada\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Singer\n* songwriter\n* record producer\n}}\n| years_active       = 2013\u2013present\n| home_town          =\n| agent              = [[Wilhelmina Models]]\n| partner            = <!--This parameter is for LONG-TERM unmarried life partners\u2014not girlfriends or flings-->\n| awards             = [[List of awards and nominations received by Shawn Mendes|Full list]]\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes<!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| background = solo_singer <!-- mandatory field -->\n| instrument      = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* guitar\n* piano\n}}\n| genre               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Pop music|Pop]]\n* [[folk-pop]]\n* [[pop rock]]\n}}<!--Only list genres that are prominent/recurring in his career. -->\n| label           = {{flatlist|\n* [[Island Records|Island]]\n* [[Republic Records|Republic]]<ref>{{cite magazine| last1=Rubin|first1=Rebecca|last2=Halperin|first2=Shirley|url=https://variety.com/2017/music/news/shawn-mendes-theres-nothing-holdin-me-back-no-1-charts-1202528804/|title=Shawn Mendes' 'There's Nothing Holdin' Me Back' Hits No. 1 on Top 40|date=15 August 2017|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=31 March 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Universal Music Canada]] <ref> https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7767524/universal-music-canada-relocating-rock-star-building-toronto</ref>\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[Teddy Geiger]]\n* [[Camila Cabello]]\n}}<!-- Please DO NOT ADD associated acts unless they have collaborated with Mendes on at least 2 songs. -->\n| website         = {{URL|shawnmendesofficial.com}}}}\n}}\n\n'''Shawn Peter Raul Mendes''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|m|\u025b|n|d|\u025b|z}}; born August 8, 1998) is a Canadian singer and songwriter. He gained a following in 2013, posting song covers on the video-sharing application [[Vine (software)|Vine]]. The following year, he caught the attention of artist manager [[Andrew Gertler]] and [[Island Records]] [[Artists and repertoire|A&R]] Ziggy Chareton, which led to him signing a deal with the record label. He has since released [[Shawn Mendes discography|three studio albums]], headlined [[Shawn Mendes#Tours|three world tours]], and received [[List of awards and nominations received by Shawn Mendes|several awards]].\n\nMendes released his [[The Shawn Mendes EP|self-titled debut EP]] (2014) and his debut studio album ''[[Handwritten (Shawn Mendes album)|Handwritten]]'' (2015), whose single \"[[Stitches (Shawn Mendes song)|Stitches]]\" reached number one in the United Kingdom and the top 10 in the United States and Canada. He then released his second studio album ''[[Illuminate (Shawn Mendes album)|Illuminate]]'' (2016), whose singles \"[[Treat You Better]]\" and \"[[There's Nothing Holdin' Me Back]]\" reached the top 10 in several countries. His [[Shawn Mendes (album)|self-titled third studio album]] (2018) was supported by the lead single \"[[In My Blood (Shawn Mendes song)|In My Blood]]\". All three albums debuted atop the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], with the first one making Mendes one of five artists ever to debut at number one before the age of 18 and the third one making him the third-youngest artist to achieve three number one albums. In 2017, Mendes became the first artist to land three number-one singles on the ''Billboard'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]] chart before turning 20 years old. In 2018, he became the first artist to achieve four number-one singles on the [[Adult Top 40|Adult Pop Songs]] chart before the age of 20 as well. In 2019, he released the hit singles \"[[If I Can't Have You (Shawn Mendes song)|If I Can't Have You]]\" and \"[[Se\u00f1orita (Shawn Mendes and Camila Cabello song)|Se\u00f1orita]]\", with the latter peaking at number one on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].\n\nAmong his accolades, Mendes has won 13 [[Society of Composers, Authors and Music Publishers of Canada|SOCAN]] awards, 10 [[MTV Europe Music Award]]s, eight [[Juno Award]]s, eight [[iHeartRadio MMVAs]], two [[American Music Awards]], and received three [[Grammy Award]] nominations. In 2018, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' named Mendes as one of the 100 most influential people in the world on their [[Time 100|annual list]].\n\n== Early life ==\nMendes was born in the city of [[Pickering, Ontario]], to Karen ([[n\u00e9e]] Rayment), a real estate agent, and Manuel Mendes, a businessman, who sells bar and restaurant supplies in Toronto. His father is Portuguese (from the [[Algarve]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noticiasmagazine.pt/2015/shawn-mendes-o-rapaz-do-momento/|title=Shawn Mendes: o rapaz do momento|date=October 23, 2015|work=noticiasmagazine.pt|accessdate=February 2, 2016}}</ref> while his mother is from England. He has a younger sister named Aaliyah.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/music/a28137090/shawn-mendes-sister-aaliyah/|title=Who Is Shawn Mendes's Sister Aaliyah Mendes and Is She Famous?|date=June 21, 2019|work=Seventeen|accessdate=July 24, 2019}}</ref> He was raised in a religious family.<ref>{{cite magazine| last1=Marine|first1=Brooke|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/shawn-mendes-met-gala-2018|title=Shawn Mendes Opens Up Before His First Met Gala About His Friend Hailey Baldwin, Being a Romantic at Heart, and His New Music|date=8 May 2018|magazine=[[W Magazine]]|accessdate=6 November 2018|quote=\"Forever, religion is going to have a massive impact on people's fashion. It always has been and always will be,\" Mendes\u2014who later revealed he did come from a religious upbringing\u2014told W when asked how he planned to incorporate the theme into his look for the evening.}}</ref>\n\nMendes was raised in Pickering where he attended [[Pine Ridge Secondary School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/11340960/Shawn-Mendes-How-a-six-second-video-launched-the-next-Justin-Bieber.html|title=Shawn Mendes: How a six-second video launched the next Justin Bieber|date=January 16, 2015|work=Telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=January 27, 2015}}</ref> At school, he played ice hockey and soccer, joined his high school [[glee club]], and practised his stage presence in acting lessons (leading as [[Prince Charming]] at one point). He also auditioned for [[Disney Channel]] in Toronto.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.iheartradio.com.au/entertainment/entertainment-news/shawn-mendes-was-nearly-a-disney-kid |title=Shawn Mendes Was Nearly A Disney Kid |date=July 10, 2017 |accessdate=November 9, 2018 |work=iHeartRadio |location=Canada}}</ref> Mendes graduated from high school in June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/shawn-mendes-finally-graduated-high-school|title=Shawn Mendes Finally Graduated High School Yesterday|date=June 29, 2016|work=Teen Vogue|accessdate=October 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n=== 2013\u20142015: ''Handwritten'' ===\n{{Main|Handwritten (Shawn Mendes album)}}\n[[File:Shawn Mendes VOA.png|left|200px|thumb|Mendes at the [[Jingle Ball Tour 2014]]]]\nMendes learned to play guitar by watching [[YouTube]] tutorial videos at the age of 14 in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.axs.com/shawn-mendes-5-things-you-didn-t-know-50268 |title=Shawn Mendes: 5 things you didn't know |date=April 23, 2015 |work=AXS |accessdate=February 12, 2017}}</ref> Less than a year later he started posting [[cover version|cover videos]] on YouTube. Mendes started attracting viewers after he posted a cover from [[Justin Bieber]] \"[[As Long as You Love Me (Justin Bieber song)|As Long as You Love Me]]\" on the social video app [[Vine (service)|Vine]] in 2013 and got 10,000 likes and as many followers the next day. After that he gained millions of views and followers in a few months, becoming well known for his six-second snippets of renditions of many popular songs.<ref>{{cite web |title=Getting Honest With Shawn Mendes |url=http://honestblue.com/getting-honest-with-shawn-mendes/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140605021933/http://honestblue.com/getting-honest-with-shawn-mendes/ |archive-date=June 5, 2014 |work=Honest Blue |url-status=dead |accessdate=April 30, 2018}}</ref> By August 2014, he was the third most-followed musician on Vine.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shawn Mendes: 5 Things You Need To Know About The Vine Star Turned Chart-Topping Singer (PHOTOS) |url=http://www.hngn.com/articles/142503/20151021/shawn-mendes-5-things-you-need-to-know-about-the-vine-star-turned-chart-topping-singer-photos.htm |website=Headlines & Global News |date=October 21, 2015 |accessdate=2015-11-14}}</ref> Artist manager Andrew Gertler discovered Mendes online in November 2013, bringing him to [[Island Records]] in January 2014. In April, he won [[Ryan Seacrest]]'s \"Best Cover Song\" contest with \"[[Say Something (A Great Big World song)|Say Something]]\" by [[A Great Big World]]. He officially signed to Island in May 2014.\n\nHe released his first single \"[[Life of the Party (Shawn Mendes song)|Life of the Party]]\" on June 26, 2014.<ref name=Billboard>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6165603/shawn-mendes-vine-magazine-story |title=How Shawn Mendes Is Turning Vine Fame into A Music Career |magazine=Billboard |date=July 18, 2014 |accessdate=July 18, 2014}}</ref> He became the youngest to debut in the top 25 on the US [[The Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], making it to number 24 for the week ending July 12, 2014.<ref name=Idolator1>{{cite web |url=http://www.idolator.com/7525178/shawn-mendes-vine-celebrity-life-of-the-party-billboard-debut-record-charts/ |title=Shawn Mendes, 15-Year-Old Vine Celebrity, Makes Record-Breaking Debut on Billboard Hot 100 |publisher=Idolator |date=July 2, 2014 |accessdate=July 13, 2014}}</ref> Prior to his signing, Mendes toured as a member of the [[Magcon]] Tour<ref>{{cite web |title=Girls go gaga for Vine video boys at Itasca meet and greet DailyHerald.com |url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20140301/news/140309846/ |date=March 3, 2014 |work=Daily Herald}}</ref> alongside other young Viners with a large following on social media.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2014-02-21/news/ct-vine-app-met-20140221_1_instagram-app-teen |title= Viners' meet and greet fosters teen idol frenzy Boys encounter stardom as popular producers of Twitter app's 6-second videos |date=February 21, 2014 |first=Ted |last=Gregory}}</ref> Mendes was also on a nationwide tour with [[Austin Mahone]] as an opening act. He released his debut major label EP in July.<ref>{{cite web|title='Secret' is out: Austin Mahone announces album, tour |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2014/04/04/the-secret-is-out-austin-mahone-announces-album-tour/7293633/ |work=USA Today |date=April 4, 2014}}</ref> The EP debuted and peaked at number five on [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], selling 48,000 copies in its first week.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6531900/shawn-mendes-handwritten-number-one-album|work=Billboard |title=Shawn Mendes Album on Course for No. 1 Debut on Billboard 200 Chart |first=Keith |last=Caulfield |date=April 15, 2015 |accessdate=October 2, 2015}}</ref> He won a [[Teen Choice]] award in 2014 for Webstar in Music.<ref>{{cite web |title=Vine Superstar Shawn Mendes Signed to Island Records (Exclusive) |first=Harley |last=Brown |date=June 4, 2014 |url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/legal-and-management/6106433/vine-superstar-shawn-mendes-signed-to-island-records |work=Billboard}}</ref> On September 5, 2014, \"[[Oh Cecilia (Breaking My Heart)]]\" featuring Mendes was released as the fifth single from [[The Vamps (British band)|The Vamps]]' debut album, ''[[Meet the Vamps]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://popcrush.com/the-vamps-oh-cecilia-shawn-mendes/ |title=The Vamps Release Remix of 'Oh Cecilia (Breaking My Heart)' Feat. Shawn Mendes [LISTEN] |publisher=popcrush.com}}</ref> On November 6, 2014, \"[[Something Big (song)|Something Big]]\" was released as the second single.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1990288/shawn-mendes-something-big-released/ |title=Shawn Mendes' New Single 'Something Big' Is Actually Something Huge |publisher=MTV.com}}</ref>\n\nOn April 14, 2015, Mendes released his full-length album ''[[Handwritten (Shawn Mendes album)|Handwritten]]'', which debuted at number one on the ''Billboard'' 200 chart with 119,000 [[Top Album Sales|equivalent album units]], selling 106,000 copies in its first week and was certified platinum.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6538916/shawn-mendes-handwritten-debut-no-1-billboard-200-chart|work=Billboard|title=Shawn Mendes' 'Handwritten' Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Chart|first=Keith|last=Caulfield|date=April 22, 2015|accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"RIAA\">{{cite web|title=You searched for shawn mendes&nbsp;\u2014 RIAA|url=https://www.riaa.com/?s=shawn+mendes|website=RIAA|accessdate=22 August 2017}}</ref> Mendes then became the youngest artist to debut at number one since the release of [[Justin Bieber]]'s [[My World 2.0]].<ref name=\"idolator\">{{cite web|last1=Daw|first1=Robbie|title=Shawn Mendes Becomes Youngest Artist To Top Album Chart In Half A Decade&nbsp;\u2014 idolator|url=http://www.idolator.com/7589967/shawn-mendes-youngest-artist-album-chart-handwritten|website=idolator|accessdate=22 August 2017|date=22 April 2015}}</ref> The third single from the album, \"[[Stitches (Shawn Mendes song)|Stitches]]\", peaked at number four on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100, becoming his first top 10 single in the US,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6738614/weeknd-tops-hot-100-adele-no-1-next-week|work=Billboard|title=The Weeknd Tops Hot 100; Adele No. 1 Next Week?|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=October 26, 2015|accessdate=October 26, 2015}}</ref> and became his first number one on the Adult Pop Songs<ref name=popsongs>{{Cite web| url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8467895/shawn-mendes-first-artist-to-have-four-no-1s-adult-pop-songs | title=Shawn Mendes Is the First Artist to Land Four No. 1s on the Adult Pop Songs Chart Before Age 20 | work=Billboard | date=November 15, 2015 | accessdate=23 September 2018| author=Trust, Gary}}</ref> and Adult Contemporary charts.<ref name=adultcontemporary>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8023330/shawn-mendes-ac-chart-three-number-ones-before-age-20|title=Shawn Mendes Is First Artist in AC Chart's History to Notch Three No. 1s Before Age 20|work=Billboard|last=Trust|first=Gary|accessdate= 23 September 2018}}</ref> The song later reached number one in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/shawn-mendes-stitches-knocks-justin-bieber-from-singles-number-1__13615/|title=It's not a stitch-up! Shawn Mendes knocks Bieber off Number 1|last=Copsey|first=Rob|date=January 22, 2016|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=January 24, 2016}}</ref> Also in 2015, Mendes opened for [[Taylor Swift]] during [[1989 World Tour]] dates for North America and recorded \"[[Believe (Shawn Mendes song)|Believe]]\" for the soundtrack of [[Disney Channel Original Movie]] ''[[Descendants (2015 film)|Descendants]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/music/news/a31593/disneys-descendants-will-feature-a-brand-new-song-from-shawn-mendes/|work=Seventeen|title=Shawn Mendes Wrote a New Song for Disney's \"Descendants\" Soundtrack!|first=Hayley|last=Glatter|date=June 12, 2015|accessdate=November 5, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news| url=http://headlineplanet.com/home/2014/11/03/vance-joy-shawn-mendes-join-taylor-swifts-1989-tour-dates-revealed/ | work= Headline Planet | title=Vance Joy, Shawn Mendes tapped to support Taylor Swift on her \"1989\" tour | date=November 3, 2014}}</ref> In late 2015, Mendes and [[Camila Cabello]], who was at the time a member of the group [[Fifth Harmony]], released their collaborative single \"[[I Know What You Did Last Summer (song)|I Know What You Did Last Summer]]\". The song was included on Mendes' ''Handwritten Revisited'' reissue.<ref>{{cite web|title = Shawn Mendes & Camila Cabello Announce 'I Know What You Did Last Summer' Duet: Hear a Preview|url = https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6760707/shawn-mendes-camila-cabello-i-know-what-you-did-last-summer-song|website = Billboard|accessdate = 2015-11-14}}</ref>\n\nMendes was listed among ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'}}s \"25 Most Influential Teens of 2014\", debuting in the list after being the youngest-ever artist to debut in the top 25 of ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://time.com/3486048/most-influential-teens-2014/ | title=The 25 Most Influential Teens of 2014 | publisher=Time | work=TIME Staff | date=October 13, 2014 | accessdate=November 16, 2015}}</ref> He was listed in ''Time''{{'}}s \"The 30 Most Influential Teens of 2015\", making the list after his debut album topped the ''Billboard'' 200 and his single \"Stitches\" made the top 10 in the US and other countries.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://time.com/4081618/most-influential-teens-2015/ | title=The 30 Most Influential Teens of 2015 | publisher=Time | work=TIME Staff | date=October 27, 2015 | accessdate=November 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016\u20142017: ''Illuminate'' ===\n{{Main|Illuminate (Shawn Mendes album)}}\n[[File:Shawn Mendes live in concert.jpg|thumb|220px|Mendes in 2017]]\nOn January 21, 2016, Mendes made his acting debut on [[The CW]]'s ''[[The 100 (TV series)|The 100]]'' third-season premiere.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2724779/shawn-mendes-the-100-song/?xrs=_s.fb_news | title=Watch Shawn Mendes Bring Sweet, Beautiful Music To 'The 100\u2032 | work=MTV news | accessdate=January 18, 2016}}</ref> He later announced his second world tour as a headliner, the [[Shawn Mendes World Tour]], which started in March 2016<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/shawn-mendes-announces-second-headlining-world-tour-20160128 | title=Shawn Mendes Announces Second Headlining World Tour | work=Rolling Stone | date=January 28, 2016 | accessdate=January 31, 2016 | author=Spanos, Brittany}}</ref> and sold out 38 shows in North America and Europe within minutes.<ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite web|last1=Guardia|first1=Niko|last2=Berkofsky|first2=Blossom|title=Shawn Mendes' World Tour Sells Out in Minutes&nbsp;\u2014 Music News|url=http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2016/2/8/shawn-mendes-world-tour-sells-out-in-minutes.html|website=ABC News Radio|accessdate=22 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nMendes released \"[[Treat You Better]]\", the lead single from his second studio album, in June 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7438055/shawn-mendes-treat-you-better-video | title=Shawn Mendes Tries to End an Abusive Relationship in 'Treat You Better' Video | work=Billboard | date=July 12, 2016 | accessdate=July 13, 2016}}</ref> In the US, the single reached the top 10 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, became his second single to peak atop both the Adult Contemporary<ref name=adultcontemporary /> and Adult Pop Songs<ref name=popsongs /> chart, and was certified triple platinum.<ref name=\"RIAA\" /> It also went top 10 in the UK. The album, [[Illuminate (Shawn Mendes album)|Illuminate]], was released on September 23, 2016 and debuted at number one on the US ''Billboard'' 200 with 145,000 equivalent album units, including 121,000 in pure album sales and was certified platinum.<ref name=\"RIAA\" /><ref name=\"US debut\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7526648/shawn-mendes-no-1-billboard-200|title=Shawn Mendes Earns Second No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 With 'Illuminate'|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=October 2, 2016|accessdate=October 3, 2016}}</ref> It debuted atop the charts in Canada, becoming his second number one album in his home country. \"[[Mercy (Shawn Mendes song)|Mercy]]\" was released as the second single on August 18, 2016,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.teenvogue.com/story/shawn-mendes-mercy|work=[[Teen Vogue]]|title=Shawn Mendes's New Song \"Mercy\" Will Break Your Heart|first=Ella|last=Ceron|date=August 18, 2016|accessdate=December 24, 2016}}</ref> which entered the top 20 in the US and the UK and was certified double platinum.<ref name=\"RIAA\" /> Mendes released the live album ''Live at Madison Square Garden'' in December 2016.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7625617/shawn-mendes-live-at-madison-square-garden-album-release |title=Shawn Mendes Gifts Fans Early: 'Live at Madison Square Garden' Coming Friday |date=December 19, 2016 |work=Billboard}}</ref> He appeared as the musical guest on [[Saturday Night Live]] December 3, 2016.<ref name=\"SNL\">{{cite web|last1=Atkinson|first1=Katie|title=Shawn Mendes Performs 'Mercy' & 'Treat You Better' on 'Saturday Night Live'|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7597359/shawn-mendes-performs-snl-mercy-treat-you-better|website=Billboard|accessdate=22 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, Mendes embarked on his [[Illuminate World Tour]], which sold out arenas around the world such as Los Angeles' [[Staples Center]] and London's [[The O2 Arena]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Middleton|first=Ryan|title=Shawn Mendes Announces 2017 Illuminate World Tour Dates|url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/73147/20160908/shawn-mendes-2017-illuminate-world-tour-dates.htm|work=musictimes.com|date=September 8, 2016|accessdate=December 28, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"staples center\">{{cite web|last1=Wilker|first1=Deborah|title=Shawn Mendes Rocks His Dream Stage at Sold-Out L.A. Staples Center Concert|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7865868/shawn-mendes-staples-center-la-concert-recap-charlie-puth|website=Billboard|accessdate=August 24, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Standard\">{{cite web|last1=McClean|first1=Craig|title=Shawn Mendes: I was the most upset I've ever been after Manchester|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/music/shawn-mendes-after-the-manchester-attack-i-was-the-most-upset-i-ve-ever-been-a3554201.html|website=Evening Standard|accessdate=August 24, 2017}}</ref> He released the single \"[[There's Nothing Holdin' Me Back]]\" on April 20, 2017, included on his [[Illuminate (Shawn Mendes album)|''Illuminate'' deluxe edition]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7767807/shawn-mendes-theres-nothing-holdin-me-back-new-single-listen|title=Shawn Mendes Drops Feisty New Single 'There's Nothing Holdin' Me Back' |last=Weatherby|first=Taylor|date=April 20, 2017|work=Billboard|accessdate=May 24, 2017}}</ref> The song was Mendes' third single to reach the top 10 in the US<ref name=\"Forbes\">{{cite web|last1=McIntyre|first1=Hugh|title=Shawn Mendes Grabs Another Top 10 Hit, While 'Despacito' Leads For Week 10|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2017/07/17/shawn-mendes-grabs-another-top-10-hit-while-despacito-leads-for-week-10/#472a753f71e5|website=Forbes|date=July 17, 2017|accessdate=August 24, 2017}}</ref> and third single to reach number one on both the Adult Contemporary<ref name=adultcontemporary /> and Adult Pop Songs<ref name=popsongs /> chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shawn Mendes' \"There's Nothing Holdin' Me Back\" tops \"Billboard's\" Pop Songs chart&nbsp;\u2014 Music News|url=http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2017/8/15/shawn-mendes-theres-nothing-holdin-me-back-tops-billboards-p.html|website=ABC News Radio|date=August 15, 2017|accessdate=August 24, 2017}}</ref> In August 2017, he became the first artist under 20 years old to have three number-one songs on the ''Billboard'' Adult Pop Songs chart.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Trust|first1=Gary|title=Shawn Mendes First Artist Under 20 to Land Three No. 1s on Adult Pop Songs Chart|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7942259/shawn-mendes-three-no-1s-adult-pop-songs-before-20|website=Billboard|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> In November 2017, Mendes became the first artist to have three number-one songs on the ''Billboard'' Adult Contemporary chart before turning 20 years old,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8023330/shawn-mendes-ac-chart-three-number-ones-before-age-20|title=Shawn Mendes Is First Artist in AC Chart's History to Notch Three No. 1s Before Age 20|accessdate=23 September 2018|work=Billboard|first=Gary|last=Trust}}</ref> an unprecedented feat since the founding of the chart more than 50 years ago.\n\nMendes was listed among ''Time's The 30 Most Influential Teens of 2016''<ref name=\"Time 2016\">{{cite web|title=The 30 Most Influential Teens of 2016|url=http://time.com/4532104/most-influential-teens-2016/|publisher=Time|work=TIME Staff|date=October 19, 2016|accessdate=August 27, 2018}}</ref> and made his first appearance on ''[[Forbes]]'s 30 Under 30 2016: Music''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/30-under-30-2016/music/ | title=Forbes 30 Under 30: Music | work=Forbes | date=January 3, 2016 | accessdate=January 4, 2016}}</ref> He topped ''Billboard''{{'}}s 21 Under 21 list in 2017, after his two albums topped ''Billboard'' 200 and his single \"There's Nothing Holding Me Back\" became his fifth top 20 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/photos/7980786/21-under-21-shawn-mendes-lorde-khalid-camila|title=21 Under 21 2017: Music's Next Generation|accessdate=13 October 2018|work=Billboard}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018\u2014present: ''Shawn Mendes'' ===\n{{Main|Shawn Mendes (album)}}\nOn March 22, 2018, Mendes released the lead single \"[[In My Blood (Shawn Mendes song)|In My Blood]]\" from his upcoming third studio album,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-shawn-mendes-raw-new-song-in-my-blood-w518221|title=Hear Shawn Mendes' Raw New Song 'In My Blood'|publisher=}}</ref> followed up by the second single \"[[Lost in Japan]]\" on March 23.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ShawnMendes/status/977032906802696197|title=Shawn Mendes on Twitter|website=Twitter}}</ref> \"In My Blood\" topped the ''Billboard'' Adult Pop Songs chart, making Mendes the first and only artist to have four number one singles in the chart before turning 20 years old.<ref name=popsongs /> \"[[Youth (Shawn Mendes song)|Youth]]\" was released on May 3, featuring American singer [[Khalid (singer)|Khalid]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mymix106.com/shawn-mendes-and-khalid-release-youth/|title=Shawn Mendes and Khalid release 'Youth'|work=Mix 106|last=Tucker|first=Eric|date=May 7, 2018|accessdate=January 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHis [[Shawn Mendes (album)|self-titled studio album]] was released on May 25, 2018, to positive critical reviews, with particular praise towards his songwriting and artistic growth.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8384050/shawn-mendes-shares-artwork-track-list-and-release-date-for-new-album |title=Shawn Mendes Shares Artwork, Track List and Release Date for New Album |last=Brandle |first=Lars |date=April 26, 2018 |work=Billboard |accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref> It debuted at number one in Canada, making it his third number one album in his home country. It debuted at number one on the US ''Billboard'' 200, making Mendes the third-youngest artist to collect three number-one albums.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8459028/shawn-mendes-album-billboard-200-chart-no-1|title=Shawn Mendes Scores No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart|work=Billboard|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=June 3, 2018|accessdate=June 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:QueenbdayRAH210418-28 (26886325387) (cropped).jpg|200px|thumb|left|Mendes performing at the concert honouring the 92nd birthday of [[Elizabeth II]] <small>(April 2018)</small>]]\nTo promote the album, Mendes embarked on his self-titled world tour in 2019.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8455111/shawn-mendes-tour-dates-2019 |title=Shawn Mendes Announces Self-Titled International Arena Tour |last=Jones |first=Abby |date=May 8, 2018 |work=Billboard |accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref> Besides the tour, he performed at music festivals across Europe, North America, and South America. He performed at a televised concert honouring the 92nd birthday of [[Queen Elizabeth II]] on April 21, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/stars-like-tom-jones-and-kylie-minogue-shine-for-queens-92nd-birthday-party-11342015|title=Stars like Tom Jones and Kylie Minogue shine for Queen's 92nd birthday party|publisher=}}</ref> He made TV show appearances on ''[[The Late Late Show with James Corden]]'' in June where he sang one of his latest singles each night for a week.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbs.com/shows/late-late-show/news/1008442/shawn-mendes-is-moving-in/|title=Shawn Mendes Is Crashing With James Corden At The Late Late Show For A Week|accessdate=23 September 2018}}</ref> The tracks he performed live were \"Nervous\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=oN0qlGigpKg|title=Shawn Mendes:Nervous #LateLateShawn|accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref> \"Lost in Japan\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=6Diq5gWKHSE|title=Shawn Mendes:Lost In Japan #LateLateShawn|accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref> \"Perfectly Wrong\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=nc6pLSQGcHQ|title=Shawn Mendes:Perfectly Wrong #LateLateShawn|accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref> and the duet with Julia Michaels \"Like to be You\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=FnL0ubcralI|title=Shawn Mendes:Like to be You #LateLateShawn|accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref> Mendes made an appearance on the late-night talk show ''The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon'' in October and performed Lost in Japan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=xMTX50rb2LY|title=Shawn Mendes- Lost in Japan|accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref> He, together with Fallon and the show's resident band [[The Roots]], performed a special version of \"Treat You Better\" for the show's ''Classroom Instruments'' series.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://etcanada.com/news/374553/shawn-mendes-joins-jimmy-fallon-to-perform-treat-you-better-using-classroom-instruments-watch/|title=Shawn Mendes Joins Jimmy Fallon To Perform 'Treat You Better' Using Classroom Instruments \u2014 Watch!|accessdate=9 October 2018|work=ET Canada|last=Longmire|first=Becca}}</ref> He has also performed his latest singles on the [[iHeartRadio MMVAs]] in Canada on August 27, where he received eight nominations and won four awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8472211/shawn-mendes-dominates-2018-iHeartRadio-Much-Music-Video-Awards|title=Shawn Mendes Dominates iHeartRadio MMVAs 2018|work=Billboard|accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nMendes starred in a documentary directed by YouTube star [[Casey Neistat]]. The short film is part of YouTube's Artist Spotlight Story series, featuring an interview with Mendes and backstage and behind-the-scene footage of Mendes during one of his tours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capitalfm.com/artists/shawn-mendes/documentary-watch-youtube-news/|title=Shawn Mendes' New Documentary Is Confirmed: Here's Where To Watch It|work=CapitalFM|accessdate=23 September 2018}}</ref> The trailer was released on YouTube on September 22 to officially announce the upcoming documentary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=JHUCsvYlFHw|title=SHAWN MENDES \u2013 Artist Spotlight Story (Official Trailer)|accessdate=23 September 2018}}</ref> The documentary, ''Shawn Mendes \u2013 Artist Spotlight Stories'', was published on September 28.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=ZYkvxtriIrI|title=SHAWN MENDES \u2013 Artist Spotlight Stories|accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref> Ahead of the official release day, Mendes and Neistat held a previewing show of the film where selected fans of Mendes were invited for the event.\n\nThe remixed version of \"Lost in Japan\", by Russian-German DJ [[Zedd]], was released on September 27.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8477169/zedd-remix-shawn-mendes-lost-in-japan|title=Zedd Turns Shawn Mendes' 'Lost In Japan' Into a Neon Fantasy: Watch|accessdate=9 October 2018|work=Billboard|last=Bein|first=Kat}}</ref> Mendes performed the remix version of the single during the 2018 American Music Award held in Los Angeles on October 9.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/events/amas/8478128/shawn-mendes-camila-cabello-to-perform-2018-amas|title=Shawn Mendes, Zedd & Camila Cabello To Perform at 2018 American Music Awards|work=Billboard|last=Weatherby|first=Taylor|accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref> He was joined onstage by Zedd.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=CpHHzv5xGBs|title=Shawn Mendes, Zedd \u2013 Lost in Japan (Live from the AMAs / 2018)|accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref> Mendes was listed on ''Billboard'' \"21 Under 21 2018\", topping the list for the second year in a row for his chart performance, having three consecutive number one albums.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/photos/8478197/2018-21-under-21-shawn-mendes-lil-pump-billie-eilish-list|title=21 Under 21 2018: Shawn Mendes, Juice WRLD, Noah Cyrus & More|accessdate=13 October 2018|work=Billboard}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Shawn Mendes Performs \"In My Blood\" MTV VMAs in 2018 Part 4.jpg|220px|thumb|right|Mendes performs \"[[In My Blood (Shawn Mendes song)|In My Blood]]\" at the [[2018 MTV Video Music Awards]].]]\nMendes and [[Zac Brown Band]] were featured in an episode of the American TV program [[CMT Crossroads]], a show that pairs a country musician with a musician from another genre. The episode was aired on October 24 and was taped a month before the scheduled airing date. Mendes and Zac Brown Band performed nine songs, where they sang parts of each other's songs and covered [[Michael Jackson]]'s \"[[Man in the Mirror]]\". Parts of the dialogue between Mendes and Zac Brown Band, talking about music and experiences throughout their career, were shown in between the song performances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/shawn-mendes-zac-brown-band-crossroads-746292/|title=Shawn Mendes on Working With Zac Brown Band, Country-Pop Fusion|work=Rolling Stone|last=Kelly|first=Hunter|accessdate=25 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn November 1, Mendes was announced as one of the musical performers for the 2018 Victoria's Secret Fashion Show which was recorded in New York City in November and aired in December.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8482734/victorias-secret-fashion-show-2018-performers|title=Victoria's Secret Fashion Show Performers Announced: Shawn Mendes, Halsey, The Chainsmokers & More|work=Billboard|last=Bajgrowicz|first=Brooke|accessdate=3 November 2018}}</ref> He released a three-song remix EP on December 21 entitled ''The Album (Remixes)''. The EP includes remixes of songs from his self-titled album such as \"[[Where Were You in the Morning?]]\" with [[Kaytranada]], \"Why\" with [[Leon Bridges]], and \"[[Youth (Shawn Mendes song)|Youth]]\" with [[Jessie Reyez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8491239/shawn-mendes-remix-ep|title=Shawn Mendes Drops Remix EP Featuring Leon Bridges, Jessie Reyez & Kaytranada|work=Billboard|last=Bajgrowicz|first=Brooke|accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn May 3, 2019, Mendes released the single \"[[If I Can't Have You (Shawn Mendes song)|If I Can't Have You]]\" along with its music video.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/shawn-mendes-if-i-cant-have-you-new-single-831360/|title=Song You Need to Know: Shawn Mendes, 'If I Can't Have You'|accessdate=14 May 2019|magazine=RollingStone|last=Spanos|first=Brittany}}</ref> The single debuted at number two in the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100, becoming his highest charting single on the chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8511123/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-sixth-week-hot-100-number-one|title=Lil Nas X's 'Old Town Road' Rules Billboard Hot 100 for Sixth Week; Shawn Mendes, Logic & Eminem Debut in Top Fivepublisher=Billboard|accessdate=14 May 2019|last=Trust|first=Gary}}</ref> It also debuted in the top 10 in Australia and the UK, becoming his fifth top 10 single in both countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/32758/shawn-mendes/|title=Official Charts: Shawn Mendes|accessdate=14 May 2019|publisher=Official Charts}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ariacharts.com.au/news/2019/fourth-week-at-1-for-lil-nas-x-s-old-town-road|title=FOURTH WEEK AT #1 FOR LIL NAS X'S OLD TOWN ROAD, Debuts for Shawn Mendes, Logic and more!|accessdate=14 May 2019|publisher=ARIA Charts}}</ref> On July 19, he released the [[Gryffin]] remix of \"If I Can't Have You\".<ref>{{cite|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/if-i-cant-have-you-gryffin-remix-single/1473301023|title=If I Can't Have You (Gryffin Remix) - Single Shawn Mendes on Apple Music|website=[[iTunes]]|date=July 19, 2019|accessdate=July 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn June 21, 2019, he released \u201c[[Se\u00f1orita (Shawn Mendes and Camila Cabello song)|Se\u00f1orita]]\u201d with [[Cuban Americans|Cuban-American]] singer-songwriter [[Camila Cabello]], along with the music video.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/5416141/shawn-mendes-camila-cabello-single-2019/|title=Shawn Mendes, Camila Cabello release new song, video for \u2018Se\u00f1orita\u2019 - National {{!}} Globalnews.ca|date=2019-06-21|website=globalnews.ca|language=en|access-date=2019-06-21}}</ref> The song debuted at number 2 on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100 chart and marks Mendes' and Cabello's second collaboration, following \"[[I Know What You Did Last Summer (song)|I Know What You Did Last Summer]]\" released in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Shawn-Mendes/chart-history/hot-100|title=Shawn Mendes Chart History (Billboard Hot 100)|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8518516/camila-cabello-shawn-mendes-senorita-five-burning-questions|title=Five Burning Questions: Billboard Staffers Discuss Shawn Mendes and Camila Cabello's 'Senorita' No. 2 Hot 100 Debut|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref> On August 26, 2019, \"Se\u00f1orita\" ascended to the number one position, making it Mendes' first chart-topper on the Hot 100.<ref>{{cite|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8528339/shawn-mendes-camila-cabello-senorita-number-one-hot-100|title=Shawn Mendes & Camila Cabello's 'Se\u00f1orita' Hits No. 1 on Billboard Hot 100|website=[[Billboard Hot 100]]|date=August 26, 2019|accessdate=August 26, 2019}}</ref> The deluxe edition of ''Shawn Mendes'' was released on July 27, 2019, and includes the songs \"If I Can't Have You\" and \"Se\u00f1orita\".<ref>{{cite|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/shawn-mendes-deluxe/1474313635|title=Shawn Mendes (Deluxe) by Shawn Mendes on Apple Music|website=[[iTunes]]|date=July 27, 2019|accessdate=July 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Artistry and musical influences ==\nMendes has mainly been described as a [[Pop music|pop]] and [[folk-pop]] singer.<ref name=AllMusic>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/shawn-mendes-mn0003276902/discography|title=Shawn Mendes AllMusic|website=[[AllMusic]]|author=David Jeffries|accessdate=November 11, 2017}}</ref><ref name=rsilluminate /> Mendes has cited [[John Mayer]], [[Ed Sheeran]], [[Justin Timberlake]], and [[Bruno Mars]] as his main musical influences.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/shawn-mendes/news/mtv-meets-shawn-mendes|work=MTV|title=MTV Meets: Shawn Mendes |first=Jennifer|last=Lynn|date=September 2, 2014|accessdate=September 27, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"et can\"/> .Mendes also has cited [[Justin Bieber]] as a \"big early influence\" on him<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressparty.com/pg/newsdesk/shawnmendes/view/158968/|title=Shawn Mendes talks moving on from Justin Bieber influence|website=Pressparty|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>. Growing up, Mendes listened to reggae music, [[Led Zeppelin]], [[Garth Brooks]], and country music thanks to his parents.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.axs.com/news/q-a-shawn-mendes-talks-touring-musical-influences-and-having-a-no-1-al-55487|work=AXS|title=Q&A: Shawn Mendes talks touring, musical influences and having a No. 1 album|first=William|last=Pankey|date=May 27, 2015|accessdate=September 27, 2015}}</ref> He expressed that his second studio album was influenced by Mayer's work<ref name=\"et can\">{{Cite news |url=https://etcanada.com/news/169573/shawn-mendes-says-john-mayer-was-the-inspiration-behind-his-second-album/ |title=Shawn Mendes Says John Mayer Was The Inspiration Behind His Second Album |date=September 23, 2016 |work=ET Canada |accessdate=April 4, 2018}}</ref> while his third album was inspired by Timberlake, [[Kings of Leon]], [[Kanye West]], and [[Daniel Caesar]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Schiller|first=Rebecca|title=Shawn Mendes Talks Justin Timberlake-Inspired 'Lost in Japan,' Says He's 'Really Proud' of 'In My Blood': Watch|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8257664/shawn-mendes-interview-new-songs-in-my-blood-lost-in-japan-video|accessdate=March 23, 2018|work=Billboard|date=March 23, 2018}}</ref> For Brittany Spanos of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', Mendes incorporates \"catchy acoustic folk-pop tunes\" in his catalogue,<ref name=rsilluminate>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/shawn-mendes-on-grown-up-illuminate-dream-acting-role-w441215|title=Shawn Mendes on Grown-Up New LP, John Mayer's Advice, Dream Acting Role|work=Rolling Stone|date=September 23, 2016|accessdate=October 29, 2016}}</ref> while for Joe Coscarelli of ''[[The New York Times]]'', \"his soft, sometimes soulful pop-rock plays primarily to tweens and teenagers, but has also found traction on adult contemporary radio stations\".<ref name=\"tnyt\">{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/21/arts/music/shawn-mendes-illuminate-interview.html?_r=0 | title=Shawn Mendes, Pop Idol, Is Not Banking on a Gimmick | work=The New York Times | date=September 20, 2016 | accessdate=October 18, 2016}}</ref> In an interview with [[Clash (magazine)|''Clash'' magazine]], Mendes stated: <blockquote>\"I want to create anthems for people. I want to create anthems for big moments in their lives...I don't want my music to play for a few months and then go away forever. And not only that, I want to do incredible things that make a difference too. I think it's not only about the music you release, it's about the things you do while you're making the music.\"<ref name=\"Clash\">{{cite web|title=Shawn Mendes Is The First Face Of Issue 104|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/magazine/shawn-mendes-is-the-first-face-of-issue-104|website=Clash Magazine|accessdate=23 August 2017}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n== Brand endorsement and modelling ==\nMendes signed with [[Wilhelmina Models]] in 2016.<ref name=\"Shawn Mendes\">{{cite web|url=https://models.com/people/shawn-mendes|title=Shawn Mendes|website= models.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.teenvogue.com/story/shawn-mendes-modeling-contract | title=Shawn Mendes Gets Modelling Contract | work=[[Teen Vogue]] | date=January 5, 2016 | accessdate=February 27, 2016 | last=McCall|first=Tyler}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Roth|first1=Madeline|title=SHAWN MENDES IS A MODEL NOW&nbsp;\u2014 AND THESE PICS PROVE HE'S A NATURAL|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2721538/shawn-mendes-model-contract/|website=MTV News|accessdate=18 December 2018|date=4 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wilhelmina.com/talent/shawn-mendes-30074|title=Shawn Mendes \u2013 Model|website= www.wilhelmina.com}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Mendes walked the runway during the \"[[Armani|Emporio Armani]] Spring 2018\" show held in Milan, Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwd.com/fashion-news/fashion-scoops/emporio-armani-extends-partnership-shawn-mendes-1202693845/|title=Emporio Armani Extends Partnership With Shawn Mendes|publisher=WWD}}</ref> Mendes was wearing the Italian brand's new smartwatch, EA Connected, during the show. Ahead of his runway walk, the promotional video featuring Mendes was shown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7833946/shawn-mendes-emporio-armani-milan-fashion-week|title=Shawn Mendes Takes Turn on Emporio Armani Runway at Milan Fashion Week|work=Billboard|accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn June 6, 2018, Mendes was announced as the ambassador for Emporio Armani's entire \"Fall Winter 2018-2019\" watch collection. In July 2018, photographs of Mendes wearing the new EA Connected smartwatches were published on social media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8465841/shawn-mendes-emporio-armani-watch-campaign-pics-ea-connected|title=Shawn Mendes Models New Emporio Armani Watches For EA Connected Campaign|accessdate=28 October 2018|work=Billboard|last=Weatherby|first=Taylor}}</ref>\n\nOn February 16, 2019, Mendes announced that he was the latest brand ambassador for Calvin Klein's #MyCalvins campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8498744/shawn-mendes-calvin-klein-underwear-photos|title=Shawn Mendes Strips Down to His Underwear for Calvin Klein Campaign|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-02-17}}</ref> During the [[61st Annual Grammy Awards]], [[SmileDirectClub]] released an advertisement showcasing a campaign between the company and Mendes with some of the proceeds going to \"organizations that seek to improve children's health as well as mental and emotional well-being.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/shawn-mendes-smile-direct-club-partnership-1203130396/|title=Shawn Mendes to Launch SmileDirectClub Partnership With TV Spot During Grammys|magazine=Variety|author=Staff|date=6 February 2019|access-date=28 February 2019}}</ref> Later that month, Emporio Armani released a new black-and-white advertisement for its touchscreen smartwatches featuring an instrumental version of \"In My Blood\" with Mendes boxing.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8500503/shawn-mendes-armani-watch-ad-video-photos|title=Shawn Mendes Shares Steamy Ad for Armani Watches: Watch|magazine=Billboard|first=Glenn|last=Rowley|date=28 February 2019|access-date=28 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Mendes announced a partnership with Canadian-based food chain, [[Tim Hortons]], in which he features in a commercial and on beverage cups,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/why-shawn-mendes-is-taking-over-tim-hortons-coffee-cups-1.4570265|title=Why Shawn Mendes is taking over Tim Hortons coffee cups|publisher=toronto.ctvnews.ca|date=August 29, 2019}}</ref> followed by a partnership with [[Roots Canada]] in September.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/shawn-mendes-roots-tim-hortons-880065/|title=Shawn Mendes\u2019 Latest Collaborations Are the Most Canadian Thing Ever|publisher=rollingstone.com|date=September 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Philanthropy and supported causes ==\nIn 2014, Mendes and [[DoSomething.org]] launched their campaign called \"Notes from Shawn\" where fans were encouraged to write positive notes and leave them in unexpected places. The campaign was inspired by the lyrics to his first single, \"Life of the Party\", and addressed low self-esteem, depression and awareness of self-harm.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/a24633/shawn-mendes-do-something-notes-from-shawn/|work=seventeenmag|title=Join Shawn Mendes to Combat Low Self-Esteem & Spread LOVE! |first=Alex|last=Abel|date=August 28, 2014|accessdate=October 20, 2016}}</ref> They relaunched their campaign for the second year in a row in 2015, where the campaign was hashtagged online as NotesFromShawn. He partnered with BlendApp with the goal of raising up to $25,000, where $1 was raised for every signup and positive message shared on the application.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.teenvogue.com/story/shawn-mendes-notes-from-shawn-campaign |work=[[Teen Vogue]]|title=How Shawn Mendes is Spreading Happiness with Little Notes|first=Ben|last=Kassoy|date=August 13, 2015|accessdate=December 24, 2016}}</ref> The campaign was relaunched for a third year in a row in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Webster|first1=Emma Sarran|title=The One Note Shawn Mendes Wishes He Could Leave Everywhere He Goes|url=http://www.teenvogue.com/story/shawn-mendes-notes-from-shawn-papermate-campaign|website=Teen Vogue|accessdate=23 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe has also worked with [[Pencils of Promise]], a non-profit organization that builds schools and helps raise the quality of education for developing countries, raising $25,000 to build a school in [[Ghana]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.samaritanmag.com/musicians/shawn-mendes-wants-continue-making-difference-perhaps-go-africa|work=SamaritanMag|title=Shawn Mendes Wants To Continue Making a Difference, Perhaps Go to Africa |first=Karen|last=Bliss|date=November 11, 2015|accessdate=October 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, after witnessing the devastation of the [[Central Mexico earthquake|earthquake in Mexico City]], Mendes created the Mexico Earthquake Relief Fund in conjunction with the [[American Red Cross]] and donated $100,000 towards relief efforts.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tenreyro|first1=Tatiana|title=Shawn Mendes Teams Up With Red Cross For Mexico Earthquake Relief Campaign, $100,000 Already Donated|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7973742/shawn-mendes-red-cross-mexico-earthquake-donated|website=Billboard|accessdate=12 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Mendes worked with Omaze to raise funds through donations to support the WE Schools program, a movement aiming to support youth through educational services and mentorship. Mendes encouraged his fans to help the cause while giving the donors a chance to attend his upcoming concert tour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.omaze.com/experiences/hang-with-shawn-mendes?ref=shawn|title=Meet Shawn Mendes and Sit Front Row at His Show|accessdate=30 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, Mendes took part in the annual Global Citizen festival held at [[Central Park]], New York City.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/globalcitizen/news/how-watch-2018-global-citizen-festival-nyc-ncna913351|title=How to watch the 2018 Global Citizen Festival|accessdate=30 September 2018}}</ref> He performed, alongside other artists such as Janelle Mon\u00e1e, John Legend, and Janet Jackson, and raised awareness regarding the importance of education and children's lack of access to education around the world, particularly young women. Ahead of the event, he took to social media to reach out to Canada's Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]], thanking the Prime Minister for leading the initiative for Leave No Girl Behind, a movement whose goal is to empower girls through workshops and programs,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.leavenogirlbehind.org/directors-message/|title=Leave No Girl Behind International|accessdate=30 September 2018}}</ref> and expressing his willingness to talk more about the project. He also encouraged his fans to support the movement. In response, the Prime Minister thanked Mendes and stated that \"The more people we have fighting for girls' education, the better! Let's talk.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://etcanada.com/news/370734/shawn-mendes-urges-fans-to-join-him-in-supporting-leavenogirlbehind-ahead-of-global-citizen-performance/|title=Shawn Mendes Urges Fans To Join Him In Supporting #LeaveNoGirlBehind Ahead Of Global Citizen Performance|accessdate=30 September 2018|work=ET Canada}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, Mendes, together with producer Teddy Geiger, released a cover of \"[[Under Pressure]]\" by the British rock band [[Queen (band)|Queen]] and [[David Bowie]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://etcanada.com/news/375923/shawn-mendes-teams-up-with-teddy-geiger-for-cover-of-queen-bowie-classic-under-pressure/|title=Shawn Mendes Teams Up With Teddy Geiger For Cover Of Queen-Bowie Classic 'Under Pressure'|accessdate=14 October 2018|work=ET Canada}}</ref> The single was part of a series of covers of Queen's songs, released in celebration of Queen's biopic ''Bohemian Rhapsody''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/shawn-mendes-teddy-geiger-under-pressure-queen-david-bowie-736296/|title=Hear Shawn Mendes, Teddy Geiger Cover Queen's 'Under Pressure'|work=Rollong Stone|accessdate=14 October 2018}}</ref> The proceeds from the single were donated to the [[Mercury Phoenix Trust]], an organization founded by Queen bandmembers after [[Freddie Mercury]]'s death, which helps fight against HIV/AIDS.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2018/10/12/listen-now-shawn-mendes-covers-queens-under-pressure-to-bene.html|title=Listen now: Shawn Mendes covers Queen's \"Under Pressure\" to benefit fight against AIDS|accessdate=14 October 2018|work=ABC Radio}}</ref> Queen's manager, Jim Beach, expressed his gratitude to Mendes and Universal Music Group for helping the cause.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.peoplemagazine.co.za/celebrity-news/international-celebrities/shawn-mendes-teddy-geiger-cover-under-pressure-to-honour-freddie-mercury/|title=Shawn Mendes & Teddy Geiger Cover Under Pressure To Honour Freddie Mercury|accessdate=14 October 2018|work=People Magazine}}</ref>\n\nOn October 20, 2018, Mendes performed along with other artists such as Khalid, NF, Marshmello, Meghan Trainor, and Ella Mai at The Hollywood Bowl, Los Angeles for the \"We Can Survive\" event. The event was organized to raise funds for Young Survival Coalition, in an effort to support young women who were diagnosed with breast cancer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/concerts/8480938/we-can-survive-concert-2018-shawn-mendes-charlie-puth-meghan-trainor|title=Shawn Mendes, Charlie Puth, Meghan Trainor & More Team Up for 'We Can Survive' Concert|accessdate=22 October 2018|work=Billboard|last=Lenniger|first=Shea}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Mendes announced the launch of the Shawn Mendes Foundation, with the aim to \"inspire and empower his fans and today\u2019s youth to bring about positive change in the world and advocate for issues they care most about.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/5827681/shawn-mendes-foundation-audience-charity/|title=Shawn Mendes launches foundation; $1M raised to support audience issues|publisher=globalnews.ca|date=August 28, 2019}}</ref> On 8<sup>th</sup> January, 2020, Mendes announced that both he and his Shawn Mendes Foundation will be donating an undisclosed sum of money to causes including Australia's Red Cross, the New South Wales Rural Fire Service, and South Australia Country Fire Service, to help ease the strain on those impacted by the devastating fires that are tearing through parts of the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-xl/lifestyle/celebs/shawn-mendes-donates-to-australia-wildfire-relief-efforts/ar-BBYLcod?li=BBKhQr3&ocid=wispr|title=Shawn Mendes donates to Australia wildfire relief efforts|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nMendes has been open about his struggles with [[anxiety disorder|anxiety]], which he disclosed publicly through \"[[In My Blood (Shawn Mendes song)|In My Blood]]\", a track from his third studio album. He declared that he had been undergoing therapy in order to help him deal with the mental health condition, stating:\n{{quote|I spoke to a therapist a couple of times [...] Therapy is what works for you. Therapy is listening to music and running on the treadmill, therapy is going to dinner with your friends\u2014it's something that distracts you, that helps you heal and so it just depends on what you think therapy is. I made a conscious effort to be more connected to the people in my life. I found I was closing myself off from everybody, thinking that would help me battle it then realizing the only way I was going to battle it was completely opening up and letting people in.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/shawn-mendes-undergoes-therapy-to-cure-anxiety-118042100102_1.html |title=Shawn Mendes undergoes therapy to cure anxiety |date=April 21, 2018 |work=[[Business Standard]] |accessdate=April 22, 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nWith regard to speculation about his [[Sexual orientation|sexuality]], Mendes stated, \"First of all, I'm not gay. Second of all, it shouldn't make a difference if I was or if I wasn't. The focus should be on the music and not my sexuality.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Real |first1=Evan |title=Shawn Mendes Responds to Rumors About His Sexuality |url=https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/shawn-mendes-responds-to-rumors-about-his-sexuality-w211236/ |accessdate=27 November 2018 |work=Us Weekly |date=24 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Brammer |first1=John Paul |title=Let Shawn Mendes Be Heterosexual in Peace |url=https://www.them.us/story/shawn-mendes-is-heterosexual |accessdate=27 November 2018 |work=them. |date=9 May 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Doyle |first1=Patrick |title=Shawn Mendes: Confessions of a Neurotic Teen Idol |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/shawn-mendes-cover-interview-756847/ |accessdate=27 November 2018 |work=Rolling Stone |date=26 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nSince July 2019, he has been dating Cuban-American singer [[Camila Cabello]]. However, the relationship has garnered controversy, as both were accused of attempting to [[Publicity stunt|form a relationship for publicity]],<ref name=\"Capital 2019\">{{cite web |title=Inside Shawn Mendes and Camila Cabello's relationship |website=Capital FM |date=2019-09-12 |url=https://www.capitalfm.com/artists/shawn-mendes/camila-cabello-dating-relationship/ |access-date=2019-10-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/sep/13/camila-cabello-shawn-mendes-romance-real-j-lo-drake |title=Bad fauxmance: when celebrity couples become PR stunts |last=Cooper |first=Leonie |date=September 13, 2019 |website=The Guardian |language=en-GB |access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Bonner 2019\">{{cite web |last=Bonner |first=Mehera |title=Shawn Mendes and Camila Cabello's Relationship Timeline |website=Cosmopolitan.com |date=2019-07-30 |url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/entertainment/celebs/amp28551280/shawn-mendes-camila-cabello-relationship-timeline/ |access-date=2019-10-10}}</ref> but Mendes insisted it is \"definitely not a publicity stunt\".<ref name=\"Elle\">{{cite web |last=Bailey |first=Alyssa |title=Shawn Mendes Wants You To Know His Relationship With Camila Cabello Is 'Not A Publicity Stunt'|website=elle.com |date=2019-09-19 |url=https://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/a29122311/shawn-mendes-camila-cabello-kissing-date-fake-relationship-response/ |access-date=2019-10-20}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Shawn Mendes}}\nMendes has received several nominations and awards. He won 13 [[Society of Composers, Authors and Music Publishers of Canada]] (SOCAN) awards, 11 [[MTV Europe Music Awards]] (EMA), eight [[iHeartRadio Much Music Video Awards]] (MMVA), eight [[Juno Award]]s, three [[BMI Awards]], three [[American Music Award]]s, two [[MTV Video Music Award]]s, and the Allan Slaight Honour from [[Canada's Walk of Fame]]. He was nominated for three [[Grammy Award]]s.\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Films roles\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Roles !! Notes\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Metegol]]''\n| Young Jake (voice)\n| English dub; direct to video\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Television roles\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Roles !! Notes\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Yo quisiera''\n| Himself\n| Episode: \"Yo soy la bloguera de moda\"\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2016\n| ''[[The 100 (TV series)|The 100]]''\n| Macallan\n| Episode: \"Wanheda: Part 1\"\n|-\n| ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''\n|rowspan=3|Himself\n|Episode: \"[[Emma Stone]]/Shawn Mendes\"\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Drop the Mic]]''\n| Episode: \"[[Odell Beckham Jr]]. vs. Shawn Mendes / [[Molly Ringwald]] vs. [[Jon Cryer]]\"\n|-\n|2019\n| ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''\n|Episode: \"[[Adam Sandler]]/Shawn Mendes\"\n|-\n|}\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Shawn Mendes discography|List of songs recorded by Shawn Mendes|l2 = songs}}\n* ''[[Handwritten (Shawn Mendes album)|Handwritten]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Illuminate (Shawn Mendes album)|Illuminate]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Shawn Mendes (album)|Shawn Mendes]]'' (2018)\n\n== Tours ==\n=== Headlining ===\n* [[Shawn's First Headlines|#ShawnsFirstHeadlines]] (2014\u20132015)\n* [[Shawn Mendes World Tour]] (2016)\n* [[Illuminate World Tour]] (2017)\n* [[Shawn Mendes: The Tour]] (2019)\n\n=== Co-headlining ===\n* [[Jingle Ball Tour 2014]] (with various artists) (2014)\n* Jingle Ball Tour 2015 (with various artists) (2015)\n* Jingle Ball Tour 2018 (with various artists) (2018)\n\n=== Supporting ===\n* [[Austin Mahone: Live on Tour]] ([[Austin Mahone]]) (North America) (2014)\n* [[The 1989 World Tour]] ([[Taylor Swift]]) (North America) (2015)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links\n|collapsible=yes\n|wikt=no\n|c=Category:Shawn Mendes\n|n=no\n|q=Shawn Mendes\n|s=no\n|author=no\n|b=no\n|v=no\n}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.shawnmendesofficial.com/}}\n* {{IMDb name|6658398}}\n* {{Twitter|ShawnMendes}}\n* {{Instagram|shawnmendes}}\n\n{{Shawn Mendes}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mendes, Shawn}}\n[[Category:Shawn Mendes| ]]\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian pianists]]\n[[Category:Canadian child singers]]\n[[Category:Canadian male singers]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Portuguese descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian pop guitarists]]\n[[Category:Canadian male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Canadian pop pianists]]\n[[Category:Canadian pop singers]]\n[[Category:Child pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Toronto]]\n[[Category:People from Pickering, Ontario]]\n[[Category:MTV EMA winners]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for Single of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Juno Fan Choice Award winners]]\n[[Category:Canadian male pianists]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for Pop Album of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for Album of the Year winners]]\n", "name_user": "Jennythute678", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shawn_Mendes"}
{"title_page": "Kamran Abbasi", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical person\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Kamran Abbasi\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| image             = \n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = <!-- only use if different from name above -->\n| birth_date        = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> \n| birth_place       = [[Lahore]], Pakistan\n| death_date        = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)  -->\n| death_place       = \n| death_cause       = \n| nationality       = \n| citizenship       = \n| education         = *[[Oakwood High School, Rotherham|Oakwood School]]\n*[[Thomas Rotherham College]]\n*[[Leeds School of Medicine]]\n| occupation        = *Editor of the ''[[Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine]]''\n*Executive editor of the ''[[The BMJ|British Medical Journal]]''\n| years_active      = \n| known_for         = *[[Editing]]\n*[[Global health]]\n*[[E-learning]]\n*[[Sports journalism|Writer on cricket]]\n*[[Journalism]]\n| relations         = \n| website           = \n| profession        = [[Physician]]\n| field             = \n| work_institutions = \n| specialism        = \n| research_field    = [[Internal medicine|Medicine]]\n| notable_works     = \n| prizes            = \n| child             = \n| module2           = \n| signature         = \n}}\n'''Kamran Abbasi''' is a [[physician]], [[visiting professor]] at [[Imperial College]], London,<ref name=Imperial>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imperial.ac.uk/school-public-health/primary-care-and-public-health/people/|title=People {{!}} Faculty of Medicine {{!}} Imperial College London|last=|first=|date=|website=www.imperial.ac.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> executive editor of the ''[[The BMJ|British Medical Journal]]'' ''(BMJ)'', editor of the ''[[Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine]]'' ''(JRSM)'', journalist, [[Sports journalism|cricket writer]] and broadcaster.\n\nRaised in Yorkshire, he graduated in medicine from [[Leeds School of Medicine]] in 1992 and worked in [[internal medicine|general medicine]] before commencing a career in journal editing in 1997, beginning with the ''BMJ'', followed by the ''[[Bulletin of the World Health Organization]]'' and later the ''JRSM''. He is an honorary senior lecturer at the Department of Primary Care, [[Imperial College School of Medicine|Imperial College]], London, and a fellow of the [[Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh]] and the [[Royal College of Physicians of London]].\n\nHe has been a consultant editor for ''[[PLOS Medicine]]'' and has created [[e-learning]] resources for [[continuous professional development|professional development]] of doctors, including [[BMJ Learning]] and the [[Royal Society of Medicine]]'s video lecture service.\n\nIn addition, he is a writer on cricket and in 2012 authored ''Zindabad; The English Chronicles: a Modern History of Pakistan Cricket''.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nKamran Abbasi was born in [[Lahore]], Pakistan and raised in Yorkshire.<ref name=Abbasi2006>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2006/aug/20/cricket.comment|title=Cricket: British Asians in cricket|last=Abbasi|first=Kamran|date=19 August 2006|work=The Observer|access-date=19 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> He completed his early education at [[Oakwood High School, Rotherham|Oakwood School]] before attending the [[Thomas Rotherham College]], both in Rotherham, South Yorkshire. In 1992, he graduated in medicine from [[Leeds School of Medicine]].<ref name=Lancet2004>{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=August 2004|title=Kamran Abbasi|url=https://www.thelancet.com/action/showPdf?pii=S0140-6736%2804%2916877-3|journal=The Lancet|language=English|volume=364|issue=9435|pages=657|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(04)16877-3|issn=0140-6736|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn 1997, following five years in [[internal medicine]] in both Yorkshire and London,<ref name=Lancet2004/><ref name=BMJBio>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bmj.com/about-bmj/editorial-staff/kamran-abbasi|title=Kamran Abbasi {{!}} The British Medial Journal|website=www.bmj.com|access-date=18 July 2019}}</ref> he joined the ''[[British Medical Journal|BMJ]]'' from the [[Royal London Hospital|Royal London]] and [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]]s. He took up the post of editorial registrar and then assistant editor, before becoming deputy editor in 2002 and acting editor in 2004.<ref name=Lancet2004/> He was influenced by [[Richard Smith (editor)]].<ref name=Lancet2004/>\n\n===Global health and politics===\nIn 1999, he published a series of six articles in the ''BMJ'' looking at the role of the [[World Bank]] in [[global health]].<ref name=Simmons2012>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=hgqVCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA422&dq=who+kamran+abbasi#v=onepage&q=who%20kamran%20abbasi&f=false|title=Managing Global Issues: Lessons Learned|last=Simmons|first=P. J.|last2=Oudraat|first2=Chantal de Jonge|date=2012|publisher=Brookings Institution Press|isbn=9780870033360|language=en}}</ref><ref name=Stott1999>{{Cite journal|last=Stott|first=Robin|date=1999|title=The World Bank: Friend or foe to the Poor?|journal=BMJ: British Medical Journal|volume=318|issue=7187|pages=822\u2013823|issn=0959-8138|jstor=25184112|doi=10.1136/bmj.318.7187.822|pmid=10092238|pmc=1115258}}{{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=Incite2006>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=KNLhDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT278&dq=israel+kamran+abbasi#v=onepage&q=abbasi&f=false|title=Color of Violence: The INCITE! Anthology|last=|first=|date=2006|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=9780822363057|location=|pages=28|language=en}}</ref> A year later, he was appointed editor of the ''[[Bulletin of the World Health Organization]]''.<ref name=Lancet2004/><ref name=Ferriman2004>{{cite journal|last=Ferriman|first=Annabel|date=15 July 2004|title=BMJ group appoints acting editor and acting chief executive|journal=BMJ|volume=329|issue=7458|pages=128.3|doi=10.1136/bmj.329.7458.128-b|pmc=478251|issn=0959-8138}}</ref>\n\nAbassi became the BMJ's executive editor for content, developing the journal's expansion internationally, digitally, and in print,<ref name=BMJBio/> particularly the ''BMJ'' International editions,<ref name=DebatingMatters/> which he considers his greatest achievement.<ref name=Lancet2004/> The first of the themed issues was in 2003,<ref name=BMJTheme2003>{{Cite journal|last=Group|first=British Medical Journal Publishing|date=2003-01-18|title=Forthcoming BMJ theme issues (provisional dates and titles)|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/326/7381/160|journal=BMJ|language=en|volume=326|issue=7381|pages=160|doi=10.1136/bmj.326.7381.160|issn=0959-8138|pmc=1125240}}</ref> and shortly after, he was one of the three main organisers of the ''BMJ\u2019s'' first international theme issue on South Asia, where investment in [[primary care]] and particularly the education of girls in Sri Lanka and Kerala was shown to be beneficial.<ref name=Smith2004>{{Cite journal|last=Smith|first=Richard|date=1 April 2004|title=Towards a global social contract|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/328/7443/0.8|journal=BMJ|language=en|volume=328|issue=7443|pages=|doi=10.1136/bmj.328.7443.0-g|issn=0959-8138|via=|pmc=383356}}</ref> Their interest and continued work in South Asia has led to the ''BMJ'' offering a dedicated page to South Asia on their website since 2013.<ref name=Bhutta2016>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bmj.com/about-bmj/editorial-staff/bmj-south-asia|title=BMJ in South Asia {{!}} The BMJ|website=www.bmj.com|access-date=20 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2004, while he was acting editor of the ''BMJ'', Abbasi became the recipient of a sudden flood of responses to a ''BMJ'' article written by [[Derek Summerfield]], who published his personal view over what he saw as organised violations of the [[fourth Geneva Convention]] by the Israeli army in Gaza and their effects on public health. The reaction to that article was later analysed by [[Karl Sabbagh]] and revealed the hostility that editors can receive when publishing on a sensitive issue.<ref name=Sabbagh2009>{{cite journal|last=Sabbagh|first=Karl|date=25 February 2009|title=Perils of criticising Israel|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/338/bmj.a2066|journal=[[British Medical Journal]]|volume=338|pages=a2066|doi=10.1136/bmj.a2066|issn=0959-8138|pmid=19244219}}</ref> In response to the messages sent to the journal's website and the over 1000 emails sent directly to Abbasi, a sample number were published on-line within 24 hours of submission. Sabbagh explained that the published messages \"were a skewed sample of what had been received, as abusive and obscene contributions were not posted\",<ref name=Sabbagh2009/> In response to these messages, many of which \"abused the ''BMJ'' or Abbasi personally\",<ref name=Sabbagh2009/> Abbasi published an editorial entitled: \u201cShould journals mix medicine and politics?\u201d Abbasi noted that the messages were \"largely biased and inflammatory on both sides\"<ref name=Feldman2014>{{Cite journal|last=Feldman|first=Arthur M.|date=October 2014|title=Mixing Politics and Medicine: A Case Study|journal=Clinical and Translational Science|volume=7|issue=5|pages=351\u2013353|doi=10.1111/cts.12233|issn=1752-8054|pmc=5350878|pmid=25348106}}</ref> and that a number of people felt that dialogue could resolve the conflict. He specified that \u201cin a state of conflict [those] views will be sometime abrasive and unpalatable\" and argued that medicine cannot exist in a political void.<ref name=Sabbagh2009/><ref name=Feldman2014/>\n\n===E-learning===\nHe founded [[BMJ Learning]], an e-learning resource.<ref name=DebatingMatters/>\n\n===''Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine''===\nAbbasi has been editor of the ''[[Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine]]'' since 2005.<ref name=DebatingMatters/><ref name=Sokol2012>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iN3fK8aI62kC&pg=PA36&dq=kamran+abbasi+sokol#v=onepage&q=kamran%20abbasi%20sokol&f=false|title=Doing Clinical Ethics: A Hands-on Guide for Clinicians and Others|last=Sokol|first=Daniel K.|date=2011|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=9789400727823|location=|pages=36\u201337|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Other roles==\nHe is also an honorary senior lecturer at the Department of Primary Care, [[Imperial College School of Medicine|Imperial College]], London, member of the General Advisory Council of the [[King's Fund]], a Fellow of the [[Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh]] and the [[Royal College of Physicians of London]], and patron of the [[South Asian Health Foundation]]. He is a Fellow of the [[Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh]] and the [[Royal College of Physicians of London]].<ref name=BMJBio/><ref name=ESPNcricinfo>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.cricinfo.com/pakspin/|title=ESPNcricinfo - Cricket Teams, Scores, Stats, News, Fixtures, Results, Tables|website=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=2018-09-03}}</ref>\n\nHe has been a consultant editor for ''[[PLOS Medicine]]'' and has created three e-learning resources for [[continuous professional development|professional development]] of doctors, including [[BMJ Learning]] and the [[Royal Society of Medicine]]'s video lecture service.<ref name=BMJBio/>\n\nHe has consulted for a number of organisations including [[Harvard University]], the [[NHS]], the [[World Health Organization]] and [[McKinsey & Company|McKinsey & Co]].<ref name=BMJBio/>\n\nHe has also made contributions on radio and television,<ref name=BMJBio/> particularly with [[Mark Porter (general practitioner)|Mark Porter]]. In this role, Abbasi has acted as a sceptic to [[BBC Radio 4]]'s weekly medical programme, Inside Health.<ref name=BBCRadio4>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01n65zl|title=BBC Radio 4 - Inside Health, Stem cells, Functional disorders, Epilepsy, Stoptober, Whiplash|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=19 July 2019}}</ref> He also writes for ''[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]'', a Pakistani English-language newspaper.<ref name=DebatingMatters/>\n\n==Cricket==\nFollowing cricket since the 1970s, Abbasi has been an international writer on Pakistan cricket since 1996, starting as a blogger for [[Cricinfo.com]] with a blog called Pak Spin, and with a particular interest in the politics of cricket.<ref name=Indie/><ref name=Ezekiel2011>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=s5MkBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA92&dq=Kamran+abbasi+cricket#v=onepage&q=Kamran%20abbasi%20cricket&f=false|title=Cricket and Beyond|last=Ezekiel|first=Gulu|date=2011|publisher=Prabhat Prakashan|isbn=9788184301007|location=|pages=92|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=zO3VL4ybLQwC&pg=PA234&dq=Kamran+abbasi+cricket#v=onepage&q=Kamran%20abbasi%20&f=false|title=Cricket, Lovely Cricket?: An Addict's Guide to the World's Most Exasperating Game|last=Booth|first=Lawrence|date=2008|publisher=Yellow Jersey Press|isbn=9780224079143|location=|pages=234|language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe was the first Asian columnist in an English cricket publication when he started writing for [[Wisden Cricket Monthly]].<ref name=DebatingMatters>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.debatingmatters.com/people/kamran_abbasi/|title=Debating Matters - People - Kamran Abbasi|website=archive.debatingmatters.com|language=en|access-date=19 July 2019}}</ref>{{when|date=July 2019}} In 2000, in one ''Wisden Cricket'' entry, he reported on [[Hansie Cronje]] and the [[South Africa cricket match fixing]] and responded by saying that the \"enigma of match fixing will remain. But the reflex judgement that white is good and brown is bad is now less sustainable than it ever was. For that at least, thank you, Hansie\".<ref name=Vahed2013>{{Cite journal|last=Vahed|first=Goolam|date=July 2013|title=Cricket and corruption: the post-apartheid relationship between India and South Africa within and beyond the boundary|journal=Diaspora Studies|language=en|volume=6|issue=2|pages=80\u201391|doi=10.1080/09739572.2013.853439|issn=0973-9572}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, he co-authored a paper on the influence of a [[1986 Austral-Asia Cup Final|1986 Pakistani victory in cricket over India]] on subsequent matches up to 2003.<ref name=\"Vorocek2006\">{{Cite journal|last=Voracek|first=Martin|last2=Formann|first2=Anton K.|date=April 2006|title=The Miandad Effect Reconsidered: Analysis of Pakistan's Cricket Performance 1952 to 2005|journal=Perceptual and Motor Skills|language=en-US|volume=102|issue=2|pages=323\u2013326|doi=10.2466/pms.102.2.323-326|pmid=16826652|issn=0031-5125}}</ref> Later, in 2012, he published a book titled ''The English Chronicles: Zindabad: A Modern History of Pakistan Cricket''.<ref name=Indie>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiebound.org/book/9781475100525|title=Zindabad: The English Chronicles: Zindabad: A Modern History of Pakistan Cricket {{!}} IndieBound.org|website=www.indiebound.org|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n===Articles===\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1136/bmj.317.7172.1599c | volume=317 | title=Film: The Knowledge of Healing | year=1998 | journal=BMJ | page=1599 | last1 = Culliford | first1 = L.}}\n*{{cite journal | year = 1999 | title = The World Bank and World Health | url = https://www.bmj.com/content/bmj/318/7187/865.full.pdf | format = PDF | journal = British Medical Journal | volume = 318 | issue = | page = 865 | doi = 10.1136/bmj.318.7187.865  | last1 = Abbasi | first1 = K.}}\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1136/bmj.328.7443.800 | volume=328 | title=India versus Pakistan and the power of a six: an analysis of cricket results | year=2004 | journal=BMJ | page=800 | last1 = Abbasi | first1 = Kamran | last2 = Khan | first2 = Khalid S}}  \n*{{cite journal | pmid = 24965786 | doi=10.1136/bmj.g4184 | volume=348 | title=Corruption: medicine's dirty open secret | year=2014 | journal=BMJ | page=g4184  | last1 = Jain | first1 = A | last2 = Nundy | first2 = S | last3 = Abbasi | first3 = K}}.\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1136/bmj.329.7474.0-g | volume=329 | title=Should journals mix medicine and politics? | year=2004 | journal=BMJ | last1 = Abbasi | first1 = Kamran}}\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1177/0141076817720629 | volume=110 | title=A future of technology and other humans | year=2017 | journal=Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine | page=263 | last1 = Abbasi | first1 = Kamran}}\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1177/0141076818782032 | volume=111 | title=How to fund the NHS | year=2018 | journal=Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine | page=187 | last1 = Abbasi | first1 = Kamran}}\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1136/bmj.l348 | title=We need fewer leaders and more followers | year=2019 | journal=BMJ | page=l348 | last1 = Abbasi | first1 = Kamran}}\n\n===''BMJ'' theme issues===\n*[https://www.bmj.com/content/326/7381/160 \"Forthcoming BMJ theme issues\"]. ''British Medical Journal'' 18 January 2003; 326 {{doi|10.1136/bmj.326.7381.160}}\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC259154/ \"Why a special issue of the BMJ on South Asia?\"]. Co-authored with Zuliqar A Bhutta and Samiran Nundy. ''British Medical Journal'' 25 October 2003; 327(7421): 941\u2013942. {{doi|10.1136/bmj.327.7421.941}}\n*[https://www.bmj.com/content/328/7443/0.1 \u201cMaternal and child health vital to progress of South Asia\u201d]. ''British Medical Journal'' 1 April 2004. {{doi|10.1136/bmj.328.7443.0}}\n*[https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/25cf/108d6770ac2e10cca4d616af735c42d47e7a.pdf \u201cTwelve years on: a call for papers for another special collection of articles on South Asia\u201d]. Co-authored with Zuliqar A Bhutta and Samiran Nundy. BMJ 10 June 2016. 2016;353:i3252 {{doi|10.1136/bmj.i3252}}\n\n===Journalism===\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/1999/aug/25/cricket5 \"East or West, Nasser's best\"]. An extract from a piece in the Wisden Cricket.  ''The Guardian'' 25 August 1999\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2006/aug/20/cricket.comment \"United Front\"]. ''[[The Guardian]]'', 20 August 2006\n\n===Books===\n*[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=kcmiuAAACAAJ&dq=kamran+abbasi&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjv4rqy-77jAhWzoFwKHcGiBn0Q6AEIKDAA Zindabad: The English Chronicles: a Modern History of Pakistan Cricket]. Createspace Independent Pub, 2012. {{ISBN|9781475100525}}\n\n====Book chapter====\n*[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=zghkDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT2&dq=Kamran+abbasi+cricket&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjkqZyu4sHjAhXbh1wKHf_aBW0Q6AEIQDAF#v=onepage&q=Kamran%20&f=false \"Younis Khan\"] in ''The Shorter Wisden 2017: The Best Writing from Wisden Cricketers' Almanack 2017'' edited by Lawrence Booth\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[https://www.bmj.com/content/329/7471/924.full?ijkey=c7b88fe81cf2cba4710713e3fed9e54a3c506f68&keytype2=tf_ipsecsha&eaf= \u201cPalestine: the assault on health and other war crimes\u201d], Derek Summerfield, ''BMJ'' 2004; 329 {{doi|10.1136/bmj.329.7471.924}}\n*[https://www.bmj.com/content/suppl/2010/01/08/329.7471.924.DC1/Emails_to_editor.pdf \"Emails sent to acting editor, Kamran Abbasi, about \u201cPalestine: the assault on health and other war crimes\u201d between 16 October 2004 and 15:03, 15 November 2004\"]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.thenightwatchman.net/news/editors-choice-issue-20 The Night Watchman], Wisden's Cricket\n*[https://www.dawn.com/authors/1154/kamran-abbasi \u2018\u2019Dawn\u2019\u2019], publications\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abbasi, Kamran}}\n[[Category:English people of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Leeds]]\n[[Category:British medical writers]]\n[[Category:Pakistani medical writers]]\n[[Category:Cricket historians and writers]]\n[[Category:Medical journal editors]]\n[[Category:Pakistani sportswriters]]\n[[Category:Science bloggers]]\n[[Category:Pakistani bloggers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British journalists of Pakistani descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical person\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Kamran Abbasi\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| image             = \n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = <!-- only use if different from name above -->\n| birth_date        = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> \n| birth_place       = [[Lahore]], Pakistan\n| death_date        = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)  -->\n| death_place       = \n| death_cause       = \n| nationality       = \n| citizenship       = \n| education         = *[[Oakwood High School, Rotherham|Oakwood School]]\n*[[Thomas Rotherham College]]\n*[[Leeds School of Medicine]]\n| occupation        = *Editor of the ''[[Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine]]''\n*Executive editor of the ''[[The BMJ|British Medical Journal]]''\n| years_active      = \n| known_for         = *[[Editing]]\n*[[Global health]]\n*[[E-learning]]\n*[[Sports journalism|Writer on cricket]]\n*[[Journalism]]\n| relations         = \n| website           = \n| profession        = [[Physician]]\n| field             = \n| work_institutions = \n| specialism        = \n| research_field    = [[Internal medicine|Medicine]]\n| notable_works     = \n| prizes            = \n| child             = \n| module2           = \n| signature         = \n}}\n'''Kamran Abbasi''' is a [[physician]], [[visiting professor]] at [[Imperial College]], London,<ref name=Imperial>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imperial.ac.uk/school-public-health/primary-care-and-public-health/people/|title=People {{!}} Faculty of Medicine {{!}} Imperial College London|last=|first=|date=|website=www.imperial.ac.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> executive editor of the ''[[The BMJ|British Medical Journal]]'' ''(BMJ)'', editor of the ''[[Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine]]'' ''(JRSM)'', journalist, [[Sports journalism|cricket writer]] and broadcaster.\n\nRaised in Yorkshire, he graduated in medicine from [[Leeds School of Medicine]] in 1992 and worked in [[internal medicine|general medicine]] before commencing a career in journal editing in 1997, beginning with the ''BMJ'', followed by the ''[[Bulletin of the World Health Organization]]'' and later the ''JRSM''. He is an honorary senior lecturer at the Department of Primary Care, [[Imperial College School of Medicine|Imperial College]], London, and a fellow of the [[Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh]] and the [[Royal College of Physicians of London]].\n\nHe has been a consultant editor for ''[[PLOS Medicine]]'' and has created [[e-learning]] resources for [[continuous professional development|professional development]] of doctors, including [[BMJ Learning]] and the [[Royal Society of Medicine]]'s video lecture service.\n\nIn addition, he is a writer on cricket and in 2012 authored ''Zindabad; The English Chronicles: a Modern History of Pakistan Cricket''.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nKamran Abbasi was born in [[Lahore]], Pakistan and raised in Yorkshire.<ref name=Abbasi2006>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2006/aug/20/cricket.comment|title=Cricket: British Asians in cricket|last=Abbasi|first=Kamran|date=19 August 2006|work=The Observer|access-date=19 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> He completed his early education at [[Oakwood High School, Rotherham|Oakwood School]] before attending the [[Thomas Rotherham College]], both in Rotherham, South Yorkshire. In 1992, he graduated in medicine from [[Leeds School of Medicine]].<ref name=Lancet2004>{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=August 2004|title=Kamran Abbasi|url=https://www.thelancet.com/action/showPdf?pii=S0140-6736%2804%2916877-3|journal=The Lancet|language=English|volume=364|issue=9435|pages=657|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(04)16877-3|issn=0140-6736|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn 1997, following five years in [[internal medicine]] in both Yorkshire and London,<ref name=Lancet2004/><ref name=BMJBio>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bmj.com/about-bmj/editorial-staff/kamran-abbasi|title=Kamran Abbasi {{!}} The British Medial Journal|website=www.bmj.com|access-date=18 July 2019}}</ref> he joined the ''[[British Medical Journal|BMJ]]'' from the [[Royal London Hospital|Royal London]] and [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]]s. He took up the post of editorial registrar and then assistant editor, before becoming deputy editor in 2002 and acting editor in 2004.<ref name=Lancet2004/> He was influenced by [[Richard Smith (editor)]].<ref name=Lancet2004/>\n\n===Global health and politics===\nIn 1999, he published a series of six articles in the ''BMJ'' looking at the role of the [[World Bank]] in [[global health]].<ref name=Simmons2012>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=hgqVCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA422&dq=who+kamran+abbasi#v=onepage&q=who%20kamran%20abbasi&f=false|title=Managing Global Issues: Lessons Learned|last=Simmons|first=P. J.|last2=Oudraat|first2=Chantal de Jonge|date=2012|publisher=Brookings Institution Press|isbn=9780870033360|language=en}}</ref><ref name=Stott1999>{{Cite journal|last=Stott|first=Robin|date=1999|title=The World Bank: Friend or foe to the Poor?|journal=BMJ: British Medical Journal|volume=318|issue=7187|pages=822\u2013823|issn=0959-8138|jstor=25184112|doi=10.1136/bmj.318.7187.822|pmid=10092238|pmc=1115258}}{{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=Incite2006>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=KNLhDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT278&dq=israel+kamran+abbasi#v=onepage&q=abbasi&f=false|title=Color of Violence: The INCITE! Anthology|last=|first=|date=2006|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=9780822363057|location=|pages=28|language=en}}</ref> A year later, he was appointed editor of the ''[[Bulletin of the World Health Organization]]''.<ref name=Lancet2004/><ref name=Ferriman2004>{{cite journal|last=Ferriman|first=Annabel|date=15 July 2004|title=BMJ group appoints acting editor and acting chief executive|journal=BMJ|volume=329|issue=7458|pages=128.3|doi=10.1136/bmj.329.7458.128-b|pmc=478251|issn=0959-8138}}</ref>\n\nAbassi became the BMJ's executive editor for content, developing the journal's expansion internationally, digitally, and in print,<ref name=BMJBio/> particularly the ''BMJ'' International editions,<ref name=DebatingMatters/> which he considers his greatest achievement.<ref name=Lancet2004/> The first of the themed issues was in 2003,<ref name=BMJTheme2003>{{Cite journal|last=Group|first=British Medical Journal Publishing|date=2003-01-18|title=Forthcoming BMJ theme issues (provisional dates and titles)|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/326/7381/160|journal=BMJ|language=en|volume=326|issue=7381|pages=160|doi=10.1136/bmj.326.7381.160|issn=0959-8138|pmc=1125240}}</ref> and shortly after, he was one of the three main organisers of the ''BMJ\u2019s'' first international theme issue on South Asia, where investment in [[primary care]] and particularly the education of girls in Sri Lanka and Kerala was shown to be beneficial.<ref name=Smith2004>{{Cite journal|last=Smith|first=Richard|date=1 April 2004|title=Towards a global social contract|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/328/7443/0.8|journal=BMJ|language=en|volume=328|issue=7443|pages=|doi=10.1136/bmj.328.7443.0-g|issn=0959-8138|via=|pmc=383356}}</ref> Their interest and continued work in South Asia has led to the ''BMJ'' offering a dedicated page to South Asia on their website since 2013.<ref name=Bhutta2016>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bmj.com/about-bmj/editorial-staff/bmj-south-asia|title=BMJ in South Asia {{!}} The BMJ|website=www.bmj.com|access-date=20 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2004, while he was acting editor of the ''BMJ'', Abbasi became the recipient of a sudden flood of responses to a ''BMJ'' article written by [[Derek Summerfield]], who published his personal view over what he saw as organised violations of the [[fourth Geneva Convention]] by the Israeli army in Gaza and their effects on public health. The reaction to that article was later analysed by [[Karl Sabbagh]] and revealed the hostility that editors can receive when publishing on a sensitive issue.<ref name=Sabbagh2009>{{cite journal|last=Sabbagh|first=Karl|date=25 February 2009|title=Perils of criticising Israel|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/338/bmj.a2066|journal=[[British Medical Journal]]|volume=338|pages=a2066|doi=10.1136/bmj.a2066|issn=0959-8138|pmid=19244219}}</ref> In response to the messages sent to the journal's website and the over 1000 emails sent directly to Abbasi, a sample number were published on-line within 24 hours of submission. Sabbagh explained that the published messages \"were a skewed sample of what had been received, as abusive and obscene contributions were not posted\",<ref name=Sabbagh2009/> In response to these messages, many of which \"abused the ''BMJ'' or Abbasi personally\",<ref name=Sabbagh2009/> Abbasi published an editorial entitled: \u201cShould journals mix medicine and politics?\u201d Abbasi noted that the messages were \"largely biased and inflammatory on both sides\"<ref name=Feldman2014>{{Cite journal|last=Feldman|first=Arthur M.|date=October 2014|title=Mixing Politics and Medicine: A Case Study|journal=Clinical and Translational Science|volume=7|issue=5|pages=351\u2013353|doi=10.1111/cts.12233|issn=1752-8054|pmc=5350878|pmid=25348106}}</ref> and that a number of people felt that dialogue could resolve the conflict. He specified that \u201cin a state of conflict [those] views will be sometime abrasive and unpalatable\" and argued that medicine cannot exist in a political void.<ref name=Sabbagh2009/><ref name=Feldman2014/>\n\n===E-learning===\nHe founded [[BMJ Learning]], an e-learning resource.<ref name=DebatingMatters/>\n\n===''Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine''===\nAbbasi has been editor of the ''[[Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine]]'' since 2005.<ref name=DebatingMatters/><ref name=Sokol2012>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iN3fK8aI62kC&pg=PA36&dq=kamran+abbasi+sokol#v=onepage&q=kamran%20abbasi%20sokol&f=false|title=Doing Clinical Ethics: A Hands-on Guide for Clinicians and Others|last=Sokol|first=Daniel K.|date=2011|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=9789400727823|location=|pages=36\u201337|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Other roles==\nHe is also an honorary senior lecturer at the Department of Primary Care, [[Imperial College School of Medicine|Imperial College]], London, member of the General Advisory Council of the [[King's Fund]], a Fellow of the [[Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh]] and the [[Royal College of Physicians of London]], and patron of the [[South Asian Health Foundation]]. He is a Fellow of the [[Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh]] and the [[Royal College of Physicians of London]].<ref name=BMJBio/><ref name=ESPNcricinfo>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.cricinfo.com/pakspin/|title=ESPNcricinfo - Cricket Teams, Scores, Stats, News, Fixtures, Results, Tables|website=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=2018-09-03}}</ref>\n\nHe has been a consultant editor for ''[[PLOS Medicine]]'' and has created three e-learning resources for [[continuous professional development|professional development]] of doctors, including [[BMJ Learning]] and the [[Royal Society of Medicine]]'s video lecture service.<ref name=BMJBio/>\n\nHe has consulted for a number of organisations including [[Harvard University]], the [[NHS]], the [[World Health Organization]] and [[McKinsey & Company|McKinsey & Co]].<ref name=BMJBio/>\n\nHe has also made contributions on radio and television,<ref name=BMJBio/> particularly with [[Mark Porter (general practitioner)|Mark Porter]]. In this role, Abbasi has acted as a sceptic to [[BBC Radio 4]]'s weekly medical programme, Inside Health.<ref name=BBCRadio4>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01n65zl|title=BBC Radio 4 - Inside Health, Stem cells, Functional disorders, Epilepsy, Stoptober, Whiplash|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=19 July 2019}}</ref> He also writes for ''[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]'', a Pakistani English-language newspaper.<ref name=DebatingMatters/>\n\n==Cricket==\nFollowing cricket since the 1970s, Abbasi has been an international writer on Pakistan cricket since 1996, starting as a blogger for [[Cricinfo.com]] with a blog called Pak Spin, and with a particular interest in the politics of cricket.<ref name=Indie/><ref name=Ezekiel2011>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=s5MkBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA92&dq=Kamran+abbasi+cricket#v=onepage&q=Kamran%20abbasi%20cricket&f=false|title=Cricket and Beyond|last=Ezekiel|first=Gulu|date=2011|publisher=Prabhat Prakashan|isbn=9788184301007|location=|pages=92|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=zO3VL4ybLQwC&pg=PA234&dq=Kamran+abbasi+cricket#v=onepage&q=Kamran%20abbasi%20&f=false|title=Cricket, Lovely Cricket?: An Addict's Guide to the World's Most Exasperating Game|last=Booth|first=Lawrence|date=2008|publisher=Yellow Jersey Press|isbn=9780224079143|location=|pages=234|language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe was the first Asian columnist in an English cricket publication when he started writing for [[Wisden Cricket Monthly]].<ref name=DebatingMatters>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.debatingmatters.com/people/kamran_abbasi/|title=Debating Matters - People - Kamran Abbasi|website=archive.debatingmatters.com|language=en|access-date=19 July 2019}}</ref>{{when|date=July 2019}} In 2000, in one ''Wisden Cricket'' entry, he reported on [[Hansie Cronje]] and the [[South Africa cricket match fixing]] and responded by saying that the \"enigma of match fixing will remain. But the reflex judgement that white is good and brown is bad is now less sustainable than it ever was. For that at least, thank you, Hansie\".<ref name=Vahed2013>{{Cite journal|last=Vahed|first=Goolam|date=July 2013|title=Cricket and corruption: the post-apartheid relationship between India and South Africa within and beyond the boundary|journal=Diaspora Studies|language=en|volume=6|issue=2|pages=80\u201391|doi=10.1080/09739572.2013.853439|issn=0973-9572}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, he co-authored a paper on the influence of a [[1986 Austral-Asia Cup Final|1986 Pakistani victory in cricket over India]] on subsequent matches up to 2003.<ref name=\"Vorocek2006\">{{Cite journal|last=Voracek|first=Martin|last2=Formann|first2=Anton K.|date=April 2006|title=The Miandad Effect Reconsidered: Analysis of Pakistan's Cricket Performance 1952 to 2005|journal=Perceptual and Motor Skills|language=en-US|volume=102|issue=2|pages=323\u2013326|doi=10.2466/pms.102.2.323-326|pmid=16826652|issn=0031-5125}}</ref> Later, in 2012, he published a book titled ''The English Chronicles: Zindabad: A Modern History of Pakistan Cricket''.<ref name=Indie>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiebound.org/book/9781475100525|title=Zindabad: The English Chronicles: Zindabad: A Modern History of Pakistan Cricket {{!}} IndieBound.org|website=www.indiebound.org|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n===Articles===\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1136/bmj.317.7172.1599c | volume=317 | title=Film: The Knowledge of Healing | year=1998 | journal=BMJ | page=1599 | last1 = Culliford | first1 = L.}}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = | first1 =  | year = 1999 | title = The World Bank and World Health | url = https://www.bmj.com/content/bmj/318/7187/865.full.pdf | format = PDF | journal = British Medical Journal | volume = 318 | issue = | page = 865 | doi = 10.1136/bmj.318.7187.865 }}\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1136/bmj.328.7443.800 | volume=328 | title=India versus Pakistan and the power of a six: an analysis of cricket results | year=2004 | journal=BMJ | page=800 | last1 = Abbasi | first1 = Kamran | last2 = Khan | first2 = Khalid S}}  \n*{{cite journal | pmid = 24965786 | doi=10.1136/bmj.g4184 | volume=348 | title=Corruption: medicine's dirty open secret | year=2014 | journal=BMJ | page=g4184  | last1 = Jain | first1 = A | last2 = Nundy | first2 = S | last3 = Abbasi | first3 = K}}.\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1136/bmj.329.7474.0-g | volume=329 | title=Should journals mix medicine and politics? | year=2004 | journal=BMJ | last1 = Abbasi | first1 = Kamran}}\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1177/0141076817720629 | volume=110 | title=A future of technology and other humans | year=2017 | journal=Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine | page=263 | last1 = Abbasi | first1 = Kamran}}\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1177/0141076818782032 | volume=111 | title=How to fund the NHS | year=2018 | journal=Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine | page=187 | last1 = Abbasi | first1 = Kamran}}\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1136/bmj.l348 | title=We need fewer leaders and more followers | year=2019 | journal=BMJ | page=l348 | last1 = Abbasi | first1 = Kamran}}\n\n===''BMJ'' theme issues===\n*[https://www.bmj.com/content/326/7381/160 \"Forthcoming BMJ theme issues\"]. ''British Medical Journal'' 18 January 2003; 326 {{doi|10.1136/bmj.326.7381.160}}\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC259154/ \"Why a special issue of the BMJ on South Asia?\"]. Co-authored with Zuliqar A Bhutta and Samiran Nundy. ''British Medical Journal'' 25 October 2003; 327(7421): 941\u2013942. {{doi|10.1136/bmj.327.7421.941}}\n*[https://www.bmj.com/content/328/7443/0.1 \u201cMaternal and child health vital to progress of South Asia\u201d]. ''British Medical Journal'' 1 April 2004. {{doi|10.1136/bmj.328.7443.0}}\n*[https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/25cf/108d6770ac2e10cca4d616af735c42d47e7a.pdf \u201cTwelve years on: a call for papers for another special collection of articles on South Asia\u201d]. Co-authored with Zuliqar A Bhutta and Samiran Nundy. BMJ 10 June 2016. 2016;353:i3252 {{doi|10.1136/bmj.i3252}}\n\n===Journalism===\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/1999/aug/25/cricket5 \"East or West, Nasser's best\"]. An extract from a piece in the Wisden Cricket.  ''The Guardian'' 25 August 1999\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2006/aug/20/cricket.comment \"United Front\"]. ''[[The Guardian]]'', 20 August 2006\n\n===Books===\n*[https://books.google.