{"title_page": "Andrea Leadsom", "text_new": "{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Andrea Leadsom\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Rt Hon Andrea Leadsom MP crop 2.jpg\n| caption = Leadsom in 2020\n| office = [[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy]]\n| primeminister = [[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start = 24 July 2019\n| term_end = 13 February 2020\n| predecessor = [[Greg Clark]]\n| successor = [[Alok Sharma]]\n| office1 = [[Leader of the House of Commons]]<br />[[Lord President of the Council]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start1 = 11 June 2017\n| term_end1 = 22 May 2019\n| predecessor1 = [[David Lidington]]\n| successor1 = [[Mel Stride]]\n| office2 = [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start2 = 14 July 2016\n| term_end2 = 11 June 2017\n| predecessor2 = [[Elizabeth Truss]]\n| successor2 = [[Michael Gove]]\n| office3 = [[Department of Energy and Climate Change|Minister of State for Energy]]\n| primeminister3 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start3 = 11 May 2015\n| term_end3 = 14 July 2016\n| predecessor3 = [[Matt Hancock]]\n| successor3 = [[Claire Perry]]\n| office4 = [[Economic Secretary to the Treasury]]\n| primeminister4 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start4 = 9 April 2014\n| term_end4 = 11 May 2015\n| predecessor4 = [[Nicky Morgan]]\n| successor4 = [[Harriett Baldwin]]\n| office5 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[South Northamptonshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Northamptonshire]]\n| term_start5 = 6 May 2010\n| term_end5 = \n| predecessor5 = ''Constituency recreated''\n| successor5 = \n| majority5 = 27,761 (41.5%)\n| birth_name = Andrea Jacqueline Salmon\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1963|5|13|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Aylesbury]], [[Buckinghamshire]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| signature = \n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Ben Leadsom|1993}}\n| children = 3\n| education = [[Tonbridge Grammar School]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Warwick]]\n}}\n'''Andrea Jacqueline Leadsom''' ({{IPAc-en|'|l|\u025b|d|s|\u0259m}};<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tHy2ANVEIvc|title=Andrea Leadsom on Newsnight|last=Anna Firth|date=29 April 2016|publisher=|via=YouTube|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707155835/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tHy2ANVEIvc|archivedate=7 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''{{n\u00e9e}}'' '''Salmon'''; born 13 May 1963)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36676170|title =Tory contender: Andrea Leadsom|website = [[BBC News]]|date = 11 July 2016|accessdate = 8 August 2018}}</ref> is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician who served as [[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy]] from 2019 to 2020, and has served as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[South Northamptonshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Northamptonshire]] since [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59418 |date=13 May 2010 |page=8744}}</ref><ref>[http://www.andrealeadsom.com/ Home] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915121112/http://www.andrealeadsom.com/ |date=15 September 2015 }}. Andrea Leadsom. Retrieved 8 May 2012.</ref> Leadsom served as the [[Leader of the House of Commons]] from 2017 to 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/andrealeadsom/status/1131267480742236160?s=21 |title=Andrea Leadsom MP |website=Twitter |accessdate=22 May 2019 |url-status = live|df=dmy-all }}</ref> Leadsom has twice run to become [[Leader of the Conservative Party (UK)|Leader of the Conservative Party]], in 2016 and 2019.\n\nAfter graduating with a degree in political science at the [[University of Warwick]], she began a career in Finance including working as Institutional Banking Director at [[Barclays]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/5829a293e4fcb505194767d9/t/586fc5279de4bbdef29211ed/1483719978641/IBD+Job+Description.pdf|title=Andrea Leadsom Institutional Banking Director|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> and later as Senior Investment Officer and Head of Corporate Governance at Invesco Perpetual.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/leadsoms-resume-controversy-overblown-her-former-supervisor-says-1468000457|title=Leadsom's R\u00e9sum\u00e9 Controversy Overblown, Her Former Supervisor Says|last=Mackintosh|first=James|date=2016-07-08|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2018-10-17|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\nLeadsom was a prominent member of the [[Vote Leave|Leave campaign]] during the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 EU referendum]], and gained standing in referendum TV debates.<ref name=\"ITV Report\">{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2016-06-30/who-is-conservative-leadership-contender-andrea-leadsom|title=Who is Conservative leadership contender Andrea Leadsom?|accessdate=11 July 2016|date=30 June 2016|publisher=|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710151049/http://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2016-06-30/who-is-conservative-leadership-contender-andrea-leadsom/|archivedate=10 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On [[David Cameron]]'s resignation, Leadsom became one of five candidates in the [[2016 Conservative Party leadership election|election for the leadership of the governing Conservative Party]], and thereby for the role of [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]]. In the second round of voting by MPs, she came second to [[Theresa May]].<ref name=\"Bulman\">{{cite news |last=Bulman |first=May |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-tory-leadership-contest-conservative-election-theresa-may-read-speech-in-full-a7130746.html |title=Andrea Leadsom quits Tory leadership contest |work=The Independent |location=London |date=11 July 2016 |access-date=11 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711131211/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-tory-leadership-contest-conservative-election-theresa-may-read-speech-in-full-a7130746.html |archivedate=11 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> May appointed Leadsom as [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]].\n\nLeadsom served in the [[First May ministry|May Government]] as [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Environment Secretary]] from 2016 to 2017. She had previously served in the [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition]] as [[Minister of State]] for Energy at the [[Department of Energy and Climate Change]] from 2015 to 2016, and [[Economic Secretary to the Treasury]] and [[City Minister]] from 2014 to 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/andrea-leadsom |title=Andrea Leadsom MP |website=GOV.UK |accessdate=27 June 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630130408/https://www.gov.uk/government/people/andrea-leadsom |archivedate=30 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Following the [[snap election]] of [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]], Leadsom was appointed [[Lord President of the Council]] and Leader of the House of Commons. On 22 May 2019, she resigned in protest at May's Brexit strategy. Two days later, May announced her resignation as party leader, taking effect on 7 June.<ref>{{cite news |title=Latest as May makes statement outside No 10 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-politics-48394091 |accessdate=24 May 2019 |work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nShe stood to be leader of the Conservative Party in June 2019 but was eliminated in the first round of voting, finishing 8th out of 10 candidates with 11 votes.<ref>{{cite news|title=Out of race to be Leader|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jun/13/andrea-leadsom-and-esther-mcvey-out-of-race-to-be-tory-leader}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and financial career ==\nLeadsom was born in [[Aylesbury]], Buckinghamshire, the daughter of Richard and Judy Salmon (''n\u00e9e'' Kitchin).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bucksherald.co.uk/news/more-news/aylesbury-born-andrea-leadsom-could-be-country-s-new-prime-minister-1-7464615 |title=Aylesbury-born Andrea Leadsom could be country's new Prime Minister |publisher=Bucksherald.co.uk |date=6 July 2016 |accessdate=10 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160712062708/http://www.bucksherald.co.uk/news/more-news/aylesbury-born-andrea-leadsom-could-be-country-s-new-prime-minister-1-7464615 |archivedate=12 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She attended [[Tonbridge Grammar School|Tonbridge Girls' Grammar School]], then read [[Political Science]] at the [[University of Warwick]].<ref name=ww >'LEADSOM, Andrea Jacqueline', Who's Who 2013, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 2013; online edn, Oxford University Press, Dec 2012; online edn, Nov 2012 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U251154, accessed 2 Jan 2013]</ref>\n\nAfter graduation, Leadsom began a career in the [[financial industry|financial sector]] as a debt trader for [[Barclays de Zoete Wedd]], then the investment bank division of [[Barclays Bank]].<ref name=\"Arnold\">{{cite news|last=Arnold|first=Martin|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/89ff6b1e-4204-11e6-b22f-79eb4891c97d.html#axzz4DZ9bXPug|title=Leadsom forced to account for financial history|work=Financial Times|location=London|date=4 July 2016|accessdate=5 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160708125253/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/89ff6b1e-4204-11e6-b22f-79eb4891c97d.html#axzz4DZ9bXPug|archivedate=8 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> For Barclays itself, she served as Deputy Director in the Financial Institutions team from 1993; this involved the maintenance of contractual relationships with other banks.<ref name=\"reaction\" /> In this role, she said she was given a \"ringside seat\" in the collapse of [[Barings Bank]].<ref name=\"lessons\">{{cite news|last1=Leadsom|first1=Andrea|title=Andrea Leadsom: The lessons about banking regulation which stay with me from the collapse of Barings|url=http://www.conservativehome.com/platform/2009/08/andrea-leadsom-the-lessons-about-banking-regulation-which-we-must-stay-with-us-from-the-collapse-of.html|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=ConservativeHome|date=18 August 2009|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807015108/http://www.conservativehome.com/platform/2009/08/andrea-leadsom-the-lessons-about-banking-regulation-which-we-must-stay-with-us-from-the-collapse-of.html|archivedate=7 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Leadsom clashed with the head of Barclays Investments who tried to persuade her to return to full-time work soon after a pregnancy, and she left the company in 1997.<ref name=\"Arnold\"/> Later, in July 2016, she submitted a CV which showed that she had served as Deputy Director.{{clarify|date=January 2020}<ref>{{cite web|title=Andrea Leadsom revises 'exaggerated' CV|url=https://next.ft.com/content/3a531ec4-4396-11e6-b22f-79eb4891c97d|accessdate=6 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1997 to 1999, Leadsom served as Managing Director of De Putron Fund Management (DPFM).<ref>{{cite news|last=Goodley|first=Simon|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/04/andrea-leadsoms-the-city-high-profile-roles-under-radar-barclays-brexit-negotiations|title=Andrea Leadsom's time in the City: high-profile roles yet under the radar|work=The Guardian|date=4 July 2016|accessdate=5 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160705150149/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/04/andrea-leadsoms-the-city-high-profile-roles-under-radar-barclays-brexit-negotiations|archivedate=5 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1998 she was promoted to board director for marketing.<ref name=CoCheck>{{cite web|title=MS ANDREA JACQUELINE SALMON|url=https://companycheck.co.uk/director/905929405/ANDREA-JACQUELINE-SALMON/companies|website=Company Check|accessdate=10 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826113445/https://companycheck.co.uk/director/905929405/ANDREA-JACQUELINE-SALMON/companies|archivedate=26 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nLeadsom was Head of Corporate Governance and a Senior Investment Officer at [[Invesco Perpetual]] from 1999 to 2009.<ref name=ww /><ref>{{cite web|title=Andrea Leadsom|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/andrea-leadsom|website=UK.Gov|accessdate=29 June 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630130408/https://www.gov.uk/government/people/andrea-leadsom|archivedate=30 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Her role was to work (sometimes part-time) on \u201cspecial projects\u201d, mostly for the Chief Investment Officer, which included negotiating pay terms for senior fund managers. Towards the end of her time, she advised on a number of governance issues, but she had no-one reporting to her in either role.<ref name=\"reaction\">{{cite web |author=Robert Stephens|title=Was Andrea Leadsom really such a City hotshot?|url=http://reaction.life/was-andrea-leadsom-really-such-a-city-hotshot/|website=reaction.life|accessdate=5 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160705171700/http://reaction.life/was-andrea-leadsom-really-such-a-city-hotshot/ |archivedate=5 July 2016 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> A former colleague, knew Leadsom when she was working in corporate governance.{{clarify|date=January 2020}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/04/andrea-leadsoms-the-city-high-profile-roles-under-radar-barclays-brexit-negotiations|title=Andrea Leadsom's time in the City: high-profile roles yet under the radar|last=Goodley|first=Simon|date=2016-07-04|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-02-23|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Approval for individuals to manage funds or deal with clients is needed from the financial services regulator (then the [[Financial Services Authority]]), which Leadsom held{{clarify|date=July 2016}} from December 2002 to February 2003.{{clarify|date=January 2020}<ref name=\"Kenber\">{{cite news|last1=Kenber|first1=Billy|last2=Wison|first2=Harry|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/leadsom-admits-misleading-claims-on-cv-for-top-job-n80lgc2rj|title=Leadsom admits 'misleading' claims on CV for top job|work=The Times|location=London|date=6 July 2016|accessdate=6 July 2016}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Leadsom has never claimed to have personally been a fund manager, and Bob Yerbury, former Chief Investment Officer at Invesco Perpetual and Leadsom's former manager, dismissed the controversy about how she described her time there and described her as \"totally honest\".<ref name=\"Mackintosh\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/leadsoms-resume-controversy-overblown-her-former-supervisor-says-1468000457|title=Leadsom's R\u00e9sum\u00e9 Controversy Overblown, Her Former Supervisor Says|first=James|last=Mackintosh|date=8 July 2016|publisher=|via=Wall Street Journal|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161108043622/http://www.wsj.com/articles/leadsoms-resume-controversy-overblown-her-former-supervisor-says-1468000457|archivedate=8 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>{{clarify|date=January 2020}\n\nLeadsom was a [[Councillor]] on [[South Oxfordshire District Council]] between 2003 and 2007.<ref name=ww /><ref name=parl>[http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/andrea-leadsom/4117 Andrea Leadsom] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630130409/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/Andrea-Leadsom/4117 |date=30 June 2016 }}, www.parliament.org. Retrieved 2 January 2013.</ref>\n\nShe contested the safe labour seat of [[Knowsley South]] constituency in the [[United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]]<ref name=ww /><ref name=parl /> unsuccessfully and finished in third place, despite this, the incumbent Labour MPs majority was reduced significantly. She was subsequently placed on the [[A-List (Conservative)|Conservative A-List]]<ref>[http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2009/04/the-18-of-the-original-100-alisters-selected-for-conservative-seats-.html ConservativeHome's Seats & Candidates blog: Where are the original A-Listers now? The 18 who have been selected for Conservative seats] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141028112024/http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2009/04/the-18-of-the-original-100-alisters-selected-for-conservative-seats-.html |date=28 October 2014 }}. Conservativehome.blogs.com (21 April 2009). Retrieved 8 May 2012.</ref> and later chosen to represent the newly created seat of South Northamptonshire.\n\n== Political career ==\n\n=== Member of Parliament ===\nLeadsom was selected to stand as the parliamentary candidate in the newly-created [[South Northamptonshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Northamptonshire]] constituency in June 2006. In 2009, [[ConservativeHome]] said that she was \"defending a notional Conservative majority of 11,356.\"<ref name=\"diary\">{{cite news|last1=Leadsom|first1=Andrea|title=Diary of a PPC: Andrea Leadsom (South Northamptonshire)|url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2009/06/diary-of-a-ppc-andrea-leadsom-south-northamptonshire.html|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=ConservativeHome|date=8 June 2009|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817152815/http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2009/06/diary-of-a-ppc-andrea-leadsom-south-northamptonshire.html|archivedate=17 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] in May, Leadsom was elected with a majority of more than 20,000. On entering the House of Commons she was elected as a member of the [[Treasury Select Committee]].<ref name=parl /> She made her [[maiden speech]] on 22 June 2010 during the budget debate, when she spoke of restoring health to the financial sector, drawing from personal experience in [[financial regulation]], particularly with [[Barings Bank]].<ref name=\"maiden\">{{cite news|last1=Isaby|first1=Jonathan|title=Andrea Leadsom draws on her City experience in her maiden speech to explain how to restore the financial services sector to health|url=http://www.conservativehome.com/thetorydiary/2010/06/andrea-leadsom-draws-on-her-city-experience-in-her-maiden-speech-to-explain-how-to-restore-the-finan.html|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=ConservativeHome|date=23 June 2010|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807011712/http://www.conservativehome.com/thetorydiary/2010/06/andrea-leadsom-draws-on-her-city-experience-in-her-maiden-speech-to-explain-how-to-restore-the-finan.html|archivedate=7 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nLeadsom campaigned for EU reform. In September 2011, she co-founded the [[Fresh Start Project]] with Conservative MPs [[Chris Heaton-Harris]] and [[George Eustice]] to \"research and build support for realistic and far-reaching proposals for reforming the EU\".<ref name=\"eureform\">{{cite web|title=European Reform|url=http://www.andrealeadsom.com/parliamentary/european-reform|website=Andrea Leadsom|accessdate=2 July 2016|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141121130837/http://www.andrealeadsom.com/parliamentary/european-reform|archivedate=21 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=telegraph-20160702>{{cite news|last=Ross|first=Tim|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/02/andrea-leadsom-interview-thatcher-god-and-why-i-should-be-prime/|title=Andrea Leadsom interview: Thatcher, God and why I should be Prime Minister|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|date=2 July 2016|accessdate=2 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703000804/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/02/andrea-leadsom-interview-thatcher-god-and-why-i-should-be-prime/|archivedate=3 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 25 October 2011, Leadsom was one of 81 Conservative MPs to defy the party whip and vote in favour of holding a referendum on the UK's membership of the [[European Union]].<ref name=\"euscep\">{{cite news|title=Eurosceptics: UKIP's Lord Hesketh and Andrea Leadsom MP|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-15578224|accessdate=2 July 2016|publisher=BBC News|date=3 November 2011|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160706043505/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-15578224|archivedate=6 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This led to a sharp ruction with the [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], [[George Osborne]], at the time, which she denies.<ref name=\"osborne\">{{cite news|title=General Election 2015: Tory backbenchers tip rising star Andrea Leadsom as successor to David Cameron as party leader |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/generalelection/general-election-2015-tory-backbenchers-tip-rising-star-andrea-leadsom-as-successor-to-david-cameron-10204409.html |accessdate=9 July 2016|work=The Independent |date=25 April 2015 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160709154517/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/generalelection/general-election-2015-tory-backbenchers-tip-rising-star-andrea-leadsom-as-successor-to-david-cameron-10204409.html |archivedate= 9 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2012, during the [[Libor scandal]], she was widely reported on for her contribution to the Treasury Select Committee's questioning of [[Bob Diamond (banker)|Bob Diamond]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/its-fair-to-say-we-were-useless-against-diamond--leadsom-7923536.html |title='It's fair to say we were useless against Diamond'&nbsp;\u2013 Leadsom |first=Oliver |last=Wright |work=The Independent |date=9 July 2012 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120814134718/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/its-fair-to-say-we-were-useless-against-diamond--leadsom-7923536.html |archivedate=14 August 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/07/04/bob-diamonds-evidence-barclays-libor-fixing_n_1649335.html |title= Bob Diamond's Evidence On Barclays Libor Fixing: What Do We Now Know? |work= Huffington Post |date= 3 September 2012 | accessdate = 9 July 2016| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160709152426/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/07/04/bob-diamonds-evidence-barclays-libor-fixing_n_1649335.html |archivedate= 9 July 2016}}</ref> At a subsequent hearing she questioned [[Paul Tucker (banker)|Paul Tucker]], who stated that the previous government had not conspired with the Bank to fix rates. In a BBC interview, Leadsom stated that the suggestion \"has now been completely squashed by Paul Tucker\", and that on that specific point, George Osborne might want to apologise to Shadow Chancellor [[Ed Balls]] for \"suggesting he was implicated in rate fixing\", although she also pointed out that Balls \"still [had] a huge amount to answer for in relation to the scandal and his time in office\".<ref name=lib>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-18778111|title=Libor scandal: William Hague rejects Ed Balls apology calls|publisher=BBC News|date=10 July 2012|accessdate=10 July 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120710165657/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-18778111|archivedate=10 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Mike Smithson (politics)|Mike Smithson]] suggested this could be a reason for Osborne to overlook her for a promotion in the 2012 cabinet reshuffle, despite the fact that \"in terms of talent she must be right at the top of the list of 2010 newbies who should be promoted.\"<ref name=\"blackball\">{{cite news|last1=Smithson|first1=Mike|title=Will Osborne black-ball a promotion for Andrea?|url=http://www2.politicalbetting.com/index.php/archives/2012/07/10/will-osborne-blockade-promotion-for-andrea/|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=Political Betting|date=10 July 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818071016/http://www2.politicalbetting.com/index.php/archives/2012/07/10/will-osborne-blockade-promotion-for-andrea/|archivedate=18 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2012, Leadsom was ranked 91 on [[Iain Dale]]'s list of top 100 most influential figures from the right.<ref name=\"influe\">{{cite news|last1=Dale|first1=Iain|title=Iain Dale's Top 100 most influential figures from the Right 2012|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/9589957/Iain-Dales-Top-100-most-influential-figures-from-the-Right-2012.html|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=7 October 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012142918/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/9589957/Iain-Dales-Top-100-most-influential-figures-from-the-Right-2012.html|archivedate=12 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nLeadsom was one of five MPs to abstain from the Government's [[Marriage (Same Sex Couples) Act 2013|Marriage (Same Sex Couples) Bill]] by voting in both lobbies.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lowther|first1=Ed|title=Yes but, no but... MPs who vote both ways|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-21591602|accessdate=1 April 2015|publisher=BBC|date=5 March 2013|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107164402/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-21591602|archivedate=7 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Leadsom had earlier said she found the wording of the legislation \"unacceptable\", and that voting no reflected the views of \"so many\" of her constituents, who felt that the bill was \"deeply wrong\",<ref>[http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2013/02/01/tory-northamptonshire-mp-i-support-the-love-of-gay-couples-but-it-is-unacceptable-for-them-to-be-able-to-marry/ \"Tory Northamptonshire MP: \"I support the love of gay couples but it is unacceptable for them to be able to marry\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130423101042/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2013/02/01/tory-northamptonshire-mp-i-support-the-love-of-gay-couples-but-it-is-unacceptable-for-them-to-be-able-to-marry/ |date=23 April 2013 }}, ''Pink News''. Retrieved 1 February 2013</ref> but ultimately chose to abstain, saying, \"I find myself genuinely torn...I cannot vote against a measure that would mean so much to the minority of homosexual couples for whom marriage is the ultimate recognition for their genuine feelings for each other. Yet nor can I vote for a measure that risks centuries of faith-based belief in marriage.\" During her Conservative Party leadership campaign in 2016, she stated she would have preferred a situation in which there were two types of services.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cowburn |first=Ashley |date=7 July 2016 |title=Andrea Ledsom: I didn't like gay marriage law because it hurts Christians |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-brexit-speech-conservative-leadership-election-next-tory-leader-a7124641.html |work=The Independent |location=London |access-date=8 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160708045908/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-brexit-speech-conservative-leadership-election-next-tory-leader-a7124641.html |archivedate=8 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Following the vote, Leadsom stated, \"I would like to make clear that I fully support the lifelong commitment that is made between any loving couple and that I believe the legal basis of a same sex marriage should be no different to that of a heterosexual couple.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.andrealeadsom.com/news/201326/same-sex-marriage|title=Same Sex Marriage|website=Andrea Leadsom|accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, Leadsom was appointed by [[David Cameron]] to the [[Number 10 Policy Unit]], with responsibility for part of the public services brief.<ref name=\"alloc\">{{cite news|title=New Number Ten Policy Board Job Allocation|url=http://order-order.com/2013/10/21/new-number-10-policy-board-job-allocation/|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=Guido Fawkes|date=21 October 2013|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818044036/http://order-order.com/2013/10/21/new-number-10-policy-board-job-allocation/|archivedate=18 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"sop\">{{cite news|last1=Church|first1=Dominic|title=No. 10 Policy Board \u2013 Serious Symposium or Sop?|url=http://www.westminsteradvisers.co.uk/2013/10/no-10-policy-board-serious-symposium-or-sop/|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=Westminster Advisers|date=17 October 2013|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161013054450/http://www.westminsteradvisers.co.uk/2013/10/no-10-policy-board-serious-symposium-or-sop/|archivedate=13 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Economic Secretary to the Treasury ===\nOn 9 April 2014 Leadsom was appointed [[Economic Secretary to the Treasury]] following [[Maria Miller]]'s resignation from the Cabinet. She was also given the additional responsibility of [[City Minister]], a post which had previously been held concurrently with the position of [[Financial Secretary to the Treasury]].<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.techuk.org/insights/news/item/1371-andrea-leadsom-mp-appointed-new-city-minister-within-hmt|title=Andrea Leadsom MP appointed new City Minister for HMT|publisher=Tech UK|date=10 April 2014|access-date=4 August 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815180524/https://www.techuk.org/insights/news/item/1371-andrea-leadsom-mp-appointed-new-city-minister-within-hmt|archivedate=15 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Leadsom received praise for her dealings with Icelandic Minister of Finance, Bjarni Benediktsson, for delivering \"an almighty dressing down from the fearsome Leadsom.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uti.is/2014/11/is-exit-tax-on-both-isk-and-fx-in-the-icelandic-christmas-crackers-this-year/|title=Is exit tax on both ISK and FX in the Icelandic Christmas crackers this year? at Sigr\u00fan Dav\u00ed\u00f0sd\u00f3ttir's Icelog|accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nLeadsom was instrumental in introducing the UK Government's first Islamic bonds, the [[Sukuk#United Kingdom|Sukuk]]. This was the first Islamic bond listed outside the Islamic world. Leadsom stated \"the strong demand for the Sukuk not only delivers good value for money for the taxpayer, but also cements Britain\u2019s position as the western hub of Islamic finance and is a part of our long term economic plan to make Britain the undisputed centre of the global financial system.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lseg.com/resources/media-centre/press-releases/london-stock-exchange-welcomes-uk-government%E2%80%99s-first-islamic-bond-listing|title=London Stock Exchange welcomes UK Government's first Islamic bond listing|website=London Stock Exchange Group|accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''[[Financial Times]]'', her period as City Minister was seen by departmental officials as \"a disaster\", \"the worst minister we ever had. \u2026 She found it difficult to understand issues or take decisions. She was monomaniacal, seeing the EU as the source of every problem. She alienated officials by continually complaining about poor drafting.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mance|first1=Henry|title=Andrea Leadsom seeks to play down pro-EU comments|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/5ec81170-4101-11e6-b22f-79eb4891c97d.html|work=Financial Times|date=4 July 2016|accessdate=6 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707023059/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/5ec81170-4101-11e6-b22f-79eb4891c97d.html|archivedate=7 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==== Inheritance tax ====\nIn about 1997, she formed the company Bandal with her husband, and bought property in [[Oxford]] and [[Surrey]]. The company was financed by loans from the Jersey arm of Kleinwort Benson, a private bank.<ref name=\"Arnold\"/> It was learned in 2014 that Leadsom had transferred her shares to a trust fund for her children.<ref name=\"Arnold\"/> A spokesman for Leadsom said: \"This is a normal corporate situation and all tax that is due is being paid. None of the loans for the properties are based offshore\".<ref name=\"Independent 17 April 2014\">{{cite news |last=Harper |first=Tom |date=17 April 2014 |title=Revealed: how City minister Andrea Leadsom used controversial trusts to reduce her potential inheritance-tax bill |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/revealed-how-city-minister-andrea-leadsom-used-controversial-trusts-to-reduce-her-potential-inheritancetax-bill-9268469.html |work=The Independent |location=London |accessdate=4 August 2014 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140625204516/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/revealed-how-city-minister-andrea-leadsom-used-controversial-trusts-to-reduce-her-potential-inheritancetax-bill-9268469.html |archivedate=25 June 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== Donations from family firm ====\nThere was further criticism in 2014 when ''[[The Independent]]'' revealed that she had received a series of donations totalling \u00a370,000 to pay for printing and research costs for the FSP over the course of three years. The company is owned by her brother in law, whose family is based in the [[British Virgin Islands]] .<ref name=\"Independent 13 July 2014\">{{cite news |last1=Armitage |first1=Jim |last2=McSmith |first2=Andy |last3=Harper |first3=Tom |date=13 July 2014 |title=Andrea Leadsom received \u00a370,000 donation from family firm with parent company controlled in tax haven |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-received-70000-donation-from-family-firm-with-parent-company-controlled-in-tax-haven-9603559.html |work=The Independent |location=London |accessdate=4 August 2014 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808052613/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-received-70000-donation-from-family-firm-with-parent-company-controlled-in-tax-haven-9603559.html |archivedate=8 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Leadsom's husband Ben is a director of the firm which made the donations, which were used to pay the salaries of staff in Leadsom's Westminster office after her election as MP; the firm has also made donations of \u00a3816,000 to the Conservative party.<ref name=\"Guardian 8 July 2014\">{{cite news |last1= Leigh |first1= David |last2= Ball |first2= James|authorlink=James Ball (journalist) |last3= Haddou |first3= Leila |date= 8 July 2014 |title= Top Tory has family link with offshore banker who gave party \u00a3800,000 |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jul/08/andrea-leadsom-family-links-offshore-bank-donations-tories |work= The Guardian |location= London |accessdate= 4 August 2014 |url-status = live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140716222434/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jul/08/andrea-leadsom-family-links-offshore-bank-donations-tories |archivedate= 16 July 2014 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> Because the firm making the donations, Gloucester Research (later becoming GR Software and Research), was based in London, the donations conformed to the rule banning political donations from abroad. The Labour MP [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]] said: \u201cThese very large donations might be within the rules, but it certainly isn\u2019t right that a Treasury minister has been taking money in this way. Most reasonable people will see this as completely unreasonable\u201d.<ref name=\"Independent 13 July 2014\" />\n\n=== Minister of State for Energy ===\nLeadsom was re-elected as MP for South Northamptonshire on 7 May 2015 with 36,607 votes, compared to her nearest rival Lucy Mills (Labour), with 10,191 votes. On 11 May 2015, Leadsom, who had previously opposed [[wind farm]]s and European [[Renewable energy in the European Union#Renewable energy targets|renewable energy targets]], was moved from Economic Secretary to the Treasury, to be appointed Minister of State at the Department of Energy and Climate Change, reporting to [[Amber Rudd]] who was promoted to Secretary of State at the same department.<ref>''Private Eye'' (2014). \"Andrea Leadsom: Family funds\", ''Private Eye'', Issue No. 1371, 25 July&nbsp;\u2013 7 August 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Murray|first1=James|title=Andrea Leadsom appointed as Energy and Climate Change Minister|url=http://www.businessgreen.com/bg/news/2408053/andrea-leadsom-appointed-as-energy-and-climate-change-minister|website=businessgreen|accessdate=11 June 2015|ref=BusinessGreen|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150612235519/http://www.businessgreen.com/bg/news/2408053/andrea-leadsom-appointed-as-energy-and-climate-change-minister|archivedate=12 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Leadsom announced the end of taxpayer funded subsidies for onshore wind farms, stating \"we now have enough onshore wind in the pipeline to be sufficient to meet our renewable electricity aims\". This was a year earlier than was originally planned and was in line with the Conservative Party Manifesto.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.andrealeadsom.com/news/20150609/onshore-wind|title=Fulfilling Our Onshore Wind Manifesto Commitments|website=Andrea Leadsom|accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Brexit campaign===\nLeadsom took a prominent role in the campaign to leave the EU in [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|June 2016]]. She argued that the [[Governor of the Bank of England|Governor]] of the [[Bank of England]], [[Mark Carney]], had destabilised financial markets and jeopardised the Bank's independence by warning of short-term negative effects on the economy caused by leaving the EU.<ref name=\"telegraph-20160429\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/29/mothers-should-vote-to-leave-says-brexiteer-minister-andrea-lead/|title=Mothers should vote to leave, says Brexiteer minister Andrea Leadsom|author=Andrea Leadsom|date=29 April 2016|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=24 May 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508102348/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/29/mothers-should-vote-to-leave-says-brexiteer-minister-andrea-lead/|archivedate=8 May 2016|url-status = live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian-20160515\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/15/brexit-minister-bank-of-england-dangerous-intervention-andrea-leadsom-financial-markets-eu|title=Brexit minister accuses Bank of England of 'dangerous intervention'|author=Rowena Mason|date=15 May 2016|work=The Guardian|accessdate=24 May 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160520231223/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/15/brexit-minister-bank-of-england-dangerous-intervention-andrea-leadsom-financial-markets-eu|archivedate=20 May 2016|url-status = live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn a televised debate on the referendum, Leadsom appeared on the \"Leave\" panel, along with [[Gisela Stuart]] and [[Boris Johnson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-politics-eu-referendum-35603388|title=Reality Check: The EU referendum|date=23 February 2016|publisher=BBC News|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626184347/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-politics-eu-referendum-35603388|archivedate=26 June 2016|url-status = live|accessdate=27 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She disputed claims that the UK should pursue single market membership, saying that 80% of the world's economy, and most EU free-trade deals, are not within the single market. She also said that the UK economy is too large to need the single market, but is hindered by the slowness of EU trade procedures.<ref name=\"wilkinson\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/21/eu-debate-boris-johnson-vs-sadiq-khan-in-final-bbc-showdown-with/|title=EU debate: Boris Johnson says Brexit will be 'Britain's independence day' as Ruth Davidson attacks 'lies' of Leave campaign in front of 6,000-strong Wembley audience|author=Wilkinson, Michael|date=21 June 2016|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160704201901/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/21/eu-debate-boris-johnson-vs-sadiq-khan-in-final-bbc-showdown-with/|archivedate=4 July 2016|url-status = live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Conservative leadership election, 2016 ===\n{{main|2016 Conservative Party leadership election}}\n{{overly detailed|section=yes|date=July 2016}}\nImmediately following the referendum vote on 23 June 2016 for Britain to leave the EU, [[David Cameron]] announced that he would resign as leader of the Conservative Party and Prime Minister by October. Leadsom was one of the early favourites to become the next Prime Minister, and was also linked with a possible role as Chancellor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2016-06-24/south-northamptonshire-mp-leadsom-emerges-as-one-of-the-favourites-to-be-next-pm/ |title=South Northamptonshire MP Leadsom emerges as one of the favourites to be next PM |work=ITV News |accessdate=27 June 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160627055021/http://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2016-06-24/south-northamptonshire-mp-leadsom-emerges-as-one-of-the-favourites-to-be-next-pm/ |archivedate=27 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 30 June 2016 she announced her [[2016 Conservative Party (UK) leadership election|candidacy]] to become [[Leader of the Conservative Party (UK)|leader of the Conservative Party]].  Leadsom said she would trigger [[s:Consolidated version of the Treaty on European Union/Title VI: Final Provisions#Article 50|Article 50]] immediately upon becoming Prime Minister, and conduct swift negotiations with the European Union.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-07-04/leadsom-launches-u-k-leadership-bid-vowing-short-brexit-talks |title=Leadsom Starts U.K. Leadership Bid Vowing Short Brexit Talks |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=4 July 2016 |access-date=5 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160704115720/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-07-04/leadsom-launches-u-k-leadership-bid-vowing-short-brexit-talks |archivedate=4 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn the first round of voting on 5 July 2016, [[Theresa May]] received support from 165 MPs, while Leadsom came second with 66 votes.<ref>{{cite news |title=Conservative leadership election: Theresa May wins more than half of MPs' votes as Liam Fox is knocked out of race |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2016/jul/05/brexit-live-tory-leadership-tom-watson-unions-jeremy-corbyn?page=with:block-577bee87e4b0445bf0e06ef6#block-577bee87e4b0445bf0e06ef6 |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=5 July 2016 |access-date=5 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160708142903/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2016/jul/05/brexit-live-tory-leadership-tom-watson-unions-jeremy-corbyn?page=with:block-577bee87e4b0445bf0e06ef6#block-577bee87e4b0445bf0e06ef6 |archivedate=8 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In the second ballot, Leadsom came second with 84 votes. [[Michael Gove]] was eliminated with 46 votes. [[Theresa May]] received 199 votes. On 11 July 2016, Leadsom announced she would be withdrawing her leadership bid, leaving [[Theresa May]] as the successor to [[David Cameron]].<ref name=\"bbc36763208\">{{cite news|title=Andrea Leadsom quits Conservative leadership race|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36763208|accessdate=11 July 2016|work=BBC News|date=11 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711120043/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36763208|archivedate=11 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Interviews====\nIn a BBC interview on 7 July 2016, Leadsom spoke of her disappointment about plotting in the leadership race, including alleged attempts by opponents to block her from the final ballot. She dismissed as \"ridiculous\" accusations that her biography was misleading, saying that her \"incredibly varied\" CV is \"all absolutely true\".<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36730216 |title=Tory leadership: Leadsom says CV criticism is 'ridiculous' |date=7 July 2016 |publisher=BBC News |access-date=7 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707075202/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36730216 |archivedate=7 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nLeadsom promised to \"banish the pessimists\" and to provide prosperity for the UK if elected, and stated that she was committed to fair trade.<ref name=\"cowburn\">{{cite news |last=Cowburn |first=Ashley |date=7 July 2016 |title=Andrea Leadsom: I didn't like gay marriage law because it hurts Christians, admits Tory contender to be PM |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-brexit-speech-conservative-leadership-election-next-tory-leader-a7124641.html |work=The Independent |location=London |access-date=7 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707114316/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-brexit-speech-conservative-leadership-election-next-tory-leader-a7124641.html |archivedate=7 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She also stated that she would review the Hunting Act with a focus on animal welfare if elected, and was asked about her concerns over the legislation passed to introduce same sex marriage.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Heather |date=7 July 2016 |title=Next PM to be woman as Theresa May and Andrea Leadsom win MPs' vote |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/07/theresa-may-andrea-leadsom-tory-leader-prime-minister |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=8 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707174549/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/07/theresa-may-andrea-leadsom-tory-leader-prime-minister |archivedate=7 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Prior to 2017 election Leadsom advised Theresa May not to repeat her promise to allow parliamentary time to discuss repealing the hunting ban, but was overruled.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/may-forced-through-toxic-manifesto-hunting-pledge-lzqtxbq32|title=May forced through 'toxic' manifesto hunting pledge|last=Editor|first=Francis Elliott, Political|date=27 November 2017|via=www.thetimes.co.uk|accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref>  She also criticised her rival Theresa May's plan to use the status of EU nationals living in the UK as \"bargaining chips\", promising that if she was elected they could stay.<ref name=\"cowburn\" />\n\n==== Alleged exaggeration of pre-government jobs and responsibilities ====\nOn 6 July 2016 ''[[The Times]]'' and other news media published articles which said that Leadsom had overstated her private sector experience and responsibilities.<ref name=\"Kenber\" /> They said that despite references her supporters had made to her managing \"billions of pounds in funds\" and her impressive-sounding job titles, she had held financial services regulator approval for only a brief three-month period in 10 years at Invesco Perpetual, and quoted former colleagues who said that she had exaggerated her level of involvement and her management responsibilities.<ref name=\"indy06072016\" /> Bob Yerbury, former Chief Investment Officer at Invesco Perpetual and Leadsom's former manager, dismissed the controversy about how she described her time there and described her as \"totally honest\".<ref name=\"Mackintosh\" />\n\n[[Penny Mordaunt]], a Leadsom supporter, described the reports as \"a concerted effort to rubbish a stellar career\".<ref name=\"indy06072016\">{{cite news |last=Stone |first=Jon |date=6 July 2016 |title=Andrea Leadsom accused of 'misleading' claims on her CV |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-accused-of-misleading-claims-on-her-cv-a7122296.html |work=The Independent |location=London |access-date=6 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160706094136/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-accused-of-misleading-claims-on-her-cv-a7122296.html |archivedate=6 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Weaver |first=Matthew |date=6 July 2016 |title=Penny Mordaunt defends Leadsom Tory leadership bid |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/06/andrea-leadsom-penny-mordaunt-tory-leadership |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=6 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707150143/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/06/andrea-leadsom-penny-mordaunt-tory-leadership |archivedate=7 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Leadsom then issued an amended CV, which ''[[The Guardian]]'' listed both deputy financial institutions director, and financial institutions director roles at Barclays.\"<ref name=\"Kenber\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Bowers |first=Simon |date=6 July 2016 |title=Publication of Andrea Leadsom's CV prompts new questions about her career |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/06/andrea-leadsoms-cv-prompts-new-questions-about-career |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=6 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707154944/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/06/andrea-leadsoms-cv-prompts-new-questions-about-career |archivedate=7 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/07/the-day-mps-marched-for-andrea-leadsom-the-woman-who-really-coul/ |title=The day MPs marched for Andrea Leadsom... the woman who really could be our next prime minister |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710075844/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/07/the-day-mps-marched-for-andrea-leadsom-the-woman-who-really-coul/ |archivedate=10 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Leadsom defended her CV in a BBC interview, saying claims of it being exaggerated were \"ridiculous\". \"I have not changed my CV,\" she said. \"I was always very clear; I was senior investment officer working very closely with the chief investment officer. I have been very clear; I'm not a funds manager. I was, in Barclays and BZW, managing huge teams of people and large budgets and responsible for the trading relationships. To be very careful not to mislead, Barclays is a very big player in the large corporate and institutional banking world, and so the trading relationships are enormous \u2013 billions and billions and billions of pounds. So, when I was there as the financial institutions director [sic] responsible for UK banking relationship, the responsibility was for billions of pounds of trading lines and facilities to those companies \u2026 I've never said I was a fund manager and I've never been a fund manager\", she said.<ref name=\"GPolLive7Jul2016\">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Leadsom says she was never a fund manager |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2016/jul/07/gove-leadsom-tory-leadership-vote-final-two-politics-live?page=with:block-577e3a3fe4b07cec9883d3fa#block-577e3a3fe4b07cec9883d3fa |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=7 July 2016 |access-date=7 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710225253/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2016/jul/07/gove-leadsom-tory-leadership-vote-final-two-politics-live?page=with:block-577e3a3fe4b07cec9883d3fa#block-577e3a3fe4b07cec9883d3fa |archivedate=10 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> According to [[Financial Services Authority|FSA]] records she was authorised to run money for only three months.<ref name=\"Kenber\" /><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://register.fca.org.uk/ShPo_IndividualDetailsPage?id=003b000000KTEIHAA5|website=The Financial Services Register|title=Ms Andrea Jacqueline Salmon|accessdate=10 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Comments about motherhood ====\nLeadsom's comments in an interview with ''[[The Times]]'' were interpreted as hinting that her being a mother meant that she was a better choice for Prime Minister than May, who has not been able to have children for health reasons, because it meant that she had \"a very real stake\" in the future.<ref name=\"Coates\">{{cite news|last1=Coates|first1=Sam|last2=Sylvester|first2=Rachel|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/being-a-mother-gives-me-edge-on-may-leadsom-0t7bbm29x|title=Being a mother gives me edge on May \u2014 Leadsom|work=The Times|location=London|date=9 July 2016|accessdate=9 July 2016}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=\"graun09072016\">{{cite news|last=Sparrow|first=Andrew|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/08/andrea-leadsom-suggests-she-would-make-better-pm-as-she-has-children|title=Leadsom attacks 'gutter journalism' in row over motherhood quotes|work=The Guardian|date=9 July 2016|accessdate=9 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160708234309/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/08/andrea-leadsom-suggests-she-would-make-better-pm-as-she-has-children|archivedate=8 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She said that she \"did not want this to be 'Andrea has children, Theresa hasn't' because I think that would be really horrible\".<ref name=\"Coates\" /> After ''The Times'' published the story, with the headline \"Being a mother gives me an edge on May\", Leadsom said that she was \"disgusted\" by the article, which was the \"exact opposite of what I said\".<ref name=\"BBC090716\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36752865|title=Andrea Leadsom 'motherhood' comments spark row|publisher=BBC News|date=9 July 2016|accessdate=9 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160709021056/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36752865|archivedate=9 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''The Times'' later released a partial transcript of the comments, and when Leadsom supporter [[Penny Mordaunt]] said that it was trying to \"smear\" Leadsom, ''The Times'' released an audio recording.<ref name=\"BBC090716\" />  Her comments were widely criticised<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2016/jul/11/blue-quartets-hostility-to-andrea-leadsom-reduces-her-to-tears|title=Rightwing papers' hostility to Andrea Leadsom reduces her to tears|first=Roy|last=Greenslade|date=11 July 2016|work=The Guardian|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206211950/https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2016/jul/11/blue-quartets-hostility-to-andrea-leadsom-reduces-her-to-tears|archivedate=6 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> with fellow Conservative MPs including [[Sarah Wollaston]] and [[Anna Soubry]] suggesting the remarks showed she lacked the judgement to be Prime Minister and calling upon her to withdraw.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.sky.com/story/leadsom-in-backlash-over-motherhood-remarks-10496432 |title=Leadsom In Backlash Over Motherhood Remarks |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160709173413/http://news.sky.com/story/leadsom-in-backlash-over-motherhood-remarks-10496432 |archivedate=9 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Alan Duncan]] described her remarks as \"vile\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cowburn|first1=Ashley|title=Andrea Leadsom attacked by Tory MPs over 'vile' and 'insulting' comments on Theresa May's childlessness|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-theresa-may-vile-insulting-children-conservative-leadership-tory-a7128311.html|accessdate=11 July 2016|work=The Independent|date=10 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710134640/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-theresa-may-vile-insulting-children-conservative-leadership-tory-a7128311.html|archivedate=10 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Tim Loughton]], Leadsom's campaign manager for the leadership contest, said that the establishment were ganging up on her.\n\n==== Comments about men and childcare ====\nIn an interview with ''The Times'', Andrea Leadsom suggested men should not be hired to look after young children as they might be paedophiles.<ref name=\"StandardJuly15\">{{cite news|url= https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/andrea-leadsom-suggests-men-should-not-be-nannies-because-they-may-be-paedophiles-a3296421.html/|title= Andrea Leadsom suggests men should not be nannies because they may be paedophiles|work= The Evening Standard|date= 15 July 2016|accessdate= 6 October 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20161010125038/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/andrea-leadsom-suggests-men-should-not-be-nannies-because-they-may-be-paedophiles-a3296421.html|archivedate= 10 October 2016|df= dmy-all}}</ref> In the interview she said: \"As an employer we\u2019re not, let\u2019s face it, most of us don\u2019t employ men as nannies, most of us don\u2019t ... Now you can call that sexist, I call that cautious and very sensible when you look at the stats. Your odds are stacked against you if you employ a man. .. We know paedophiles are attracted to working with children. I\u2019m sorry but they\u2019re the facts.\".<ref name=\"IndieJuly15\">{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-men-paedophiles-childcare-workers-hired-sensible-a7139351.html/|title= Andrea Leadsom says men should not be hired to do childcare as they may be paedophiles|work= The Independent|date= 15 July 2016|accessdate= 6 October 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20161018103712/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-men-paedophiles-childcare-workers-hired-sensible-a7139351.html|archivedate= 18 October 2016|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Questions over financial affairs====\nShe promised to publish her tax returns<ref>{{cite web|last1=May|first1=Josh|title=Andrea Leadsom, Theresa May and Michael Gove offer to publish tax returns|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/conservative-party/news/76879/andrea-leadsom-theresa-may-and-michael-gove|website=Politics Home|accessdate=10 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914065407/https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/conservative-party/news/76879/andrea-leadsom-theresa-may-and-michael-gove|archivedate=14 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> when she made it to the final ballot of the leadership election. Three days later she published \"one year of tax information after rival Theresa May released four years\u2019 worth of tax returns\". Richard Murphy, director of Tax Research UK, a tax campaign group, said \u201cThis isn\u2019t her tax return, it\u2019s a tax computation...It\u2019s a summary of numerical information but not an explanation of where it came from or what tax is due. It excludes all the information that might be of interest, so she has not published her tax return.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davies|first1=Rob|title=Andrea Leadsom discloses tax details and 2015 income of \u00a385,000|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/10/andrea-leadsom-tax-returns-reveals-85000-income-in-2015|accessdate=10 July 2016|work=The Guardian|date=10 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710143029/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/10/andrea-leadsom-tax-returns-reveals-85000-income-in-2015|archivedate=10 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====\"Black ops\" allegation====\nFormer conservative leader [[Iain Duncan Smith]] alleged that the intensity and nature of the sniping at Andrea Leadsom revealed ulterior motives, unconnected to her fitness for the post, saying to journalist [[Robert Peston]] that they indicated \"a kind of real 'black-ops' operation to denigrate her reputation\", writing later it constituted a \"concerted and brutal attempt to destroy her character\".<ref name=\"IDS\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36757909| title=Iain Duncan Smith claims 'black ops' bid to 'denigrate' Leadsom| work=BBC news| date=10 July 2016| accessdate=10 July 2016|url-status = live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710101844/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36757909| archivedate=10 July 2016| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/11/uniting-the-conservative-party-will-be-impossible-without-a-real/|title= Uniting the Conservative Party will be impossible without a real plan for Brexit|date= 12 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160712131449/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/11/uniting-the-conservative-party-will-be-impossible-without-a-real/|archivedate= 12 July 2016|df= dmy-all}}</ref> [[Allison Pearson]] in ''[[The Sunday Telegraph]]'' wrote, \"I have no doubt whatsoever that Leadsom became the target of a brutal and sustained character assassination.\"<ref name=\"STelJuly10\">{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/10/ive-been-under-attack-its-been-shattering-andrea-leadsom-apologi/|title= 'I've been under attack, it's been shattering': Andrea Leadsom apologises to Theresa May over motherhood comments and admits furore has left her hurt|work= The Daily Telegraph|date= 10 July 2016|accessdate= 10 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160710221154/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/10/ive-been-under-attack-its-been-shattering-andrea-leadsom-apologi/|archivedate= 10 July 2016|df= dmy-all}}</ref> The next day she wrote, \"Andrea Leadsom has nothing to be ashamed of: her conscience is clear. Those who sought to destroy her should examine theirs, if they can find it.\"<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/11/how-the-skulduggers-succeeded-in-bringing-an-end-to-andrea-leads/|title= How the skulduggers succeeded in bringing an end to Andrea Leadsom's campaign to be prime minister|work= The Daily Telegraph|date= 11 July 2016|accessdate= 11 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160711204437/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/11/how-the-skulduggers-succeeded-in-bringing-an-end-to-andrea-leads/|archivedate= 11 July 2016|df= dmy-all}}</ref> [[Norman Tebbit]] described the efforts to remove her candidature as an intense smear campaign, saying that he suspected they may have arisen from her opposition to gay marriage as much as her Euroscepticism.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/12/theresa-may-will-drive-tory-members-into-the-arms-of-ukip/ |title= Theresa May will drive Tory members into the arms of Ukip |work= The Daily Telegraph |url-status = live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160712063043/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/12/theresa-may-will-drive-tory-members-into-the-arms-of-ukip/ |archivedate= 12 July 2016 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== Withdrawal from the leadership contest ====\nOn 11 July 2016 Leadsom withdrew from the Conservative leadership election, stating that she did not have enough support for her cause, with only a quarter of the votes from the parliamentary party.<ref name=\"bbc36763208\" /> The previous day ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' had reported a rumour that up to 20 Tory MPs would quit the party if Leadsom won the leadership contest; this was later supported by reports in other news media<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/leadsoms-enemies-stick-the-knife-in-g0psn6s73|title=Leadsom's enemies stick the knife in|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Merrick |first=Jane |date=11 July 2016 |title=If Andrea Leadsom had won, the Conservative Party would have become a basket case |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/11/if-andrea-leadsom-had-won-the-conservative-party-would-have-beco/ |work=The Telegraph |location=London |access-date=11 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711145150/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/11/if-andrea-leadsom-had-won-the-conservative-party-would-have-beco/ |archivedate=11 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> but \"denied by MPs\" according to ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Asthana |first=Anushka |date=11 July 2016 |title=Andrea Leadsom pulls out of Conservative leadership race |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/11/conservative-leadership-andrea-leadsom-pulls-out-of-race |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=12 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170625061303/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/11/conservative-leadership-andrea-leadsom-pulls-out-of-race |archivedate=25 June 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn her statement Leadsom said: \"the interests of our country are best served by the immediate appointment of a strong and well-supported prime minister. I am therefore withdrawing from the leadership election, and I wish Mrs May the very greatest success.\" Her campaign manager, MP Tim Loughton spoke about an \"onslaught of often very personal attacks from colleagues and journalists\" as well as  \"underhand tactics against decent people\".<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |last=Booth |first=Robert |date=11 July 2016 |title=How it all went wrong for Andrea Leadsom's leadership bid |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/11/how-it-all-went-wrong-for-andrea-leadsoms-leadership-bid |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=12 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160712031052/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/11/how-it-all-went-wrong-for-andrea-leadsoms-leadership-bid |archivedate=12 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Leadsom had been under pressure from the news media, with reports criticising her exaggeration of business and management experience<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\" /><ref name=\"thetimes.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/leadsom-admits-misleading-claims-on-cv-for-top-job-n80lgc2rj|title=Leadsom admits 'misleading' claims on CV for top job|work=The Times|date= 6 July 2016}}</ref> and her suggestion that motherhood strengthened her candidacy for Prime Minister.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-accused-of-misleading-claims-on-her-cv-a7122296.html|title=Andrea Leadsom accused of 'misleading' claims on her CV|date=6 July 2016|publisher=|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170703030149/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-accused-of-misleading-claims-on-her-cv-a7122296.html|archivedate=3 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"thetimes.co.uk\" /><ref name=\"Sparrow\">{{cite news |last=Sparrow |first=Andrew |date= |title=Leadsom attacks 'gutter journalism' in row over motherhood quotes |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/08/andrea-leadsom-suggests-she-would-make-better-pm-as-she-has-children |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=8 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160708231608/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/08/andrea-leadsom-suggests-she-would-make-better-pm-as-she-has-children |archivedate=8 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Leadsom charged ''[[The Times]]'' with \"gutter journalism\" in response to the article about the motherhood issue.<ref>{{cite news |last=Coates |first=Sam |date=9 July 2016 |title=Being a mother gives me edge on May \u2014 Leadsom |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/being-a-mother-gives-me-edge-on-may-leadsom-0t7bbm29x |work=The Times |location=London |access-date=11 July 2016}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Sparrow |first=Andrew |date=8 July 2016 |title=Leadsom attacks 'gutter journalism' in row over motherhood quotes |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/08/andrea-leadsom-suggests-she-would-make-better-pm-as-she-has-children |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=11 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711113434/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/08/andrea-leadsom-suggests-she-would-make-better-pm-as-she-has-children |archivedate=11 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> ''[[The Times]]'' subsequently released the audio tapes of the interview to confirm Leadsom's statement. Although she subsequently apologised \"for any hurt I have caused\" to [[Theresa May]], she also related that she had felt \"under attack, under enormous pressure \u2026 It has been shattering.\"<ref name=\"auto1\" />\n\nHer resignation statement did not touch on either controversy or her personal feelings. Instead, she thanked the 84 MPs who had supported her, conceding that \"this is less than 25% of the parliamentary party and ... I do not believe this is sufficient support to win a strong and stable government should I win the leadership election\".<ref name=\"Bulman\" /> After her appointment as a Cabinet minister, other comments that Leadsom had made during the leadership race came to light and also led to criticism. During the 6 July 2016 interview with ''[[The Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/leadsom-male-carers-might-be-paedophiles-btxfs8hx7|title=Leadsom: male carers might be paedophiles|work=The Times}}</ref> she had stated that men were more likely to be paedophiles than women and hence, were not suitable to be hired for jobs in daycare.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stone |first=Jon |date=15 July 2016 |title=Andrea Leadsom says men should not be hired to do childcare as they may be paedophiles |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-men-paedophiles-childcare-workers-hired-sensible-a7139351.html |work=The Independent |location=London |access-date=17 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716125823/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-men-paedophiles-childcare-workers-hired-sensible-a7139351.html |archivedate=16 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Several MPs in opposition parties called for May to dismiss Leadsom from the Cabinet but the prime minister declined to do so.<ref name=\"standard1\">{{cite web |author=Mark Chandler |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/theresa-may-under-pressure-to-sack-andrea-leadsom-over-stupid-paedophile-comments-a3297091.html |title=Theresa May 'should sack' Andrea Leadsom over 'stupid' paedophile comments |work=London Evening Standard |date=14 July 2016 |accessdate=18 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160718011320/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/theresa-may-under-pressure-to-sack-andrea-leadsom-over-stupid-paedophile-comments-a3297091.html |archivedate=18 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs ===\nFollowing [[Theresa May]]'s cabinet shuffle on 14 July 2016 Leadsom moved from her role as Energy Minister to become [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]].<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Andrea Leadsom appointed environment secretary |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/live/2016/jul/14/theresa-may-cabinet-reshuffle-boris-johnson-philip-hammond-rules-out-emergency-budget |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=14 July 2016 |access-date=14 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160714091607/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/live/2016/jul/14/theresa-may-cabinet-reshuffle-boris-johnson-philip-hammond-rules-out-emergency-budget |archivedate=14 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n<br />In April 2017, following the announcement of the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|general election]] in June, Leadsom was instructed to delay a report of illegally high levels of diesel pollution affecting over half the population until after the election. Constitutional experts Dr Jo Murkens and Colin Talbot agreed it was a health issue and therefore not affected by the election and the government was instructed to appear in the high court to explain the delay.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/apr/25/government-delay-air-pollution-plan-due-to-election-dishonest|title=Tories 'on very dodgy ground' over delay of air pollution plan, say experts|author=Matthew Taylor|work=The Guardian|date=25 April 2017|accessdate=25 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170425162945/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/apr/25/government-delay-air-pollution-plan-due-to-election-dishonest|archivedate=25 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Criticism of broadcasters====\nOn the anniversary of the Brexit vote, Leadsom was invited to discuss progress on ''[[Newsnight]]'' and claimed that the government had made \"a good start.\" While being interviewed by [[Emily Maitlis]], Leadsom suggested broadcasters should be \"a little more patriotic.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-40386788/brexit-tory-mp-leadsom-says-broadcasters-should-be-patriotic|title=Brexit: Tory MP Leadsom says broadcasters should be patriotic|work=BBC news|date=23 June 2017|accessdate=25 June 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170625000621/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-40386788/brexit-tory-mp-leadsom-says-broadcasters-should-be-patriotic|archivedate=25 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Tim Farron]] described her remarks as \"a sinister threat to the free media,\" a comment echoed by [[Hugo Rifkind]] in ''The Times'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/past-six-days/2017-07-04/comment/we-must-resist-every-assault-on-the-free-press-mltktxjbt|title=We must resist every assault on the free press|author=Hugo Rifkind|work=The Times|date=4 July 2017|accessdate=5 July 2017|url-access=subscription }}</ref> whilst ''[[Peston on Sunday]]'' mockingly displayed his patriotism by decorating the studio with [[Union Jacks]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Marsh|first=Sarah|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jun/25/peston-on-sunday-gives-leadsoms-call-for-patriotism-a-droll-reply|title=Peston on Sunday gives Leadsom's call for patriotism a droll reply|work=The Guardian|date=25 June 2017|accessdate=26 June 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170625123045/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jun/25/peston-on-sunday-gives-leadsoms-call-for-patriotism-a-droll-reply|archivedate=25 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Lord President of the Council and Leader of the House of Commons ===\n[[File:Official portrait of Andrea Leadsom.jpg|left|thumb|241x241px|Leadsom's official parliamentary portrait after being re-elected as the MP for South Northamptonshire]]\nOn 11 June 2017, Leadsom was appointed [[Lord President of the Council]] and [[Leader of the House of Commons]]. In this capacity, in July 2017, while attempting to eulogise [[Jane Austen]], who was about to feature on the new \u00a310 note scheduled to go into circulation in September, Leadsom told the House of Commons: \"I would just add one other great lady to that lovely list, who I am delighted to join in celebrating, and that's that of Jane Austen, who will feature on the new \u00a310 note, which I think is one of our greatest living authors.\" Amid laughs from both benches, she corrected herself, adding: \"Greatest ever authors, and I think it's fantastic that at last we are starting to recognize \u2013 well I think many of us probably wish she were still living \u2013 but I absolutely share the sentiment.\"<ref name=\"Austen\">{{cite news|work=Leader of Commons refers to face of new \u00a310 note as one of Britain's greatest living authors, causing much mirth among MPs|date= 20 July 2017|title=Unreliable narrator? Andrea Leadsom mistakenly resurrects Jane Austen |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/jul/20/andrea-leadsom-jane-austen-britain-greatest-living-author}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 January 2019, Leadsom was criticised in the House of Commons by the Speaker of the House, [[John Bercow]] for the failure of the government to advance the cause of [[proxy voting]] for expectant mothers. The issue came to a head due to the imminent caesarean section delivery by [[Tulip Siddiq]] at the time of the rescheduled [[meaningful vote]] on 15 January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|date=14 January 2019|title=John Bercow says it is 'lamentable' that Labour MP forced to postpone birth over crucial Brexit vote|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/101109/john-bercow-says-it-%E2%80%98lamentable%E2%80%99-labour-mp-forced}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January 2019, Leadsom said the House of Commons' February [[Recess (parliamentary procedure)|recess]] from 15 to 24 February would be cancelled to free up time to pass the necessary [[Withdrawal Agreement and Implementation Bill|Brexit-related legislation]]. Earlier in the day, her cabinet colleague Jeremy Hunt raised the possibility of Brexit being delayed with a technical extension to Article 50. The Times newspaper reported that senior Government ministers fear that it is already too late to meet the Brexit deadline of 29 March, and that Conservative MPs have been told that a one-line whip is expected to be imposed on votes in the Commons during the week of 18\u201322 February.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/mps-lose-ten-day-break-in-scramble-to-pass-brexit-bill-mdbp0lvqc|title=MPs lose ten-day break in scramble to pass Brexit bill|first=Matt Chorley|last=Red&nbsp;Box&nbsp;Editor|date=31 January 2019|accessdate=23 May 2019|via=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nLeadsom resigned as Leader of the House of Commons on 22 May, the eve of the [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|European elections]], as a result of Theresa May's most recent Brexit proposals, including the offer of votes in the House of Commons on a customs union and a second referendum.\n\n=== Conservative leadership election, 2019 ===\n{{main|2019 Conservative Party leadership election}}\nOn 8 May 2019, Leadsom stated she was \"seriously considering\" a bid for the party leadership.<ref>{{cite news |work=The Independent |title=Tory leadership race: Andrea Leadsom says she is 'seriously considering' bid to succeed Theresa May |date=8 May 2019 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tory-leadership-race-andrea-leadsom-theresa-may-brexit-prime-minister-a8904176.html}}</ref>\nLeadsom officially announced her candidacy on 25 May, the same day that [[Matt Hancock]] and [[Dominic Raab]] also announced they were running. She was proposed and seconded by fellow MPs [[Chris Heaton-Harris]] and [[Heather Wheeler]]. Leadsom was eliminated from the contest in the first ballot, on 13 June 2019, and came overall in eighth place out of ten candidates.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Stewart|first=Heather|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jun/13/andrea-leadsom-and-esther-mcvey-out-of-race-to-be-tory-leader|title=Andrea Leadsom and Esther McVey out of race to be Tory leader|date=2019-06-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-29|last2=Walker|first2=Peter|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2019-06-13/andrea-leadsom-out-of-the-tory-leadership-race-but-matt-hancock-gets-through-to-next-round/|title=Andrea Leadsom out of the Tory leadership race but Matt Hancock gets through to next round|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/live-conservative-leadership-candidates-face-first-vote-in-race-for-number-10-11740891|title=LIVE: Leadsom, McVey and Harper eliminated in Tory leadership vote|website=Sky News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy ===\nOn 24 July 2019, Leadsom was appointed [[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy]] by incoming Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]].\n\nOn 19 October, she said she was subject to \"frightening abuse\" from anti-Brexit demonstrators whilst leaving the [[Palace of Westminster]]. [[Jacob Rees-Mogg]] and [[Michael Gove]] were also targeted as they left following a House of Commons sitting. Leadsom was given a [[police escort]] through crowds gathered for a [[People's Vote]] rally, who were protesting for a further public vote on Brexit.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/leadsom-gove-and-rees-mogg-targeted-brexit-protesters-9kttg6s9x|title=Andrea Leadsom, Michael Gove and Jacob Rees-Mogg targeted by Brexit protesters|last=Editor|first=Francis Elliott, Political|date=2019-10-19|work=The Times|access-date=2019-10-23|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nLeadsom retained her seat with an increased majority at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/politics/constituencies/E14000942|title=Northamptonshire South parliamentary constituency - Election 2019|access-date=2020-01-09|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nShe was sacked as Business Secretary in the [[2020 British cabinet reshuffle]] undertaken by Boris Johnson on 13 February 2020.\n\n==Political views==\nLeadsom said in 2016 that she was \"absolutely pro-choice\" on abortion, but was \"keeping an eye on scientific progress which makes foetuses viable earlier\". She is concerned about child development, and founded a charity which helps vulnerable mothers to bond with their babies.<ref name=\"apology\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/10/ive-been-under-attack-its-been-shattering-andrea-leadsom-apologi/|title='I've been under attack, it's been shattering': Andrea Leadsom apologises to Theresa May over motherhood comments and admits furore has left her hurt|work=The Daily Telegraph|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710221154/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/10/ive-been-under-attack-its-been-shattering-andrea-leadsom-apologi/|archivedate=10 July 2016|url-status = live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the [[2016 US Presidential election]] she supported [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] candidate [[Hillary Clinton]] against [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Donald Trump|Trump]]. When seeking the Premiership she said she \"absolutely would rule out giving [[Nigel Farage]] [of [[UKIP]]] a job\".<ref name=apology/>\n\nShe said that if she became Prime Minister she would reform the ban on [[fox hunting]] to ensure greater protections for [[animal welfare]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-fox-hunting-animal-welfare-ban-hunting-act-poll-a7127276.html|title=Andrea Leadsom says she'll bring back fox hunting to improve animal welfare|date=8 July 2016|work=The Independent|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170711014302/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-fox-hunting-animal-welfare-ban-hunting-act-poll-a7127276.html|archivedate=11 July 2017|url-status = live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Prior to the 2017 election, Leadsom advised Theresa May not to repeat her promise to allow parliamentary time to discuss repealing the hunting ban, but was overruled.<ref name=\"auto2\" />\n\n===Environment===\nBefore becoming Minister at the Department of Energy and Climate Change, Leadsom had opposed wind farms and EU renewable energy targets. After her appointment she said \"When I first came to this job one of my two questions was: 'Is [[climate change]] real?' and the other was 'Is [[hydraulic fracturing]] [\"fracking\"] safe?' And on both of those questions I am now completely persuaded.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/energy-minister-andrea-leadsom-asked-whether-climate-change-was-real-when-she-started-the-job-a6710971.html|title=New energy minister Andrea Leadsom asked whether climate change was real when she started the job|author=Doug Bolton|date=27 October 2015|work=The Independent|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160904052736/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/energy-minister-andrea-leadsom-asked-whether-climate-change-was-real-when-she-started-the-job-a6710971.html|archivedate=4 September 2016|url-status = live|accessdate=8 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAs Minister, Leadsom launched the consultation to ban microbeads. Leadsom was personally opposed to microbeads, stating \"Most people would be dismayed to know the face scrub or toothpaste they use was causing irreversible damage to the environment, with billions of indigestible plastic pieces poisoning sea creatures. Adding plastic to products like face washes and body scrubs is wholly unnecessary when harmless alternatives can be used.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-37263087|title=Plastic microbeads to be banned by 2017|date=3 September 2016|via=www.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn her role as Secretary of State for the Department for Energy, Food and Rural Affairs, Leadsom stated she was \u201cpersonally deeply committed to the importance of ensuring clean air\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/apr/25/government-delay-air-pollution-plan-due-to-election-dishonest|title=Tories 'on very dodgy ground' over delay of air pollution plan, say experts|last=Taylor|first=Matthew|date=25 April 2017|via=www.theguardian.com|accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nPrior to 2017 election Leadsom advised Theresa May not to repeat her promise to allow parliamentary time to discuss repealing the hunting ban, but was overruled.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n===European Union===\nIn April 2013 at the [[Hansard Society]]'s annual parliamentary affairs lecture, Leadsom warned against the UK leaving the European Union, stating that \"I think it would be a disaster for our economy and it would lead to a decade of economic and political uncertainty at a time when the tectonic plates of global success are moving.\"<ref name=\"Independenta7116686\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tory-conservative-leadership-andrea-leadsom-brexit-latest-eu-referendum-disaster-next-leader-a7116686.html|title=Tory leadership contender Andrea Leadsom said leaving EU would be 'disaster' \u2013 then campaigned for Brexit|last=Cowburn|first=Ashley|date=3 July 2016|work=The Independent|accessdate=5 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160704132517/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tory-conservative-leadership-andrea-leadsom-brexit-latest-eu-referendum-disaster-next-leader-a7116686.html|archivedate=4 July 2016|url-status = live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/5ec81170-4101-11e6-b22f-79eb4891c97d.html|title=Andrea Leadsom seeks to play down pro-EU comments|date=3 July 2016|work=Financial Times|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707023059/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/5ec81170-4101-11e6-b22f-79eb4891c97d.html|archivedate=7 July 2016|url-status = live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHowever, in 2016 Leadsom campaigned for leave in the UK referendum on European Union membership. ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]'' reproduced her earlier comments in its issue of 3 July 2016.<ref name=\"Independenta7116686\"/> After her comments were read out by [[Andrew Marr]] on his Sunday morning BBC programme, she explained to Marr how she reached her more recent position: \"It has been a journey. When I came into Parliament, like most people in the country I'd grown up as part of the EU and it's absolutely part of our DNA and I came into Parliament, set up something called the Fresh Start Project, which took hundreds and hundreds of hours of evidence about how the EU impacts on the UK \u2013 on everything from immigration to fisheries and so on... During that process I travelled all across Europe with lots of parliamentary colleagues \u2013 up to 100 Conservative colleagues supporting this work \u2013 to try and get a really decent, fundamental reform of the EU.\"<ref name=\"Independenta7116686\"/> A spokesman for Leadsom said that the recording was \"taken completely out of context\" because she had opened the lecture by saying that the EU needed major reforms in order for it to be \"sustainable\". She added that the democratic consent for the EU in Britain was \"wafer thin\".<ref name=\"Independenta7116686\"/>\n\n==Charity support==\nLeadsom was a founder of the Northamptonshire Parent Infant Partnership, a charity providing therapeutic support to help parents bond with their babies who have [[Attachment theory|insecure attachment]], and also founded PIPUK, the national charity for Parent Infant Partnerships which set up branches in four further counties since its inception.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pipuk.org.uk/|title=Our Story \u2013 pipuk|publisher=|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160712150552/http://www.pipuk.org.uk/|archivedate=12 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.norpip.org.uk/About/Trustees.aspx|title=NORPIP:Board of trustees|work=NORPIP Northamptonshire Parent Infant partnership|accessdate=2 February 2014|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140220120422/http://www.norpip.org.uk/About/Trustees.aspx|archivedate=20 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2012/nov/27/andrea-leadsom-lobbying-parents-children|title=Andrea Leadsom: lobbying for more support for parents and children|first=Susanna|last=Rustin|date=27 November 2012|work=The Guardian|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826025026/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2012/nov/27/andrea-leadsom-lobbying-parents-children|archivedate=26 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> NORPIP was originally set up with funding from the Ana Leaf Foundation, of which Leadsom's sister Hayley, wife of [[Peter de Putron]], is a trustee.<ref>\nDavid Pegg and Holly Watt, [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/06/andrea-leadsom-political-links-peter-de-putron-tory-leadership How close are Andrea Leadsom's political links with Peter de Putron?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201230320/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/06/andrea-leadsom-political-links-peter-de-putron-tory-leadership |date=1 December 2016 }}, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 6 July 2016</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShe married business manager Ben Leadsom in 1993 and has two sons and one daughter.<ref name=ww /> Following the birth of her first child, she suffered from [[postnatal depression]] for several months.<ref name=\"lobby\">{{cite news|last1=Rustin|first1=Susanna|title=Andrea Leadsom: lobbying for more support for parents and children|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2012/nov/27/andrea-leadsom-lobbying-parents-children|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=The Guardian|date=27 November 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826025026/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2012/nov/27/andrea-leadsom-lobbying-parents-children|archivedate=26 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nLeadsom states that [[Christianity]] has a central role in her life. She told Tim Ross of ''The Daily Telegraph'': \"I am a very committed Christian. I think my values and everything I do is driven by that.\" She participates in \"various [[Bible study (Christianity)|Bible studies]] groups\" with other parliamentarians and prays \"all the time\"<ref name=telegraph-20160702 /> and has discussed her Christian faith openly in a video hosted on the website of the all party [[parliamentary group]] Christians in Parliament.<ref name=telegraph-20160702 /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.christiansinparliament.org.uk/members-stories/andrea-leadsom-mp/ |title=Andrea Leadsom MP \u2013 Members' Stories |publisher=Christians in Parliament |date= |accessdate=10 July 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625072234/http://www.christiansinparliament.org.uk/members-stories/andrea-leadsom-mp/ |archivedate=25 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/redbox/topic/tory-leadership-race/andrea-leadsom-became-mp-to-stop-nuclear-holocaust |title=Andrea Leadsom wanted to be MP to stop 'nuclear holocaust' |work=The Times |date= |accessdate=10 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{notelist}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.andrealeadsom.com/ Official website]\n* {{UK MP links\n| parliament   = andrea-leadsom/4117\n| hansard      =\n| hansardcurr  =\n| guardian     =\n| publicwhip   = Andrea_Leadsom\n| theywork     = 24829/andrea_leadsom/south_northamptonshire\n| record       =\n| bbc          = 40456.stm\n| journalisted =\n}}\n* [https://archive.is/20140410001824/http://www.debretts.com/people-of-today/profile/26866/Andrea-Jacqueline-LEADSOM Debrett's People of Today]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[South Northamptonshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Northamptonshire]]|years=[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Nicky Morgan]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Economic Secretary to the Treasury]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Harriett Baldwin]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sajid Javid]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[City Minister]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Matthew Hancock]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department of Energy and Climate Change|Minister of State for Energy]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lucy Neville-Rolfe]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Elizabeth Truss|Liz Truss]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]]|years=2016\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Michael Gove]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[David Lidington]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Leader of the House of Commons]]|years=2017\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Mel Stride]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lord President of the Council]]|years=2017\u20132019}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Greg Clark]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy]]|years=2019\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Alok Sharma]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Johnson Cabinet}}\n{{Leader of the House of Commons}}\n{{Secretary of State for Environment}}\n{{First May Cabinet}}\n{{Second May Cabinet}}\n{{2016 Conservative Party leadership election}}\n{{2019 Conservative Party leadership election}}\n{{East Midlands Conservative Party MPs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leadsom, Andrea}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Warwick]]\n[[Category:British Secretaries of State for the Environment]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Critics of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Economic Secretaries to the Treasury]]\n[[Category:English bankers]]\n[[Category:English Christians]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Cabinet of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Lord Presidents of the Council]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Aylesbury]]\n[[Category:People from Buckinghamshire]]\n[[Category:People from Northamptonshire]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Northamptonshire]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Andrea Leadsom\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Rt Hon Andrea Leadsom MP crop 2.jpg\n| caption = Leadsom in 2020\n| office = [[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy]]\n| primeminister = [[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start = 24 July 2019\n| term_end = 13 February 2020\n| predecessor = [[Greg Clark]]\n| successor = [[Alok Sharma]]\n| office1 = [[Leader of the House of Commons]]<br />[[Lord President of the Council]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start1 = 11 June 2017\n| term_end1 = 22 May 2019\n| predecessor1 = [[David Lidington]]\n| successor1 = [[Mel Stride]]\n| office2 = [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start2 = 14 July 2016\n| term_end2 = 11 June 2017\n| predecessor2 = [[Elizabeth Truss]]\n| successor2 = [[Michael Gove]]\n| office3 = [[Department of Energy and Climate Change|Minister of State for Energy]]\n| primeminister3 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start3 = 11 May 2015\n| term_end3 = 14 July 2016\n| predecessor3 = [[Matt Hancock]]\n| successor3 = [[Claire Perry]]\n| office4 = [[Economic Secretary to the Treasury]]\n| primeminister4 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start4 = 9 April 2014\n| term_end4 = 11 May 2015\n| predecessor4 = [[Nicky Morgan]]\n| successor4 = [[Harriett Baldwin]]\n| office5 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[South Northamptonshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Northamptonshire]]\n| term_start5 = 6 May 2010\n| term_end5 = \n| predecessor5 = ''Constituency recreated''\n| successor5 = \n| majority5 = 27,761 (41.5%)\n| birth_name = Andrea Jacqueline Salmon\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1963|5|13|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Aylesbury]], [[Buckinghamshire]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| signature = \n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Ben Leadsom|1993}}\n| children = 3\n| education = [[Tonbridge Grammar School]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Warwick]]\n}}\n'''Andrea Jacqueline Leadsom''' ({{IPAc-en|'|l|\u025b|d|s|\u0259m}};<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tHy2ANVEIvc|title=Andrea Leadsom on Newsnight|last=Anna Firth|date=29 April 2016|publisher=|via=YouTube|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707155835/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tHy2ANVEIvc|archivedate=7 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''{{n\u00e9e}}'' '''Salmon'''; born 13 May 1963)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36676170|title =Tory contender: Andrea Leadsom|website = [[BBC News]]|date = 11 July 2016|accessdate = 8 August 2018}}</ref> is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician who served as [[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy]] from 2019 to 2020, and has served as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[South Northamptonshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Northamptonshire]] since [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59418 |date=13 May 2010 |page=8744}}</ref><ref>[http://www.andrealeadsom.com/ Home] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915121112/http://www.andrealeadsom.com/ |date=15 September 2015 }}. Andrea Leadsom. Retrieved 8 May 2012.</ref> Leadsom served as the [[Leader of the House of Commons]] from 2017 to 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/andrealeadsom/status/1131267480742236160?s=21 |title=Andrea Leadsom MP |website=Twitter |accessdate=22 May 2019 |url-status = live|df=dmy-all }}</ref> Leadsom has twice run to become [[Leader of the Conservative Party (UK)|Leader of the Conservative Party]], in 2016 and 2019.\n\nAfter graduating with a degree in political science at the [[University of Warwick]], she began a career in Finance including working as Institutional Banking Director at [[Barclays]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/5829a293e4fcb505194767d9/t/586fc5279de4bbdef29211ed/1483719978641/IBD+Job+Description.pdf|title=Andrea Leadsom Institutional Banking Director|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> and later as Senior Investment Officer and Head of Corporate Governance at Invesco Perpetual.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/leadsoms-resume-controversy-overblown-her-former-supervisor-says-1468000457|title=Leadsom's R\u00e9sum\u00e9 Controversy Overblown, Her Former Supervisor Says|last=Mackintosh|first=James|date=2016-07-08|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2018-10-17|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\nLeadsom was a prominent member of the [[Vote Leave|Leave campaign]] during the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 EU referendum]], and gained standing in referendum TV debates.<ref name=\"ITV Report\">{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2016-06-30/who-is-conservative-leadership-contender-andrea-leadsom|title=Who is Conservative leadership contender Andrea Leadsom?|accessdate=11 July 2016|date=30 June 2016|publisher=|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710151049/http://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2016-06-30/who-is-conservative-leadership-contender-andrea-leadsom/|archivedate=10 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On [[David Cameron]]'s resignation, Leadsom became one of five candidates in the [[2016 Conservative Party leadership election|election for the leadership of the governing Conservative Party]], and thereby for the role of [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]]. In the second round of voting by MPs, she came second to [[Theresa May]].<ref name=\"Bulman\">{{cite news |last=Bulman |first=May |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-tory-leadership-contest-conservative-election-theresa-may-read-speech-in-full-a7130746.html |title=Andrea Leadsom quits Tory leadership contest |work=The Independent |location=London |date=11 July 2016 |access-date=11 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711131211/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-tory-leadership-contest-conservative-election-theresa-may-read-speech-in-full-a7130746.html |archivedate=11 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> May appointed Leadsom as [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]].\n\nLeadsom served in the [[First May ministry|May Government]] as [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Environment Secretary]] from 2016 to 2017. She had previously served in the [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition]] as [[Minister of State]] for Energy at the [[Department of Energy and Climate Change]] from 2015 to 2016, and [[Economic Secretary to the Treasury]] and [[City Minister]] from 2014 to 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/andrea-leadsom |title=Andrea Leadsom MP |website=GOV.UK |accessdate=27 June 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630130408/https://www.gov.uk/government/people/andrea-leadsom |archivedate=30 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Following the [[snap election]] of [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]], Leadsom was appointed [[Lord President of the Council]] and Leader of the House of Commons. On 22 May 2019, she resigned in protest at May's Brexit strategy. Two days later, May announced her resignation as party leader, taking effect on 7 June.<ref>{{cite news |title=Latest as May makes statement outside No 10 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-politics-48394091 |accessdate=24 May 2019 |work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nShe stood to be leader of the Conservative Party in June 2019 but was eliminated in the first round of voting, finishing 8th out of 10 candidates with 11 votes.<ref>{{cite news|title=Out of race to be Leader|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jun/13/andrea-leadsom-and-esther-mcvey-out-of-race-to-be-tory-leader}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and financial career ==\nLeadsom was born in [[Aylesbury]], Buckinghamshire, the daughter of Richard and Judy Salmon (''n\u00e9e'' Kitchin).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bucksherald.co.uk/news/more-news/aylesbury-born-andrea-leadsom-could-be-country-s-new-prime-minister-1-7464615 |title=Aylesbury-born Andrea Leadsom could be country's new Prime Minister |publisher=Bucksherald.co.uk |date=6 July 2016 |accessdate=10 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160712062708/http://www.bucksherald.co.uk/news/more-news/aylesbury-born-andrea-leadsom-could-be-country-s-new-prime-minister-1-7464615 |archivedate=12 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She attended [[Tonbridge Grammar School|Tonbridge Girls' Grammar School]], then read [[Political Science]] at the [[University of Warwick]].<ref name=ww >'LEADSOM, Andrea Jacqueline', Who's Who 2013, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 2013; online edn, Oxford University Press, Dec 2012; online edn, Nov 2012 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U251154, accessed 2 Jan 2013]</ref>\n\nAfter graduation, Leadsom began a career in the [[financial industry|financial sector]] as a debt trader for [[Barclays de Zoete Wedd]], then the investment bank division of [[Barclays Bank]].<ref name=\"Arnold\">{{cite news|last=Arnold|first=Martin|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/89ff6b1e-4204-11e6-b22f-79eb4891c97d.html#axzz4DZ9bXPug|title=Leadsom forced to account for financial history|work=Financial Times|location=London|date=4 July 2016|accessdate=5 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160708125253/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/89ff6b1e-4204-11e6-b22f-79eb4891c97d.html#axzz4DZ9bXPug|archivedate=8 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> For Barclays itself, she served as Deputy Director in the Financial Institutions team from 1993; this involved the maintenance of contractual relationships with other banks.<ref name=\"reaction\" /> In this role, she said she was given a \"ringside seat\" in the collapse of [[Barings Bank]].<ref name=\"lessons\">{{cite news|last1=Leadsom|first1=Andrea|title=Andrea Leadsom: The lessons about banking regulation which stay with me from the collapse of Barings|url=http://www.conservativehome.com/platform/2009/08/andrea-leadsom-the-lessons-about-banking-regulation-which-we-must-stay-with-us-from-the-collapse-of.html|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=ConservativeHome|date=18 August 2009|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807015108/http://www.conservativehome.com/platform/2009/08/andrea-leadsom-the-lessons-about-banking-regulation-which-we-must-stay-with-us-from-the-collapse-of.html|archivedate=7 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Leadsom clashed with the head of Barclays Investments who tried to persuade her to return to full-time work soon after a pregnancy, and she left the company in 1997.<ref name=\"Arnold\"/> Later, in July 2016, she submitted a CV which showed that she had served as Deputy Director.{{clarify|date=January 2020}<ref>{{cite web|title=Andrea Leadsom revises 'exaggerated' CV|url=https://next.ft.com/content/3a531ec4-4396-11e6-b22f-79eb4891c97d|accessdate=6 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1997 to 1999, Leadsom served as Managing Director of De Putron Fund Management (DPFM).<ref>{{cite news|last=Goodley|first=Simon|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/04/andrea-leadsoms-the-city-high-profile-roles-under-radar-barclays-brexit-negotiations|title=Andrea Leadsom's time in the City: high-profile roles yet under the radar|work=The Guardian|date=4 July 2016|accessdate=5 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160705150149/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/04/andrea-leadsoms-the-city-high-profile-roles-under-radar-barclays-brexit-negotiations|archivedate=5 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1998 she was promoted to board director for marketing.<ref name=CoCheck>{{cite web|title=MS ANDREA JACQUELINE SALMON|url=https://companycheck.co.uk/director/905929405/ANDREA-JACQUELINE-SALMON/companies|website=Company Check|accessdate=10 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826113445/https://companycheck.co.uk/director/905929405/ANDREA-JACQUELINE-SALMON/companies|archivedate=26 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nLeadsom was Head of Corporate Governance and a Senior Investment Officer at [[Invesco Perpetual]] from 1999 to 2009.<ref name=ww /><ref>{{cite web|title=Andrea Leadsom|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/andrea-leadsom|website=UK.Gov|accessdate=29 June 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630130408/https://www.gov.uk/government/people/andrea-leadsom|archivedate=30 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Her role was to work (sometimes part-time) on \u201cspecial projects\u201d, mostly for the Chief Investment Officer, which included negotiating pay terms for senior fund managers. Towards the end of her time, she advised on a number of governance issues, but she had no-one reporting to her in either role.<ref name=\"reaction\">{{cite web |author=Robert Stephens|title=Was Andrea Leadsom really such a City hotshot?|url=http://reaction.life/was-andrea-leadsom-really-such-a-city-hotshot/|website=reaction.life|accessdate=5 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160705171700/http://reaction.life/was-andrea-leadsom-really-such-a-city-hotshot/ |archivedate=5 July 2016 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> A former colleague, knew Leadsom when she was working in corporate governance.{{clarify|date=January 2020}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/04/andrea-leadsoms-the-city-high-profile-roles-under-radar-barclays-brexit-negotiations|title=Andrea Leadsom's time in the City: high-profile roles yet under the radar|last=Goodley|first=Simon|date=2016-07-04|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-02-23|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Approval for individuals to manage funds or deal with clients is needed from the financial services regulator (then the [[Financial Services Authority]]), which Leadsom held{{clarify|date=July 2016}} from December 2002 to February 2003.{{clarify|date=January 2020}<ref name=\"Kenber\">{{cite news|last1=Kenber|first1=Billy|last2=Wison|first2=Harry|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/leadsom-admits-misleading-claims-on-cv-for-top-job-n80lgc2rj|title=Leadsom admits 'misleading' claims on CV for top job|work=The Times|location=London|date=6 July 2016|accessdate=6 July 2016}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Leadsom has never claimed to have personally been a fund manager, and Bob Yerbury, former Chief Investment Officer at Invesco Perpetual and Leadsom's former manager, dismissed the controversy about how she described her time there and described her as \"totally honest\".<ref name=\"Mackintosh\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/leadsoms-resume-controversy-overblown-her-former-supervisor-says-1468000457|title=Leadsom's R\u00e9sum\u00e9 Controversy Overblown, Her Former Supervisor Says|first=James|last=Mackintosh|date=8 July 2016|publisher=|via=Wall Street Journal|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161108043622/http://www.wsj.com/articles/leadsoms-resume-controversy-overblown-her-former-supervisor-says-1468000457|archivedate=8 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>{{clarify|date=January 2020}\n\nLeadsom was a [[Councillor]] on [[South Oxfordshire District Council]] between 2003 and 2007.<ref name=ww /><ref name=parl>[http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/andrea-leadsom/4117 Andrea Leadsom] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630130409/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/Andrea-Leadsom/4117 |date=30 June 2016 }}, www.parliament.org. Retrieved 2 January 2013.</ref>\n\nShe contested the safe labour seat of [[Knowsley South]] constituency in the [[United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]]<ref name=ww /><ref name=parl /> unsuccessfully and finished in third place, despite this, the incumbent Labour MPs majority was reduced significantly. She was subsequently placed on the [[A-List (Conservative)|Conservative A-List]]<ref>[http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2009/04/the-18-of-the-original-100-alisters-selected-for-conservative-seats-.html ConservativeHome's Seats & Candidates blog: Where are the original A-Listers now? The 18 who have been selected for Conservative seats] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141028112024/http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2009/04/the-18-of-the-original-100-alisters-selected-for-conservative-seats-.html |date=28 October 2014 }}. Conservativehome.blogs.com (21 April 2009). Retrieved 8 May 2012.</ref> and later chosen to represent the newly created seat of South Northamptonshire.\n\n== Political career ==\n\n=== Member of Parliament ===\nLeadsom was selected to stand as the parliamentary candidate in the newly-created [[South Northamptonshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Northamptonshire]] constituency in June 2006. In 2009, [[ConservativeHome]] said that she was \"defending a notional Conservative majority of 11,356.\"<ref name=\"diary\">{{cite news|last1=Leadsom|first1=Andrea|title=Diary of a PPC: Andrea Leadsom (South Northamptonshire)|url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2009/06/diary-of-a-ppc-andrea-leadsom-south-northamptonshire.html|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=ConservativeHome|date=8 June 2009|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817152815/http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2009/06/diary-of-a-ppc-andrea-leadsom-south-northamptonshire.html|archivedate=17 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] in May, Leadsom was elected with a majority of more than 20,000. On entering the House of Commons she was elected as a member of the [[Treasury Select Committee]].<ref name=parl /> She made her [[maiden speech]] on 22 June 2010 during the budget debate, when she spoke of restoring health to the financial sector, drawing from personal experience in [[financial regulation]], particularly with [[Barings Bank]].<ref name=\"maiden\">{{cite news|last1=Isaby|first1=Jonathan|title=Andrea Leadsom draws on her City experience in her maiden speech to explain how to restore the financial services sector to health|url=http://www.conservativehome.com/thetorydiary/2010/06/andrea-leadsom-draws-on-her-city-experience-in-her-maiden-speech-to-explain-how-to-restore-the-finan.html|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=ConservativeHome|date=23 June 2010|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807011712/http://www.conservativehome.com/thetorydiary/2010/06/andrea-leadsom-draws-on-her-city-experience-in-her-maiden-speech-to-explain-how-to-restore-the-finan.html|archivedate=7 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nLeadsom campaigned for EU reform. In September 2011, she co-founded the [[Fresh Start Project]] with Conservative MPs [[Chris Heaton-Harris]] and [[George Eustice]] to \"research and build support for realistic and far-reaching proposals for reforming the EU\".<ref name=\"eureform\">{{cite web|title=European Reform|url=http://www.andrealeadsom.com/parliamentary/european-reform|website=Andrea Leadsom|accessdate=2 July 2016|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141121130837/http://www.andrealeadsom.com/parliamentary/european-reform|archivedate=21 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=telegraph-20160702>{{cite news|last=Ross|first=Tim|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/02/andrea-leadsom-interview-thatcher-god-and-why-i-should-be-prime/|title=Andrea Leadsom interview: Thatcher, God and why I should be Prime Minister|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|date=2 July 2016|accessdate=2 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703000804/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/02/andrea-leadsom-interview-thatcher-god-and-why-i-should-be-prime/|archivedate=3 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 25 October 2011, Leadsom was one of 81 Conservative MPs to defy the party whip and vote in favour of holding a referendum on the UK's membership of the [[European Union]].<ref name=\"euscep\">{{cite news|title=Eurosceptics: UKIP's Lord Hesketh and Andrea Leadsom MP|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-15578224|accessdate=2 July 2016|publisher=BBC News|date=3 November 2011|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160706043505/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-15578224|archivedate=6 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This led to a sharp ruction with the [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], [[George Osborne]], at the time, which she denies.<ref name=\"osborne\">{{cite news|title=General Election 2015: Tory backbenchers tip rising star Andrea Leadsom as successor to David Cameron as party leader |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/generalelection/general-election-2015-tory-backbenchers-tip-rising-star-andrea-leadsom-as-successor-to-david-cameron-10204409.html |accessdate=9 July 2016|work=The Independent |date=25 April 2015 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160709154517/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/generalelection/general-election-2015-tory-backbenchers-tip-rising-star-andrea-leadsom-as-successor-to-david-cameron-10204409.html |archivedate= 9 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2012, during the [[Libor scandal]], she was widely reported on for her contribution to the Treasury Select Committee's questioning of [[Bob Diamond (banker)|Bob Diamond]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/its-fair-to-say-we-were-useless-against-diamond--leadsom-7923536.html |title='It's fair to say we were useless against Diamond'&nbsp;\u2013 Leadsom |first=Oliver |last=Wright |work=The Independent |date=9 July 2012 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120814134718/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/its-fair-to-say-we-were-useless-against-diamond--leadsom-7923536.html |archivedate=14 August 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/07/04/bob-diamonds-evidence-barclays-libor-fixing_n_1649335.html |title= Bob Diamond's Evidence On Barclays Libor Fixing: What Do We Now Know? |work= Huffington Post |date= 3 September 2012 | accessdate = 9 July 2016| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160709152426/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/07/04/bob-diamonds-evidence-barclays-libor-fixing_n_1649335.html |archivedate= 9 July 2016}}</ref> At a subsequent hearing she questioned [[Paul Tucker (banker)|Paul Tucker]], who stated that the previous government had not conspired with the Bank to fix rates. In a BBC interview, Leadsom stated that the suggestion \"has now been completely squashed by Paul Tucker\", and that on that specific point, George Osborne might want to apologise to Shadow Chancellor [[Ed Balls]] for \"suggesting he was implicated in rate fixing\", although she also pointed out that Balls \"still [had] a huge amount to answer for in relation to the scandal and his time in office\".<ref name=lib>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-18778111|title=Libor scandal: William Hague rejects Ed Balls apology calls|publisher=BBC News|date=10 July 2012|accessdate=10 July 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120710165657/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-18778111|archivedate=10 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Mike Smithson (politics)|Mike Smithson]] suggested this could be a reason for Osborne to overlook her for a promotion in the 2012 cabinet reshuffle, despite the fact that \"in terms of talent she must be right at the top of the list of 2010 newbies who should be promoted.\"<ref name=\"blackball\">{{cite news|last1=Smithson|first1=Mike|title=Will Osborne black-ball a promotion for Andrea?|url=http://www2.politicalbetting.com/index.php/archives/2012/07/10/will-osborne-blockade-promotion-for-andrea/|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=Political Betting|date=10 July 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818071016/http://www2.politicalbetting.com/index.php/archives/2012/07/10/will-osborne-blockade-promotion-for-andrea/|archivedate=18 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2012, Leadsom was ranked 91 on [[Iain Dale]]'s list of top 100 most influential figures from the right.<ref name=\"influe\">{{cite news|last1=Dale|first1=Iain|title=Iain Dale's Top 100 most influential figures from the Right 2012|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/9589957/Iain-Dales-Top-100-most-influential-figures-from-the-Right-2012.html|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=7 October 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012142918/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/9589957/Iain-Dales-Top-100-most-influential-figures-from-the-Right-2012.html|archivedate=12 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nLeadsom was one of five MPs to abstain from the Government's [[Marriage (Same Sex Couples) Act 2013|Marriage (Same Sex Couples) Bill]] by voting in both lobbies.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lowther|first1=Ed|title=Yes but, no but... MPs who vote both ways|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-21591602|accessdate=1 April 2015|publisher=BBC|date=5 March 2013|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107164402/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-21591602|archivedate=7 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Leadsom had earlier said she found the wording of the legislation \"unacceptable\", and that voting no reflected the views of \"so many\" of her constituents, who felt that the bill was \"deeply wrong\",<ref>[http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2013/02/01/tory-northamptonshire-mp-i-support-the-love-of-gay-couples-but-it-is-unacceptable-for-them-to-be-able-to-marry/ \"Tory Northamptonshire MP: \"I support the love of gay couples but it is unacceptable for them to be able to marry\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130423101042/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2013/02/01/tory-northamptonshire-mp-i-support-the-love-of-gay-couples-but-it-is-unacceptable-for-them-to-be-able-to-marry/ |date=23 April 2013 }}, ''Pink News''. Retrieved 1 February 2013</ref> but ultimately chose to abstain, saying, \"I find myself genuinely torn...I cannot vote against a measure that would mean so much to the minority of homosexual couples for whom marriage is the ultimate recognition for their genuine feelings for each other. Yet nor can I vote for a measure that risks centuries of faith-based belief in marriage.\" During her Conservative Party leadership campaign in 2016, she stated she would have preferred a situation in which there were two types of services.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cowburn |first=Ashley |date=7 July 2016 |title=Andrea Ledsom: I didn't like gay marriage law because it hurts Christians |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-brexit-speech-conservative-leadership-election-next-tory-leader-a7124641.html |work=The Independent |location=London |access-date=8 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160708045908/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-brexit-speech-conservative-leadership-election-next-tory-leader-a7124641.html |archivedate=8 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Following the vote, Leadsom stated, \"I would like to make clear that I fully support the lifelong commitment that is made between any loving couple and that I believe the legal basis of a same sex marriage should be no different to that of a heterosexual couple.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.andrealeadsom.com/news/201326/same-sex-marriage|title=Same Sex Marriage|website=Andrea Leadsom|accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, Leadsom was appointed by [[David Cameron]] to the [[Number 10 Policy Unit]], with responsibility for part of the public services brief.<ref name=\"alloc\">{{cite news|title=New Number Ten Policy Board Job Allocation|url=http://order-order.com/2013/10/21/new-number-10-policy-board-job-allocation/|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=Guido Fawkes|date=21 October 2013|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818044036/http://order-order.com/2013/10/21/new-number-10-policy-board-job-allocation/|archivedate=18 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"sop\">{{cite news|last1=Church|first1=Dominic|title=No. 10 Policy Board \u2013 Serious Symposium or Sop?|url=http://www.westminsteradvisers.co.uk/2013/10/no-10-policy-board-serious-symposium-or-sop/|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=Westminster Advisers|date=17 October 2013|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161013054450/http://www.westminsteradvisers.co.uk/2013/10/no-10-policy-board-serious-symposium-or-sop/|archivedate=13 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Economic Secretary to the Treasury ===\nOn 9 April 2014 Leadsom was appointed [[Economic Secretary to the Treasury]] following [[Maria Miller]]'s resignation from the Cabinet. She was also given the additional responsibility of [[City Minister]], a post which had previously been held concurrently with the position of [[Financial Secretary to the Treasury]].<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.techuk.org/insights/news/item/1371-andrea-leadsom-mp-appointed-new-city-minister-within-hmt|title=Andrea Leadsom MP appointed new City Minister for HMT|publisher=Tech UK|date=10 April 2014|access-date=4 August 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815180524/https://www.techuk.org/insights/news/item/1371-andrea-leadsom-mp-appointed-new-city-minister-within-hmt|archivedate=15 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Leadsom received praise for her dealings with Icelandic Minister of Finance, Bjarni Benediktsson, for delivering \"an almighty dressing down from the fearsome Leadsom.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uti.is/2014/11/is-exit-tax-on-both-isk-and-fx-in-the-icelandic-christmas-crackers-this-year/|title=Is exit tax on both ISK and FX in the Icelandic Christmas crackers this year? at Sigr\u00fan Dav\u00ed\u00f0sd\u00f3ttir's Icelog|accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nLeadsom was instrumental in introducing the UK Government's first Islamic bonds, the [[Sukuk#United Kingdom|Sukuk]]. This was the first Islamic bond listed outside the Islamic world. Leadsom stated \"the strong demand for the Sukuk not only delivers good value for money for the taxpayer, but also cements Britain\u2019s position as the western hub of Islamic finance and is a part of our long term economic plan to make Britain the undisputed centre of the global financial system.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lseg.com/resources/media-centre/press-releases/london-stock-exchange-welcomes-uk-government%E2%80%99s-first-islamic-bond-listing|title=London Stock Exchange welcomes UK Government's first Islamic bond listing|website=London Stock Exchange Group|accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''[[Financial Times]]'', her period as City Minister was seen by departmental officials as \"a disaster\", \"the worst minister we ever had. \u2026 She found it difficult to understand issues or take decisions. She was monomaniacal, seeing the EU as the source of every problem. She alienated officials by continually complaining about poor drafting.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mance|first1=Henry|title=Andrea Leadsom seeks to play down pro-EU comments|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/5ec81170-4101-11e6-b22f-79eb4891c97d.html|work=Financial Times|date=4 July 2016|accessdate=6 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707023059/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/5ec81170-4101-11e6-b22f-79eb4891c97d.html|archivedate=7 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==== Inheritance tax ====\nIn about 1997, she formed the company Bandal with her husband, and bought property in [[Oxford]] and [[Surrey]]. The company was financed by loans from the Jersey arm of Kleinwort Benson, a private bank.<ref name=\"Arnold\"/> It was learned in 2014 that Leadsom had transferred her shares to a trust fund for her children.<ref name=\"Arnold\"/> A spokesman for Leadsom said: \"This is a normal corporate situation and all tax that is due is being paid. None of the loans for the properties are based offshore\".<ref name=\"Independent 17 April 2014\">{{cite news |last=Harper |first=Tom |date=17 April 2014 |title=Revealed: how City minister Andrea Leadsom used controversial trusts to reduce her potential inheritance-tax bill |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/revealed-how-city-minister-andrea-leadsom-used-controversial-trusts-to-reduce-her-potential-inheritancetax-bill-9268469.html |work=The Independent |location=London |accessdate=4 August 2014 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140625204516/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/revealed-how-city-minister-andrea-leadsom-used-controversial-trusts-to-reduce-her-potential-inheritancetax-bill-9268469.html |archivedate=25 June 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== Donations from family firm ====\nThere was further criticism in 2014 when ''[[The Independent]]'' revealed that she had received a series of donations totalling \u00a370,000 to pay for printing and research costs for the FSP over the course of three years. The company is owned by her brother in law, whose family is based in the [[British Virgin Islands]] .<ref name=\"Independent 13 July 2014\">{{cite news |last1=Armitage |first1=Jim |last2=McSmith |first2=Andy |last3=Harper |first3=Tom |date=13 July 2014 |title=Andrea Leadsom received \u00a370,000 donation from family firm with parent company controlled in tax haven |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-received-70000-donation-from-family-firm-with-parent-company-controlled-in-tax-haven-9603559.html |work=The Independent |location=London |accessdate=4 August 2014 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808052613/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-received-70000-donation-from-family-firm-with-parent-company-controlled-in-tax-haven-9603559.html |archivedate=8 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Leadsom's husband Ben is a director of the firm which made the donations, which were used to pay the salaries of staff in Leadsom's Westminster office after her election as MP; the firm has also made donations of \u00a3816,000 to the Conservative party.<ref name=\"Guardian 8 July 2014\">{{cite news |last1= Leigh |first1= David |last2= Ball |first2= James|authorlink=James Ball (journalist) |last3= Haddou |first3= Leila |date= 8 July 2014 |title= Top Tory has family link with offshore banker who gave party \u00a3800,000 |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jul/08/andrea-leadsom-family-links-offshore-bank-donations-tories |work= The Guardian |location= London |accessdate= 4 August 2014 |url-status = live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140716222434/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jul/08/andrea-leadsom-family-links-offshore-bank-donations-tories |archivedate= 16 July 2014 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> Because the firm making the donations, Gloucester Research (later becoming GR Software and Research), was based in London, the donations conformed to the rule banning political donations from abroad. The Labour MP [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]] said: \u201cThese very large donations might be within the rules, but it certainly isn\u2019t right that a Treasury minister has been taking money in this way. Most reasonable people will see this as completely unreasonable\u201d.<ref name=\"Independent 13 July 2014\" />\n\n=== Minister of State for Energy ===\nLeadsom was re-elected as MP for South Northamptonshire on 7 May 2015 with 36,607 votes, compared to her nearest rival Lucy Mills (Labour), with 10,191 votes. On 11 May 2015, Leadsom, who had previously opposed [[wind farm]]s and European [[Renewable energy in the European Union#Renewable energy targets|renewable energy targets]], was moved from Economic Secretary to the Treasury, to be appointed Minister of State at the Department of Energy and Climate Change, reporting to [[Amber Rudd]] who was promoted to Secretary of State at the same department.<ref>''Private Eye'' (2014). \"Andrea Leadsom: Family funds\", ''Private Eye'', Issue No. 1371, 25 July&nbsp;\u2013 7 August 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Murray|first1=James|title=Andrea Leadsom appointed as Energy and Climate Change Minister|url=http://www.businessgreen.com/bg/news/2408053/andrea-leadsom-appointed-as-energy-and-climate-change-minister|website=businessgreen|accessdate=11 June 2015|ref=BusinessGreen|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150612235519/http://www.businessgreen.com/bg/news/2408053/andrea-leadsom-appointed-as-energy-and-climate-change-minister|archivedate=12 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Leadsom announced the end of taxpayer funded subsidies for onshore wind farms, stating \"we now have enough onshore wind in the pipeline to be sufficient to meet our renewable electricity aims\". This was a year earlier than was originally planned and was in line with the Conservative Party Manifesto.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.andrealeadsom.com/news/20150609/onshore-wind|title=Fulfilling Our Onshore Wind Manifesto Commitments|website=Andrea Leadsom|accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Brexit campaign===\nLeadsom took a prominent role in the campaign to leave the EU in [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|June 2016]]. She argued that the [[Governor of the Bank of England|Governor]] of the [[Bank of England]], [[Mark Carney]], had destabilised financial markets and jeopardised the Bank's independence by warning of short-term negative effects on the economy caused by leaving the EU.<ref name=\"telegraph-20160429\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/29/mothers-should-vote-to-leave-says-brexiteer-minister-andrea-lead/|title=Mothers should vote to leave, says Brexiteer minister Andrea Leadsom|author=Andrea Leadsom|date=29 April 2016|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=24 May 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508102348/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/29/mothers-should-vote-to-leave-says-brexiteer-minister-andrea-lead/|archivedate=8 May 2016|url-status = live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian-20160515\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/15/brexit-minister-bank-of-england-dangerous-intervention-andrea-leadsom-financial-markets-eu|title=Brexit minister accuses Bank of England of 'dangerous intervention'|author=Rowena Mason|date=15 May 2016|work=The Guardian|accessdate=24 May 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160520231223/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/may/15/brexit-minister-bank-of-england-dangerous-intervention-andrea-leadsom-financial-markets-eu|archivedate=20 May 2016|url-status = live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn a televised debate on the referendum, Leadsom appeared on the \"Leave\" panel, along with [[Gisela Stuart]] and [[Boris Johnson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-politics-eu-referendum-35603388|title=Reality Check: The EU referendum|date=23 February 2016|publisher=BBC News|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626184347/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-politics-eu-referendum-35603388|archivedate=26 June 2016|url-status = live|accessdate=27 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She disputed claims that the UK should pursue single market membership, saying that 80% of the world's economy, and most EU free-trade deals, are not within the single market. She also said that the UK economy is too large to need the single market, but is hindered by the slowness of EU trade procedures.<ref name=\"wilkinson\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/21/eu-debate-boris-johnson-vs-sadiq-khan-in-final-bbc-showdown-with/|title=EU debate: Boris Johnson says Brexit will be 'Britain's independence day' as Ruth Davidson attacks 'lies' of Leave campaign in front of 6,000-strong Wembley audience|author=Wilkinson, Michael|date=21 June 2016|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160704201901/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/21/eu-debate-boris-johnson-vs-sadiq-khan-in-final-bbc-showdown-with/|archivedate=4 July 2016|url-status = live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Conservative leadership election, 2016 ===\n{{main|2016 Conservative Party leadership election}}\n{{overly detailed|section=yes|date=July 2016}}\nImmediately following the referendum vote on 23 June 2016 for Britain to leave the EU, [[David Cameron]] announced that he would resign as leader of the Conservative Party and Prime Minister by October. Leadsom was one of the early favourites to become the next Prime Minister, and was also linked with a possible role as Chancellor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2016-06-24/south-northamptonshire-mp-leadsom-emerges-as-one-of-the-favourites-to-be-next-pm/ |title=South Northamptonshire MP Leadsom emerges as one of the favourites to be next PM |work=ITV News |accessdate=27 June 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160627055021/http://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2016-06-24/south-northamptonshire-mp-leadsom-emerges-as-one-of-the-favourites-to-be-next-pm/ |archivedate=27 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 30 June 2016 she announced her [[2016 Conservative Party (UK) leadership election|candidacy]] to become [[Leader of the Conservative Party (UK)|leader of the Conservative Party]].  Leadsom said she would trigger [[s:Consolidated version of the Treaty on European Union/Title VI: Final Provisions#Article 50|Article 50]] immediately upon becoming Prime Minister, and conduct swift negotiations with the European Union.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-07-04/leadsom-launches-u-k-leadership-bid-vowing-short-brexit-talks |title=Leadsom Starts U.K. Leadership Bid Vowing Short Brexit Talks |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=4 July 2016 |access-date=5 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160704115720/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-07-04/leadsom-launches-u-k-leadership-bid-vowing-short-brexit-talks |archivedate=4 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn the first round of voting on 5 July 2016, [[Theresa May]] received support from 165 MPs, while Leadsom came second with 66 votes.<ref>{{cite news |title=Conservative leadership election: Theresa May wins more than half of MPs' votes as Liam Fox is knocked out of race |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2016/jul/05/brexit-live-tory-leadership-tom-watson-unions-jeremy-corbyn?page=with:block-577bee87e4b0445bf0e06ef6#block-577bee87e4b0445bf0e06ef6 |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=5 July 2016 |access-date=5 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160708142903/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2016/jul/05/brexit-live-tory-leadership-tom-watson-unions-jeremy-corbyn?page=with:block-577bee87e4b0445bf0e06ef6#block-577bee87e4b0445bf0e06ef6 |archivedate=8 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In the second ballot, Leadsom came second with 84 votes. [[Michael Gove]] was eliminated with 46 votes. [[Theresa May]] received 199 votes. On 11 July 2016, Leadsom announced she would be withdrawing her leadership bid, leaving [[Theresa May]] as the successor to [[David Cameron]].<ref name=\"bbc36763208\">{{cite news|title=Andrea Leadsom quits Conservative leadership race|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36763208|accessdate=11 July 2016|work=BBC News|date=11 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711120043/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36763208|archivedate=11 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Interviews====\nIn a BBC interview on 7 July 2016, Leadsom spoke of her disappointment about plotting in the leadership race, including alleged attempts by opponents to block her from the final ballot. She dismissed as \"ridiculous\" accusations that her biography was misleading, saying that her \"incredibly varied\" CV is \"all absolutely true\".<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36730216 |title=Tory leadership: Leadsom says CV criticism is 'ridiculous' |date=7 July 2016 |publisher=BBC News |access-date=7 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707075202/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36730216 |archivedate=7 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nLeadsom promised to \"banish the pessimists\" and to provide prosperity for the UK if elected, and stated that she was committed to fair trade.<ref name=\"cowburn\">{{cite news |last=Cowburn |first=Ashley |date=7 July 2016 |title=Andrea Leadsom: I didn't like gay marriage law because it hurts Christians, admits Tory contender to be PM |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-brexit-speech-conservative-leadership-election-next-tory-leader-a7124641.html |work=The Independent |location=London |access-date=7 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707114316/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-brexit-speech-conservative-leadership-election-next-tory-leader-a7124641.html |archivedate=7 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She also stated that she would review the Hunting Act with a focus on animal welfare if elected, and was asked about her concerns over the legislation passed to introduce same sex marriage.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Heather |date=7 July 2016 |title=Next PM to be woman as Theresa May and Andrea Leadsom win MPs' vote |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/07/theresa-may-andrea-leadsom-tory-leader-prime-minister |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=8 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707174549/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/07/theresa-may-andrea-leadsom-tory-leader-prime-minister |archivedate=7 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Prior to 2017 election Leadsom advised Theresa May not to repeat her promise to allow parliamentary time to discuss repealing the hunting ban, but was overruled.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/may-forced-through-toxic-manifesto-hunting-pledge-lzqtxbq32|title=May forced through 'toxic' manifesto hunting pledge|last=Editor|first=Francis Elliott, Political|date=27 November 2017|via=www.thetimes.co.uk|accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref>  She also criticised her rival Theresa May's plan to use the status of EU nationals living in the UK as \"bargaining chips\", promising that if she was elected they could stay.<ref name=\"cowburn\" />\n\n==== Alleged exaggeration of pre-government jobs and responsibilities ====\nOn 6 July 2016 ''[[The Times]]'' and other news media published articles which said that Leadsom had overstated her private sector experience and responsibilities.<ref name=\"Kenber\" /> They said that despite references her supporters had made to her managing \"billions of pounds in funds\" and her impressive-sounding job titles, she had held financial services regulator approval for only a brief three-month period in 10 years at Invesco Perpetual, and quoted former colleagues who said that she had exaggerated her level of involvement and her management responsibilities.<ref name=\"indy06072016\" /> Bob Yerbury, former Chief Investment Officer at Invesco Perpetual and Leadsom's former manager, dismissed the controversy about how she described her time there and described her as \"totally honest\".<ref name=\"Mackintosh\" />\n\n[[Penny Mordaunt]], a Leadsom supporter, described the reports as \"a concerted effort to rubbish a stellar career\".<ref name=\"indy06072016\">{{cite news |last=Stone |first=Jon |date=6 July 2016 |title=Andrea Leadsom accused of 'misleading' claims on her CV |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-accused-of-misleading-claims-on-her-cv-a7122296.html |work=The Independent |location=London |access-date=6 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160706094136/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-accused-of-misleading-claims-on-her-cv-a7122296.html |archivedate=6 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Weaver |first=Matthew |date=6 July 2016 |title=Penny Mordaunt defends Leadsom Tory leadership bid |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/06/andrea-leadsom-penny-mordaunt-tory-leadership |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=6 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707150143/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/06/andrea-leadsom-penny-mordaunt-tory-leadership |archivedate=7 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Leadsom then issued an amended CV, which ''[[The Guardian]]'' listed both deputy financial institutions director, and financial institutions director roles at Barclays.\"<ref name=\"Kenber\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Bowers |first=Simon |date=6 July 2016 |title=Publication of Andrea Leadsom's CV prompts new questions about her career |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/06/andrea-leadsoms-cv-prompts-new-questions-about-career |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=6 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707154944/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/06/andrea-leadsoms-cv-prompts-new-questions-about-career |archivedate=7 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/07/the-day-mps-marched-for-andrea-leadsom-the-woman-who-really-coul/ |title=The day MPs marched for Andrea Leadsom... the woman who really could be our next prime minister |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710075844/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/07/the-day-mps-marched-for-andrea-leadsom-the-woman-who-really-coul/ |archivedate=10 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Leadsom defended her CV in a BBC interview, saying claims of it being exaggerated were \"ridiculous\". \"I have not changed my CV,\" she said. \"I was always very clear; I was senior investment officer working very closely with the chief investment officer. I have been very clear; I'm not a funds manager. I was, in Barclays and BZW, managing huge teams of people and large budgets and responsible for the trading relationships. To be very careful not to mislead, Barclays is a very big player in the large corporate and institutional banking world, and so the trading relationships are enormous \u2013 billions and billions and billions of pounds. So, when I was there as the financial institutions director [sic] responsible for UK banking relationship, the responsibility was for billions of pounds of trading lines and facilities to those companies \u2026 I've never said I was a fund manager and I've never been a fund manager\", she said.<ref name=\"GPolLive7Jul2016\">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Leadsom says she was never a fund manager |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2016/jul/07/gove-leadsom-tory-leadership-vote-final-two-politics-live?page=with:block-577e3a3fe4b07cec9883d3fa#block-577e3a3fe4b07cec9883d3fa |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=7 July 2016 |access-date=7 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710225253/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2016/jul/07/gove-leadsom-tory-leadership-vote-final-two-politics-live?page=with:block-577e3a3fe4b07cec9883d3fa#block-577e3a3fe4b07cec9883d3fa |archivedate=10 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> According to [[Financial Services Authority|FSA]] records she was authorised to run money for only three months.<ref name=\"Kenber\" /><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://register.fca.org.uk/ShPo_IndividualDetailsPage?id=003b000000KTEIHAA5|website=The Financial Services Register|title=Ms Andrea Jacqueline Salmon|accessdate=10 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Comments about motherhood ====\nLeadsom's comments in an interview with ''[[The Times]]'' were interpreted as hinting that her being a mother meant that she was a better choice for Prime Minister than May, who has not been able to have children for health reasons, because it meant that she had \"a very real stake\" in the future.<ref name=\"Coates\">{{cite news|last1=Coates|first1=Sam|last2=Sylvester|first2=Rachel|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/being-a-mother-gives-me-edge-on-may-leadsom-0t7bbm29x|title=Being a mother gives me edge on May \u2014 Leadsom|work=The Times|location=London|date=9 July 2016|accessdate=9 July 2016}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=\"graun09072016\">{{cite news|last=Sparrow|first=Andrew|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/08/andrea-leadsom-suggests-she-would-make-better-pm-as-she-has-children|title=Leadsom attacks 'gutter journalism' in row over motherhood quotes|work=The Guardian|date=9 July 2016|accessdate=9 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160708234309/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/08/andrea-leadsom-suggests-she-would-make-better-pm-as-she-has-children|archivedate=8 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She said that she \"did not want this to be 'Andrea has children, Theresa hasn't' because I think that would be really horrible\".<ref name=\"Coates\" /> After ''The Times'' published the story, with the headline \"Being a mother gives me an edge on May\", Leadsom said that she was \"disgusted\" by the article, which was the \"exact opposite of what I said\".<ref name=\"BBC090716\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36752865|title=Andrea Leadsom 'motherhood' comments spark row|publisher=BBC News|date=9 July 2016|accessdate=9 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160709021056/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36752865|archivedate=9 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''The Times'' later released a partial transcript of the comments, and when Leadsom supporter [[Penny Mordaunt]] said that it was trying to \"smear\" Leadsom, ''The Times'' released an audio recording.<ref name=\"BBC090716\" />  Her comments were widely criticised<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2016/jul/11/blue-quartets-hostility-to-andrea-leadsom-reduces-her-to-tears|title=Rightwing papers' hostility to Andrea Leadsom reduces her to tears|first=Roy|last=Greenslade|date=11 July 2016|work=The Guardian|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206211950/https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2016/jul/11/blue-quartets-hostility-to-andrea-leadsom-reduces-her-to-tears|archivedate=6 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> with fellow Conservative MPs including [[Sarah Wollaston]] and [[Anna Soubry]] suggesting the remarks showed she lacked the judgement to be Prime Minister and calling upon her to withdraw.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.sky.com/story/leadsom-in-backlash-over-motherhood-remarks-10496432 |title=Leadsom In Backlash Over Motherhood Remarks |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160709173413/http://news.sky.com/story/leadsom-in-backlash-over-motherhood-remarks-10496432 |archivedate=9 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Alan Duncan]] described her remarks as \"vile\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cowburn|first1=Ashley|title=Andrea Leadsom attacked by Tory MPs over 'vile' and 'insulting' comments on Theresa May's childlessness|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-theresa-may-vile-insulting-children-conservative-leadership-tory-a7128311.html|accessdate=11 July 2016|work=The Independent|date=10 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710134640/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-theresa-may-vile-insulting-children-conservative-leadership-tory-a7128311.html|archivedate=10 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Tim Loughton]], Leadsom's campaign manager for the leadership contest, said that the establishment were ganging up on her.\n\n==== Comments about men and childcare ====\nIn an interview with ''The Times'', Andrea Leadsom suggested men should not be hired to look after young children as they might be paedophiles.<ref name=\"StandardJuly15\">{{cite news|url= https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/andrea-leadsom-suggests-men-should-not-be-nannies-because-they-may-be-paedophiles-a3296421.html/|title= Andrea Leadsom suggests men should not be nannies because they may be paedophiles|work= The Evening Standard|date= 15 July 2016|accessdate= 6 October 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20161010125038/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/andrea-leadsom-suggests-men-should-not-be-nannies-because-they-may-be-paedophiles-a3296421.html|archivedate= 10 October 2016|df= dmy-all}}</ref> In the interview she said: \"As an employer we\u2019re not, let\u2019s face it, most of us don\u2019t employ men as nannies, most of us don\u2019t ... Now you can call that sexist, I call that cautious and very sensible when you look at the stats. Your odds are stacked against you if you employ a man. .. We know paedophiles are attracted to working with children. I\u2019m sorry but they\u2019re the facts.\".<ref name=\"IndieJuly15\">{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-men-paedophiles-childcare-workers-hired-sensible-a7139351.html/|title= Andrea Leadsom says men should not be hired to do childcare as they may be paedophiles|work= The Independent|date= 15 July 2016|accessdate= 6 October 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20161018103712/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-men-paedophiles-childcare-workers-hired-sensible-a7139351.html|archivedate= 18 October 2016|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Questions over financial affairs====\nShe promised to publish her tax returns<ref>{{cite web|last1=May|first1=Josh|title=Andrea Leadsom, Theresa May and Michael Gove offer to publish tax returns|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/conservative-party/news/76879/andrea-leadsom-theresa-may-and-michael-gove|website=Politics Home|accessdate=10 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914065407/https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/conservative-party/news/76879/andrea-leadsom-theresa-may-and-michael-gove|archivedate=14 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> when she made it to the final ballot of the leadership election. Three days later she published \"one year of tax information after rival Theresa May released four years\u2019 worth of tax returns\". Richard Murphy, director of Tax Research UK, a tax campaign group, said \u201cThis isn\u2019t her tax return, it\u2019s a tax computation...It\u2019s a summary of numerical information but not an explanation of where it came from or what tax is due. It excludes all the information that might be of interest, so she has not published her tax return.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davies|first1=Rob|title=Andrea Leadsom discloses tax details and 2015 income of \u00a385,000|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/10/andrea-leadsom-tax-returns-reveals-85000-income-in-2015|accessdate=10 July 2016|work=The Guardian|date=10 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710143029/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/10/andrea-leadsom-tax-returns-reveals-85000-income-in-2015|archivedate=10 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====\"Black ops\" allegation====\nFormer conservative leader [[Iain Duncan Smith]] alleged that the intensity and nature of the sniping at Andrea Leadsom revealed ulterior motives, unconnected to her fitness for the post, saying to journalist [[Robert Peston]] that they indicated \"a kind of real 'black-ops' operation to denigrate her reputation\", writing later it constituted a \"concerted and brutal attempt to destroy her character\".<ref name=\"IDS\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36757909| title=Iain Duncan Smith claims 'black ops' bid to 'denigrate' Leadsom| work=BBC news| date=10 July 2016| accessdate=10 July 2016|url-status = live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710101844/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36757909| archivedate=10 July 2016| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/11/uniting-the-conservative-party-will-be-impossible-without-a-real/|title= Uniting the Conservative Party will be impossible without a real plan for Brexit|date= 12 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160712131449/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/11/uniting-the-conservative-party-will-be-impossible-without-a-real/|archivedate= 12 July 2016|df= dmy-all}}</ref> [[Allison Pearson]] in ''[[The Sunday Telegraph]]'' wrote, \"I have no doubt whatsoever that Leadsom became the target of a brutal and sustained character assassination.\"<ref name=\"STelJuly10\">{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/10/ive-been-under-attack-its-been-shattering-andrea-leadsom-apologi/|title= 'I've been under attack, it's been shattering': Andrea Leadsom apologises to Theresa May over motherhood comments and admits furore has left her hurt|work= The Daily Telegraph|date= 10 July 2016|accessdate= 10 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160710221154/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/10/ive-been-under-attack-its-been-shattering-andrea-leadsom-apologi/|archivedate= 10 July 2016|df= dmy-all}}</ref> The next day she wrote, \"Andrea Leadsom has nothing to be ashamed of: her conscience is clear. Those who sought to destroy her should examine theirs, if they can find it.\"<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/11/how-the-skulduggers-succeeded-in-bringing-an-end-to-andrea-leads/|title= How the skulduggers succeeded in bringing an end to Andrea Leadsom's campaign to be prime minister|work= The Daily Telegraph|date= 11 July 2016|accessdate= 11 July 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160711204437/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/11/how-the-skulduggers-succeeded-in-bringing-an-end-to-andrea-leads/|archivedate= 11 July 2016|df= dmy-all}}</ref> [[Norman Tebbit]] described the efforts to remove her candidature as an intense smear campaign, saying that he suspected they may have arisen from her opposition to gay marriage as much as her Euroscepticism.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/12/theresa-may-will-drive-tory-members-into-the-arms-of-ukip/ |title= Theresa May will drive Tory members into the arms of Ukip |work= The Daily Telegraph |url-status = live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160712063043/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/12/theresa-may-will-drive-tory-members-into-the-arms-of-ukip/ |archivedate= 12 July 2016 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== Withdrawal from the leadership contest ====\nOn 11 July 2016 Leadsom withdrew from the Conservative leadership election, stating that she did not have enough support for her cause, with only a quarter of the votes from the parliamentary party.<ref name=\"bbc36763208\" /> The previous day ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' had reported a rumour that up to 20 Tory MPs would quit the party if Leadsom won the leadership contest; this was later supported by reports in other news media<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/leadsoms-enemies-stick-the-knife-in-g0psn6s73|title=Leadsom's enemies stick the knife in|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Merrick |first=Jane |date=11 July 2016 |title=If Andrea Leadsom had won, the Conservative Party would have become a basket case |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/11/if-andrea-leadsom-had-won-the-conservative-party-would-have-beco/ |work=The Telegraph |location=London |access-date=11 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711145150/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/11/if-andrea-leadsom-had-won-the-conservative-party-would-have-beco/ |archivedate=11 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> but \"denied by MPs\" according to ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Asthana |first=Anushka |date=11 July 2016 |title=Andrea Leadsom pulls out of Conservative leadership race |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/11/conservative-leadership-andrea-leadsom-pulls-out-of-race |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=12 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170625061303/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/11/conservative-leadership-andrea-leadsom-pulls-out-of-race |archivedate=25 June 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn her statement Leadsom said: \"the interests of our country are best served by the immediate appointment of a strong and well-supported prime minister. I am therefore withdrawing from the leadership election, and I wish Mrs May the very greatest success.\" Her campaign manager, MP Tim Loughton spoke about an \"onslaught of often very personal attacks from colleagues and journalists\" as well as  \"underhand tactics against decent people\".<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |last=Booth |first=Robert |date=11 July 2016 |title=How it all went wrong for Andrea Leadsom's leadership bid |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/11/how-it-all-went-wrong-for-andrea-leadsoms-leadership-bid |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=12 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160712031052/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/11/how-it-all-went-wrong-for-andrea-leadsoms-leadership-bid |archivedate=12 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Leadsom had been under pressure from the news media, with reports criticising her exaggeration of business and management experience<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\" /><ref name=\"thetimes.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/leadsom-admits-misleading-claims-on-cv-for-top-job-n80lgc2rj|title=Leadsom admits 'misleading' claims on CV for top job|work=The Times|date= 6 July 2016}}</ref> and her suggestion that motherhood strengthened her candidacy for Prime Minister.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-accused-of-misleading-claims-on-her-cv-a7122296.html|title=Andrea Leadsom accused of 'misleading' claims on her CV|date=6 July 2016|publisher=|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170703030149/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-accused-of-misleading-claims-on-her-cv-a7122296.html|archivedate=3 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"thetimes.co.uk\" /><ref name=\"Sparrow\">{{cite news |last=Sparrow |first=Andrew |date= |title=Leadsom attacks 'gutter journalism' in row over motherhood quotes |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/08/andrea-leadsom-suggests-she-would-make-better-pm-as-she-has-children |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=8 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160708231608/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/08/andrea-leadsom-suggests-she-would-make-better-pm-as-she-has-children |archivedate=8 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Leadsom charged ''[[The Times]]'' with \"gutter journalism\" in response to the article about the motherhood issue.<ref>{{cite news |last=Coates |first=Sam |date=9 July 2016 |title=Being a mother gives me edge on May \u2014 Leadsom |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/being-a-mother-gives-me-edge-on-may-leadsom-0t7bbm29x |work=The Times |location=London |access-date=11 July 2016}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Sparrow |first=Andrew |date=8 July 2016 |title=Leadsom attacks 'gutter journalism' in row over motherhood quotes |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/08/andrea-leadsom-suggests-she-would-make-better-pm-as-she-has-children |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=11 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711113434/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/08/andrea-leadsom-suggests-she-would-make-better-pm-as-she-has-children |archivedate=11 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> ''[[The Times]]'' subsequently released the audio tapes of the interview to confirm Leadsom's statement. Although she subsequently apologised \"for any hurt I have caused\" to [[Theresa May]], she also related that she had felt \"under attack, under enormous pressure \u2026 It has been shattering.\"<ref name=\"auto1\" />\n\nHer resignation statement did not touch on either controversy or her personal feelings. Instead, she thanked the 84 MPs who had supported her, conceding that \"this is less than 25% of the parliamentary party and ... I do not believe this is sufficient support to win a strong and stable government should I win the leadership election\".<ref name=\"Bulman\" /> After her appointment as a Cabinet minister, other comments that Leadsom had made during the leadership race came to light and also led to criticism. During the 6 July 2016 interview with ''[[The Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/leadsom-male-carers-might-be-paedophiles-btxfs8hx7|title=Leadsom: male carers might be paedophiles|work=The Times}}</ref> she had stated that men were more likely to be paedophiles than women and hence, were not suitable to be hired for jobs in daycare.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stone |first=Jon |date=15 July 2016 |title=Andrea Leadsom says men should not be hired to do childcare as they may be paedophiles |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-men-paedophiles-childcare-workers-hired-sensible-a7139351.html |work=The Independent |location=London |access-date=17 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716125823/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-men-paedophiles-childcare-workers-hired-sensible-a7139351.html |archivedate=16 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Several MPs in opposition parties called for May to dismiss Leadsom from the Cabinet but the prime minister declined to do so.<ref name=\"standard1\">{{cite web |author=Mark Chandler |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/theresa-may-under-pressure-to-sack-andrea-leadsom-over-stupid-paedophile-comments-a3297091.html |title=Theresa May 'should sack' Andrea Leadsom over 'stupid' paedophile comments |work=London Evening Standard |date=14 July 2016 |accessdate=18 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160718011320/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/theresa-may-under-pressure-to-sack-andrea-leadsom-over-stupid-paedophile-comments-a3297091.html |archivedate=18 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs ===\nFollowing [[Theresa May]]'s cabinet shuffle on 14 July 2016 Leadsom moved from her role as Energy Minister to become [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]].<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Andrea Leadsom appointed environment secretary |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/live/2016/jul/14/theresa-may-cabinet-reshuffle-boris-johnson-philip-hammond-rules-out-emergency-budget |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=14 July 2016 |access-date=14 July 2016 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160714091607/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/live/2016/jul/14/theresa-may-cabinet-reshuffle-boris-johnson-philip-hammond-rules-out-emergency-budget |archivedate=14 July 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n<br />In April 2017, following the announcement of the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|general election]] in June, Leadsom was instructed to delay a report of illegally high levels of diesel pollution affecting over half the population until after the election. Constitutional experts Dr Jo Murkens and Colin Talbot agreed it was a health issue and therefore not affected by the election and the government was instructed to appear in the high court to explain the delay.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/apr/25/government-delay-air-pollution-plan-due-to-election-dishonest|title=Tories 'on very dodgy ground' over delay of air pollution plan, say experts|author=Matthew Taylor|work=The Guardian|date=25 April 2017|accessdate=25 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170425162945/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/apr/25/government-delay-air-pollution-plan-due-to-election-dishonest|archivedate=25 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Criticism of broadcasters====\nOn the anniversary of the Brexit vote, Leadsom was invited to discuss progress on ''[[Newsnight]]'' and claimed that the government had made \"a good start.\" While being interviewed by [[Emily Maitlis]], Leadsom suggested broadcasters should be \"a little more patriotic.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-40386788/brexit-tory-mp-leadsom-says-broadcasters-should-be-patriotic|title=Brexit: Tory MP Leadsom says broadcasters should be patriotic|work=BBC news|date=23 June 2017|accessdate=25 June 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170625000621/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-40386788/brexit-tory-mp-leadsom-says-broadcasters-should-be-patriotic|archivedate=25 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Tim Farron]] described her remarks as \"a sinister threat to the free media,\" a comment echoed by [[Hugo Rifkind]] in ''The Times'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/past-six-days/2017-07-04/comment/we-must-resist-every-assault-on-the-free-press-mltktxjbt|title=We must resist every assault on the free press|author=Hugo Rifkind|work=The Times|date=4 July 2017|accessdate=5 July 2017|url-access=subscription }}</ref> whilst ''[[Peston on Sunday]]'' mockingly displayed his patriotism by decorating the studio with [[Union Jacks]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Marsh|first=Sarah|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jun/25/peston-on-sunday-gives-leadsoms-call-for-patriotism-a-droll-reply|title=Peston on Sunday gives Leadsom's call for patriotism a droll reply|work=The Guardian|date=25 June 2017|accessdate=26 June 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170625123045/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jun/25/peston-on-sunday-gives-leadsoms-call-for-patriotism-a-droll-reply|archivedate=25 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Lord President of the Council and Leader of the House of Commons ===\n[[File:Official portrait of Andrea Leadsom.jpg|left|thumb|241x241px|Leadsom's official parliamentary portrait after being re-elected as the MP for South Northamptonshire]]\nOn 11 June 2017, Leadsom was appointed [[Lord President of the Council]] and [[Leader of the House of Commons]]. In this capacity, in July 2017, while attempting to eulogise [[Jane Austen]], who was about to feature on the new \u00a310 note scheduled to go into circulation in September, Leadsom told the House of Commons: \"I would just add one other great lady to that lovely list, who I am delighted to join in celebrating, and that's that of Jane Austen, who will feature on the new \u00a310 note, which I think is one of our greatest living authors.\" Amid laughs from both benches, she corrected herself, adding: \"Greatest ever authors, and I think it's fantastic that at last we are starting to recognize \u2013 well I think many of us probably wish she were still living \u2013 but I absolutely share the sentiment.\"<ref name=\"Austen\">{{cite news|work=Leader of Commons refers to face of new \u00a310 note as one of Britain's greatest living authors, causing much mirth among MPs|date= 20 July 2017|title=Unreliable narrator? Andrea Leadsom mistakenly resurrects Jane Austen |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/jul/20/andrea-leadsom-jane-austen-britain-greatest-living-author}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 January 2019, Leadsom was criticised in the House of Commons by the Speaker of the House, [[John Bercow]] for the failure of the government to advance the cause of [[proxy voting]] for expectant mothers. The issue came to a head due to the imminent caesarean section delivery by [[Tulip Siddiq]] at the time of the rescheduled [[meaningful vote]] on 15 January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|date=14 January 2019|title=John Bercow says it is 'lamentable' that Labour MP forced to postpone birth over crucial Brexit vote|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/101109/john-bercow-says-it-%E2%80%98lamentable%E2%80%99-labour-mp-forced}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January 2019, Leadsom said the House of Commons' February [[Recess (parliamentary procedure)|recess]] from 15 to 24 February would be cancelled to free up time to pass the necessary [[Withdrawal Agreement and Implementation Bill|Brexit-related legislation]]. Earlier in the day, her cabinet colleague Jeremy Hunt raised the possibility of Brexit being delayed with a technical extension to Article 50. The Times newspaper reported that senior Government ministers fear that it is already too late to meet the Brexit deadline of 29 March, and that Conservative MPs have been told that a one-line whip is expected to be imposed on votes in the Commons during the week of 18\u201322 February.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/mps-lose-ten-day-break-in-scramble-to-pass-brexit-bill-mdbp0lvqc|title=MPs lose ten-day break in scramble to pass Brexit bill|first=Matt Chorley|last=Red&nbsp;Box&nbsp;Editor|date=31 January 2019|accessdate=23 May 2019|via=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nLeadsom resigned as Leader of the House of Commons on 22 May, the eve of the [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|European elections]], as a result of Theresa May's most recent Brexit proposals, including the offer of votes in the House of Commons on a customs union and a second referendum.\n\n=== Conservative leadership election, 2019 ===\n{{main|2019 Conservative Party leadership election}}\nOn 8 May 2019, Leadsom stated she was \"seriously considering\" a bid for the party leadership.<ref>{{cite news |work=The Independent |title=Tory leadership race: Andrea Leadsom says she is 'seriously considering' bid to succeed Theresa May |date=8 May 2019 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tory-leadership-race-andrea-leadsom-theresa-may-brexit-prime-minister-a8904176.html}}</ref>\nLeadsom officially announced her candidacy on 25 May, the same day that [[Matt Hancock]] and [[Dominic Raab]] also announced they were running. She was proposed and seconded by fellow MPs [[Chris Heaton-Harris]] and [[Heather Wheeler]]. Leadsom was eliminated from the contest in the first ballot, on 13 June 2019, and came overall in eighth place out of ten candidates.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Stewart|first=Heather|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jun/13/andrea-leadsom-and-esther-mcvey-out-of-race-to-be-tory-leader|title=Andrea Leadsom and Esther McVey out of race to be Tory leader|date=2019-06-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-29|last2=Walker|first2=Peter|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2019-06-13/andrea-leadsom-out-of-the-tory-leadership-race-but-matt-hancock-gets-through-to-next-round/|title=Andrea Leadsom out of the Tory leadership race but Matt Hancock gets through to next round|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/live-conservative-leadership-candidates-face-first-vote-in-race-for-number-10-11740891|title=LIVE: Leadsom, McVey and Harper eliminated in Tory leadership vote|website=Sky News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy ===\nOn 24 July 2019, Leadsom was appointed [[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy]] by incoming Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]].\n\nOn 19 October, she said she was subject to \"frightening abuse\" from anti-Brexit demonstrators whilst leaving the [[Palace of Westminster]]. [[Jacob Rees-Mogg]] and [[Michael Gove]] were also targeted as they left following a House of Commons sitting. Leadsom was given a [[police escort]] through crowds gathered for a [[People's Vote]] rally, who were protesting for a further public vote on Brexit.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/leadsom-gove-and-rees-mogg-targeted-brexit-protesters-9kttg6s9x|title=Andrea Leadsom, Michael Gove and Jacob Rees-Mogg targeted by Brexit protesters|last=Editor|first=Francis Elliott, Political|date=2019-10-19|work=The Times|access-date=2019-10-23|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nLeadsom retained her seat with an increased majority at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/politics/constituencies/E14000942|title=Northamptonshire South parliamentary constituency - Election 2019|access-date=2020-01-09|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nShe was sacked as Business Secretary in the [[2020 British cabinet reshuffle]] undertaken by Boris Johnson on 13 February 2020.\n\n==Political views==\nLeadsom said in 2016 that she was \"absolutely pro-choice\" on abortion, but was \"keeping an eye on scientific progress which makes foetuses viable earlier\". She is concerned about child development, and founded a charity which helps vulnerable mothers to bond with their babies.<ref name=\"apology\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/10/ive-been-under-attack-its-been-shattering-andrea-leadsom-apologi/|title='I've been under attack, it's been shattering': Andrea Leadsom apologises to Theresa May over motherhood comments and admits furore has left her hurt|work=The Daily Telegraph|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710221154/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/10/ive-been-under-attack-its-been-shattering-andrea-leadsom-apologi/|archivedate=10 July 2016|url-status = live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the [[2016 US Presidential election]] she supported [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] candidate [[Hillary Clinton]] against [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Donald Trump|Trump]]. When seeking the Premiership she said she \"absolutely would rule out giving [[Nigel Farage]] [of [[UKIP]]] a job\".<ref name=apology/>\n\nShe said that if she became Prime Minister she would reform the ban on [[fox hunting]] to ensure greater protections for [[animal welfare]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-fox-hunting-animal-welfare-ban-hunting-act-poll-a7127276.html|title=Andrea Leadsom says she'll bring back fox hunting to improve animal welfare|date=8 July 2016|work=The Independent|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170711014302/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andrea-leadsom-fox-hunting-animal-welfare-ban-hunting-act-poll-a7127276.html|archivedate=11 July 2017|url-status = live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Prior to the 2017 election, Leadsom advised Theresa May not to repeat her promise to allow parliamentary time to discuss repealing the hunting ban, but was overruled.<ref name=\"auto2\" />\n\n===Environment===\nBefore becoming Minister at the Department of Energy and Climate Change, Leadsom had opposed wind farms and EU renewable energy targets. After her appointment she said \"When I first came to this job one of my two questions was: 'Is [[climate change]] real?' and the other was 'Is [[hydraulic fracturing]] [\"fracking\"] safe?' And on both of those questions I am now completely persuaded.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/energy-minister-andrea-leadsom-asked-whether-climate-change-was-real-when-she-started-the-job-a6710971.html|title=New energy minister Andrea Leadsom asked whether climate change was real when she started the job|author=Doug Bolton|date=27 October 2015|work=The Independent|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160904052736/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/energy-minister-andrea-leadsom-asked-whether-climate-change-was-real-when-she-started-the-job-a6710971.html|archivedate=4 September 2016|url-status = live|accessdate=8 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAs Minister, Leadsom launched the consultation to ban microbeads. Leadsom was personally opposed to microbeads, stating \"Most people would be dismayed to know the face scrub or toothpaste they use was causing irreversible damage to the environment, with billions of indigestible plastic pieces poisoning sea creatures. Adding plastic to products like face washes and body scrubs is wholly unnecessary when harmless alternatives can be used.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-37263087|title=Plastic microbeads to be banned by 2017|date=3 September 2016|via=www.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn her role as Secretary of State for the Department for Energy, Food and Rural Affairs, Leadsom stated she was \u201cpersonally deeply committed to the importance of ensuring clean air\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/apr/25/government-delay-air-pollution-plan-due-to-election-dishonest|title=Tories 'on very dodgy ground' over delay of air pollution plan, say experts|last=Taylor|first=Matthew|date=25 April 2017|via=www.theguardian.com|accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nPrior to 2017 election Leadsom advised Theresa May not to repeat her promise to allow parliamentary time to discuss repealing the hunting ban, but was overruled.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n===European Union===\nIn April 2013 at the [[Hansard Society]]'s annual parliamentary affairs lecture, Leadsom warned against the UK leaving the European Union, stating that \"I think it would be a disaster for our economy and it would lead to a decade of economic and political uncertainty at a time when the tectonic plates of global success are moving.\"<ref name=\"Independenta7116686\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tory-conservative-leadership-andrea-leadsom-brexit-latest-eu-referendum-disaster-next-leader-a7116686.html|title=Tory leadership contender Andrea Leadsom said leaving EU would be 'disaster' \u2013 then campaigned for Brexit|last=Cowburn|first=Ashley|date=3 July 2016|work=The Independent|accessdate=5 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160704132517/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tory-conservative-leadership-andrea-leadsom-brexit-latest-eu-referendum-disaster-next-leader-a7116686.html|archivedate=4 July 2016|url-status = live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/5ec81170-4101-11e6-b22f-79eb4891c97d.html|title=Andrea Leadsom seeks to play down pro-EU comments|date=3 July 2016|work=Financial Times|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707023059/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/5ec81170-4101-11e6-b22f-79eb4891c97d.html|archivedate=7 July 2016|url-status = live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHowever, in 2016 Leadsom campaigned for leave in the UK referendum on European Union membership. ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]'' reproduced her earlier comments in its issue of 3 July 2016.<ref name=\"Independenta7116686\"/> After her comments were read out by [[Andrew Marr]] on his Sunday morning BBC programme, she explained to Marr how she reached her more recent position: \"It has been a journey. When I came into Parliament, like most people in the country I'd grown up as part of the EU and it's absolutely part of our DNA and I came into Parliament, set up something called the Fresh Start Project, which took hundreds and hundreds of hours of evidence about how the EU impacts on the UK \u2013 on everything from immigration to fisheries and so on... During that process I travelled all across Europe with lots of parliamentary colleagues \u2013 up to 100 Conservative colleagues supporting this work \u2013 to try and get a really decent, fundamental reform of the EU.\"<ref name=\"Independenta7116686\"/> A spokesman for Leadsom said that the recording was \"taken completely out of context\" because she had opened the lecture by saying that the EU needed major reforms in order for it to be \"sustainable\". She added that the democratic consent for the EU in Britain was \"wafer thin\".<ref name=\"Independenta7116686\"/>\n\n==Charity support==\nLeadsom was a founder of the Northamptonshire Parent Infant Partnership, a charity providing therapeutic support to help parents bond with their babies who have [[Attachment theory|insecure attachment]], and also founded PIPUK, the national charity for Parent Infant Partnerships which set up branches in four further counties since its inception.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pipuk.org.uk/|title=Our Story \u2013 pipuk|publisher=|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160712150552/http://www.pipuk.org.uk/|archivedate=12 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.norpip.org.uk/About/Trustees.aspx|title=NORPIP:Board of trustees|work=NORPIP Northamptonshire Parent Infant partnership|accessdate=2 February 2014|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140220120422/http://www.norpip.org.uk/About/Trustees.aspx|archivedate=20 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2012/nov/27/andrea-leadsom-lobbying-parents-children|title=Andrea Leadsom: lobbying for more support for parents and children|first=Susanna|last=Rustin|date=27 November 2012|work=The Guardian|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826025026/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2012/nov/27/andrea-leadsom-lobbying-parents-children|archivedate=26 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> NORPIP was originally set up with funding from the Ana Leaf Foundation, of which Leadsom's sister Hayley, wife of [[Peter de Putron]], is a trustee.<ref>\nDavid Pegg and Holly Watt, [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/06/andrea-leadsom-political-links-peter-de-putron-tory-leadership How close are Andrea Leadsom's political links with Peter de Putron?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201230320/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/06/andrea-leadsom-political-links-peter-de-putron-tory-leadership |date=1 December 2016 }}, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 6 July 2016</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShe married business manager Ben Leadsom in 1993 and has two sons and one daughter.<ref name=ww /> Following the birth of her first child, she suffered from [[postnatal depression]] for several months.<ref name=\"lobby\">{{cite news|last1=Rustin|first1=Susanna|title=Andrea Leadsom: lobbying for more support for parents and children|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2012/nov/27/andrea-leadsom-lobbying-parents-children|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=The Guardian|date=27 November 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826025026/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2012/nov/27/andrea-leadsom-lobbying-parents-children|archivedate=26 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nLeadsom states that [[Christianity]] has a central role in her life. She told Tim Ross of ''The Daily Telegraph'': \"I am a very committed Christian. I think my values and everything I do is driven by that.\" She participates in \"various [[Bible study (Christianity)|Bible studies]] groups\" with other parliamentarians and prays \"all the time\"<ref name=telegraph-20160702 /> and has discussed her Christian faith openly in a video hosted on the website of the all party [[parliamentary group]] Christians in Parliament.<ref name=telegraph-20160702 /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.christiansinparliament.org.uk/members-stories/andrea-leadsom-mp/ |title=Andrea Leadsom MP \u2013 Members' Stories |publisher=Christians in Parliament |date= |accessdate=10 July 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625072234/http://www.christiansinparliament.org.uk/members-stories/andrea-leadsom-mp/ |archivedate=25 June 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/redbox/topic/tory-leadership-race/andrea-leadsom-became-mp-to-stop-nuclear-holocaust |title=Andrea Leadsom wanted to be MP to stop 'nuclear holocaust' |work=The Times |date= |accessdate=10 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{notelist}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.andrealeadsom.com/ Official website]\n* {{UK MP links\n| parliament   = andrea-leadsom/4117\n| hansard      =\n| hansardcurr  =\n| guardian     =\n| publicwhip   = Andrea_Leadsom\n| theywork     = 24829/andrea_leadsom/south_northamptonshire\n| record       =\n| bbc          = 40456.stm\n| journalisted =\n}}\n* [https://archive.is/20140410001824/http://www.debretts.com/people-of-today/profile/26866/Andrea-Jacqueline-LEADSOM Debrett's People of Today]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[South Northamptonshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Northamptonshire]]|years=[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Nicky Morgan]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Economic Secretary to the Treasury]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Harriett Baldwin]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sajid Javid]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[City Minister]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Matthew Hancock]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department of Energy and Climate Change|Minister of State for Energy]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lucy Neville-Rolfe]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Elizabeth Truss|Liz Truss]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]]|years=2016\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Michael Gove]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[David Lidington]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Leader of the House of Commons]]|years=2017\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Mel Stride]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lord President of the Council]]|years=2017\u20132019}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Greg Clark]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy]]|years=2019\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Alok Sharma]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Johnson Cabinet}}\n{{Leader of the House of Commons}}\n{{Secretary of State for Environment}}\n{{First May Cabinet}}\n{{Second May Cabinet}}\n{{2016 Conservative Party leadership election}}\n{{2019 Conservative Party leadership election}}\n{{East Midlands Conservative Party MPs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leadsom, Andrea}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Warwick]]\n[[Category:British Secretaries of State for the Environment]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Critics of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Economic Secretaries to the Treasury]]\n[[Category:English bankers]]\n[[Category:English Christians]]\n[[Category:People from Aylesbury]]\n[[Category:People from Buckinghamshire]]\n[[Category:People from Northamptonshire]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Northamptonshire]]\n[[Category:Lord Presidents of the Council]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Cabinet of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Headhitter", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Reordered cats", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrea_Leadsom"}
{"title_page": "James Glen", "text_new": "{{About||the Canadian parliamentarian|James Allison Glen|the Canadian flying ace|James Alpheus Glen}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = James Glen\n|image         =James Glen (politican).JPG\n|imagesize     =\n|caption       =\n|office        = 25th [[List of colonial governors of South Carolina|Governor of South Carolina]]\n|monarch = [[George II of Great Britain|George II]]\n|termstart     = December 17, 1743\n|termend       = June 1, 1756\n|nominator     =\n|appointer     =\n|predecessor   = [[William Bull (governor)|William Bull]]\n|successor     = [[William Lyttelton, 1st Baron Lyttelton|William Henry Lyttelton]]\n|birth_date  = 1701\n|birth_place =\n|death_date  = {{Death date|mf=yes|1777|7|18}}\n|death_place = [[London]], [[England]], UK}}\n\n'''James Glen''' (1701 \u2013 July 18, 1777) was a politician in the [[Province of South Carolina]]. He was appointed Royal Governor of South Carolina in 1738, but did not arrive in the province until December 17, 1743. He served as governor until June 1, 1756 and was succeeded by [[William Lyttelton, 1st Baron Lyttelton|William Henry Lyttelton]]. On June 21, 1761, Glen returned to Europe and died in London. He is buried in [[Linlithgow]], Scotland.\n\nGovernor Glen was noted for forging a 1755 treaty with the [[Cherokee]], known as the Treaty of Saluda Old Town, in present-day [[Saluda County, South Carolina|Saluda County]] and the building of Fort Prince George near [[Keowee River]]. He was also responsible for promoting an official policy that aimed to create in Indians an \"aversion\" to African Americans in an attempt to thwart possible alliances between them.<ref name=\"PatrickMinges\">{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X9W31OHDxQYC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_atb#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Slavery in the Cherokee Nation: the Keetoowah Society and the defining of a people, 1855-1867|page=27|author=[[Patrick Minges]]|publisher=Psychology Press|year=2003|isbn=978-0-415-94586-8}}</ref><ref name=\"KimberleyTolley\">{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eoQ-aRXS4WwC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Transformations in Schooling: Historical and Comparative Perspectives|page=228|author=Kimberley Tolley|publisher=Macmillan|year=2007|isbn=978-1-4039-7404-4}}</ref>\n\n== Governorship ==\nJames Glen has the longest term of governorship of any of those of colonial South Carolina.  His term was noted for extensive dealings with Native American tribes on the colony's western and southern borders.\n\n=== Controversy over Salary ===\nTraditionally the governor of South Carolina played the role of defender of the southern frontier but with the creation of Georgia that role passed to the Georgian governor [[James Oglethorpe]]. This transfer of roles was accompanied by the transfer of a thousand pounds that no longer went to the governor of South Carolina but now went to his Georgian counterpart. James Glen stayed in England to protest this change and [[William Bull (governor)|William Bull]] acted as governor in his stead.\n\n=== King George's War ===\nDuring [[King George's War]], Governor Glen sent a trade delegation led by notable Indian trader and historian [[James Adair (historian)|James Adair]] to win over [[Red Shoes (Choctaw chief)]] to abandon their alliance with the French and to side with the British.  The efforts led to a great civil war amongst the [[Choctaw Nation]].  Adair blames the resulting failure on the Glen for not supporting this mission.<ref>''History of the American Indians'' by [[James Adair (historian)|James Adair]], pg 143-148.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of colonial governors of South Carolina]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*[http://library.sc.edu/socar/mnscrpts/glenj.html ''The James Glen Papers'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Glen, James}}\n[[Category:Scottish people of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:1701 births]]\n[[Category:1777 deaths]]\n[[Category:Colonial governors of South Carolina]]\n\n\n{{SouthCarolina-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About||the Canadian parliamentarian|James Allison Glen|the Canadian flying ace|James Alpheus Glen}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = James Glen\n|image         =James Glen (politican).JPG\n|imagesize     =\n|caption       =\n|office        = 25th [[List of colonial governors of South Carolina|Governor of South Carolina]]\n|monarch = [[George II]]\n|termstart     = December 17, 1743\n|termend       = June 1, 1756\n|nominator     =\n|appointer     =\n|predecessor   = [[William Bull (governor)|William Bull]]\n|successor     = [[William Lyttelton, 1st Baron Lyttelton|William Henry Lyttelton]]\n|birth_date  = 1701\n|birth_place =\n|death_date  = {{Death date|mf=yes|1777|7|18}}\n|death_place = [[London]], [[England]], UK}}\n\n'''James Glen''' (1701 \u2013 July 18, 1777) was a politician in the [[Province of South Carolina]]. He was appointed Royal Governor of South Carolina in 1738, but did not arrive in the province until December 17, 1743. He served as governor until June 1, 1756 and was succeeded by [[William Lyttelton, 1st Baron Lyttelton|William Henry Lyttelton]]. On June 21, 1761, Glen returned to Europe and died in London. He is buried in [[Linlithgow]], Scotland.\n\nGovernor Glen was noted for forging a 1755 treaty with the [[Cherokee]], known as the Treaty of Saluda Old Town, in present-day [[Saluda County, South Carolina|Saluda County]] and the building of Fort Prince George near [[Keowee River]]. He was also responsible for promoting an official policy that aimed to create in Indians an \"aversion\" to African Americans in an attempt to thwart possible alliances between them.<ref name=\"PatrickMinges\">{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X9W31OHDxQYC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_atb#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Slavery in the Cherokee Nation: the Keetoowah Society and the defining of a people, 1855-1867|page=27|author=[[Patrick Minges]]|publisher=Psychology Press|year=2003|isbn=978-0-415-94586-8}}</ref><ref name=\"KimberleyTolley\">{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eoQ-aRXS4WwC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Transformations in Schooling: Historical and Comparative Perspectives|page=228|author=Kimberley Tolley|publisher=Macmillan|year=2007|isbn=978-1-4039-7404-4}}</ref>\n\n== Governorship ==\nJames Glen has the longest term of governorship of any of those of colonial South Carolina.  His term was noted for extensive dealings with Native American tribes on the colony's western and southern borders.\n\n=== Controversy over Salary ===\nTraditionally the governor of South Carolina played the role of defender of the southern frontier but with the creation of Georgia that role passed to the Georgian governor [[James Oglethorpe]]. This transfer of roles was accompanied by the transfer of a thousand pounds that no longer went to the governor of South Carolina but now went to his Georgian counterpart. James Glen stayed in England to protest this change and [[William Bull (governor)|William Bull]] acted as governor in his stead.\n\n=== King George's War ===\nDuring [[King George's War]], Governor Glen sent a trade delegation led by notable Indian trader and historian [[James Adair (historian)|James Adair]] to win over [[Red Shoes (Choctaw chief)]] to abandon their alliance with the French and to side with the British.  The efforts led to a great civil war amongst the [[Choctaw Nation]].  Adair blames the resulting failure on the Glen for not supporting this mission.<ref>''History of the American Indians'' by [[James Adair (historian)|James Adair]], pg 143-148.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of colonial governors of South Carolina]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*[http://library.sc.edu/socar/mnscrpts/glenj.html ''The James Glen Papers'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Glen, James}}\n[[Category:Scottish people of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:1701 births]]\n[[Category:1777 deaths]]\n[[Category:Colonial governors of South Carolina]]\n\n\n{{SouthCarolina-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "R'n'B", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGeorge II(link changed toGeorge II of Great Britain) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Glen"}
